<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-139  ERGONOMIC OFFICE EQUIPMENT, FURNITURE
AND SUPPLIES: GROWTH MARKETS FOR THE 1990s
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-139  ERGONOMIC OFFICE EQUIPMENT, FURNITURE
AND SUPPLIES: GROWTH MARKETS FOR THE 1990s
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>JOSEPH CASTROVILLA</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Coupled with a concern for employee health, employer liability
issues have heightened the interest in ergonomics and the
possible market implications of ergonomic products.
Ergonomics combines product engineering, psychology, and
medicine to improve human performance and health.<P>

This BCC report analyzes the growing ergonomic office
equipment products market, and describes the technology and
performance criteria for ergonomic or adjustable office
equipment, furniture and computer accessories. It views future
trends that meet the health, safety, and productivity
requirements of the office computing environment.<P>

Legislation both past and pending requires that adjustments be
made available to people who use video display terminals and
keyboards  intensively for more than four hours a day.<P>

Until recently, advanced ergonomic systems have been kept from
wider implementation by their higher cost, limited supply, and
lack of standards and testing. However, the growing demands
for adjustable usage and ever smaller systems are breaking
down these barriers.<P>

Significant technological advancements are taking place today,
despite the current economic recession. Ergonomic office
equipment and accessories represent the cutting edge of
product design with great potential for business opportunity.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report presents a detailed analysis of current and future
developments in ergonomics and ergonomic office equipment for
safety and productivity. The design of today's office
equipment has become a major factor in the design and
manufacture of the total system.  Market forecasts are
revealed by individual product segments from 1992 through
1997. Case studies of technology applications, as well as
market size, growth and usage trends through 1997, are
featured.<P>

Additionally, leading suppliers are profiled. This unique
strategic planning tool  shows suppliers to the industry the
paths to business opportunity, while end-users will benefit
from knowing about the new products, processes and their
suppliers.<P>

This report is directed to the following decision-makers who
need strategic planning data on ergonomic office products and
devices, together with information on the manufacturers,
industry and markets. They are:<P>

<UL>
<LI>electronic office equipment suppliers<BR>
<LI>manufacturers of personal computers, and peripherals--keyboards,  mouses, monitors<BR>
<LI>manufacturers of office equipment and furniture--desks,
   tables, chairs and printers<BR>
<LI>manufacturers of computer and furniture accessories:
   keyboard storage drawers; wrist rests; back support lumbar
   rolls; footrests; workstation retrofits; tiltable screen
   arms; antiglare hoods; and other products<BR>
<LI>companies that use computers and workstations<BR>
<LI>rehabilitation and physical therapy professionals
<LI>insurance companies<BR>
<LI>information industry companies -- publishing, advertising,
   etc.<BR>
<LI>government  agencies, OSHA, state agencies<BR>
<LI>electronic and electrical equipment manufacturers<BR>
<LI>merger and acquisition and investment executives</UL><P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This BCC report, which first analyzes the trends in office
illness and the implications for workers' compensation claims
as a driving force for ergonomic products, recognizes the
irrefutable logic for preventing office injuries and improved
evidence of the need for ergonomic furniture. The report then
analyzes trends in office furniture, computer accessories and
new computer keyboard design by type and relationship to
industry sectors. Production trends are highlighted with
market forecasts through 1997.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Research was conducted by way of discussions and in-depth
interviews with a representative sample of vendors, end-users,
and trade associations. All dollar projections in this report
are in 1992 constant dollars.<P>

Data are based on a thorough review and appraisal of ergonomic
technology and products based on a systematic review of
developments through telephone and in-person interviews,
together with an extensive data base of technical and
marketing sources.<P>

Additional data for this document were obtained from an
exhaustive review of technical papers.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC RESEARCH CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Since 1971, BCC has been a leader in market research and
consulting to the electronics, computing and
telecommunications industries. BCC continues its in-depth
analysis with the current volume.<P>


