<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>

G-142: ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING IN THE 1990S:

THE EVOLUTION BEYOND THE PRINTED PAGE

</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY>

<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">

<CENTER><H2>G-142: ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING IN THE 1990S:

THE EVOLUTION BEYOND THE PRINTED PAGE

</H2>



<HR><P>



<I>Christiane Toenne

</I><BR>

PROJECT ANALYST

<P>



<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>

</CENTER>



<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>



The Clinton Administration has committed itself to building a national 

information infrastructure in the U.S., popularly referred to as the 

"Information Highway." Today, information can be the basis of building large 

fortunes, much as land was a century ago in the American West. Information of 

any kind can race along electronic "superhighways" at the speed of light. In 

the process, barriers are broken down that once segmented huge economic 

empires: computer companies and phone companies, cable systems, movie studios 

and media and information oriented conglomerates.<P> 



All these efforts will, in the near future, make information of any kind 

easily available for individual consumers as well as large companies. The 

printed paper page, long the carrier not only of information but also of 

cultural value, is rapidly being replaced by electronic "blips" that appear on 

our computer screens. And this affects the printing and publishing industry as 

well as our sense of cultural values. Electronic information, while providing 

vastly improved access to published matter, does not have the "permanent" 

qualities of a printed publication. It requires new skills to access, thus 

restricting large shares to information specialists, creating new classes of 

society.<P> 



Another question that is starting to worry many inside and outside the 

industry is how this huge flow of data will be controlled, regulated and 

secured. If anybody can access it, then the real danger exists that anybody 

can also tamper with it, potentially bringing the whole system to a crashing 

halt, with unforeseeable effects on the U.S. or even world economy.<P> 



This study examines the structure of the electronic information service 

industry to the extent that it has replaced or is replacing the printed word. 

It addresses questions such as "What is the future of electronic publishing?" 

and "Who will benefit most: users -publishers - service providers - hardware 

suppliers or software developers?"<P> 





<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>





Over the past decade, computers have become an indispensable tool, in the 

business world as well as at home, for the professional as well as the casual 

user. By some estimates there are now some 40 million personal computers in 

use worldwide. With it went an explosion of new applications and uses, which a 

few years ago might have been considered "science fiction." One of the early 

promises of computer applications in the business was to create the "paperless 

office." These efforts are receiving additional attention, in the U.S. as well 

as worldwide, because the production of printing and writing paper uses wood, 

a natural resource that is becoming more and more sparse, and the paper 

manufacturing process can pose significant environmental threats.<P> 



Although few businesses or individuals are as yet ready to replace all printed 

communications with electronics, significant progress is being made towards 

that goal. Today, electronic databases can provide information in a few 

seconds or minutes that would have otherwise taken hours or days to locate. 

Furthermore, electronic information can be directly stored on magnetic media, 

and thus be easily accessible for anyone using a computer. The range of 

applications is enormous: from CD-ROM library catalogs to on-line 

communications via bulletin boards, from on-line commercial databases offering 

a vast array of downloadable information to electronically filed tax returns, 

from on-line shopping clubs to electronic books, the field appears to be 

limitless.<P> 





<b>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>





This study pulls together achievements in electronic communications 

technologies and efficiencies during the past decade. It analyzes the limits 

and opportunities of various kinds of technologies and access methods for the 

decade to come. Based on previous patterns, technology developments, and the 

opinions of many industry insiders, we then forecast potential use patterns 

for the nineties and beyond. This report summarizes and compares pertinent 

scenarios, using the most likely ones for our own forecasts.<P> 





<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>





This BCC report focuses on the aspect of electronic publishing, including 

books, magazines and newspapers, advertising, marketing, travel and real 

estate transactions, and the like. We examine the current, recent past, and 

foreseeable future developments of electronic publishing in the U.S.A., try to 

quantify its volume, and examine its qualitative impact on the way business is 

done today and people communicate via electronic means. Especially, we 

investigate currently used products and technologies facilitating electronic 

publishing, and attempt to forecast their likely development in various 

applications until the end of the decade. Lastly, we take international 

developments into account, comparing U.S. developments to the rest of the 

world, in order to show possible alternative developments, and how electronic 

publishing will make international communications easier than ever before.<P> 





<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>





In assembling this report, published data from various governmental and 

private sources were considered. Projections were established by BCC, taking 

into consideration projections made by published sources as well as industry 

consensus and external influences such as demographic and economic data and 

likely political developments.<P> 



Using these data, we have attempted to quantify, in as much detail as possible, the

current and future markets for electronic publications in their various subject categories.

For underlying market developments, we adopted to some extent market forecasts for

the telecommunications industry in general, published by trade associations such as the

National Telecommunications Association (NATA) and others.<P>





<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>





This study relies heavily on the input provided by experts in the field as well as on the vast scientific and popular literature that is available. The topic of electronic communications is being addressed by a variety of interested parties, ranging from major computer

hardware and software suppliers to major and minor telecommunications concerns as well as the television and entertainment industries. The one industry that is perhaps most concerned is the publishing industry, which is looking for ways to utilize this trend to electronic communications to their advantage.<P>



Lastly, there are a number of government and private entities concerned with the security and safety of electronically transmitted information, developing methods and products to achieve this end. We have attempted to incorporate the latest thinking on these subject matters and are grateful for the input

of all those contacted.<P>





<b>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>





