<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-144  FIBER-OPTIC TEST EQUIPMENT - A WORLDWIDE ANALYSIS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-144  FIBER-OPTIC TEST EQUIPMENT - A WORLDWIDE ANALYSIS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>RICHARD W BRYANT, Ph.D</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This new Business Communications Co. (BCC) report provides
a technical and economic market analysis of the fiber-optic
test equipment industry.<P>

The principal objectives of this study are to:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Investigate and discuss the instruments, technologies,
       and applications<P>

<LI>Characterize and quantify the current and future U.S.
       and worldwide markets for fiber-optic test equipment,
       including:<P>

<UL><LI>OTDRs--full-featured OTDRs, mini-OTDRs, and
              PC/laptop-
              based OTDRs<BR>
<LI>Power meters<BR>
<LI>Test sets<BR>
<LI>Remote/automatic test equipment<BR>
<LI>Fiber-optic manufacturing test equipment,
              such as optical spectrum analyzers, chromatic-
              dispersion analyzers, profilometers, etc.<BR>
<LI>Other instrumentation such as sources,
              attenuators, talk sets, fiber identifiers, etc.</UL><P>

<LI>Identify and characterize the principal industry
       participants<P>

<LI>Provide an overview and characterize the end-use
       markets for fiber-optic systems, including
       telecommunications (both short- and long-haul
       applications), cable television, other video and
       interactive video, information and data communications,
       etc., and to show how growth for these varied
       applications relates to the fiber-optic test equipment
       business<P>

<LI>Identify and discuss the pertinent institutional and
       legal issues<P>

<LI>Identify and characterize the principal government
       entities.</UL><P>

This study provides a very substantive overview of the
industries served by the fiber-optic test equipment industry
to explain why there will be significant growth in test
equipment over the next 5 years and beyond. In addition to the
in-depth market analysis of the test equipment industry, the
report presents a detailed overview of telecommunications,
cable TV, video, data communications, and other end-use
markets.<P>

This study does not cover process-control instrumentation,
sometimes used during fiber or cable manufacture.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR CONDUCTING THE STUDY</B><P>

Business Communications Co. (BCC) initiated this study of the
fiber-optic test equipment industry in response to numerous
inquiries regarding this market. The report, a natural follow-
on for a number of other optics, electro-optics, and fiber-optics reports which have been published by BCC over the last
few years, provides a thorough analysis of the U.S./North
American market, and, in addition, it is the only current
study that provides a worldwide market analysis and market
projections.  In addition, this report is a natural follow-up
for a number of other optics, electro-optics, and fiber-optics
reports published recently by BCC.<P>

The study is timely because of the many changes occurring in
the fiber-optics end-use industries, particularly in the
telecommunications and cable TV industries. There is
tremendous potential for expanding the use of fiber-optics and
fiber-optic test equipment.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study comes at a critical time in the development of new
fiber-optic test equipment and new fiber applications that
will demand different types of equipment, less expensive
equipment, remote/automatic test equipment, and new testing
requirements. This timely BCC study seeks to answer these
questions through discussion, and provide reasons for its
conclusions.<P>

To provide market projections for fiber-optic test equipment,
it is necessary to thoroughly analyze and characterize the
future markets for the many important new applications for
fiber, as well as expanded use for existing applications.
Thus, this report not only  provides a thorough market
analysis of the fiber-optic test equipment industry, it also
analyzes the major end-use markets for fiber systems as
follows:<P>

<UL><LI>It assesses relevant technologies<BR>
<LI>Provides market projections for 1991, 1992, and 1993
       through 1998, and in some cases through 2003<BR>
<LI>Characterizes existing and potential applications<BR>
<LI>Discusses the major driving forces behind the
       development of the industry<BR>
<LI>Identifies niches of specific promise<BR>
<LI>Discusses thorny institutional and legal issues<BR>
<LI>Provides a thorough list of companies and organizations
      involved in the test-equipment industry and major end-
      users<BR>
<LI>Provides brief company profiles</UL><P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The information presented in this study was derived, in part,
from more than 75 interviews with knowledgeable industry and
government sources. In view of the increasingly worldwide
nature and importance of the industry, both domestic and
foreign sources were contacted, and global information and
market data are included in this report. In all, more than 150
companies and organizations were surveyed. In addition, a
thorough search of technical, trade, and government literature
was conducted.<P>

The "Rest-of-the-World" (outside the U.S.) market information
was derived from contacts with foreign companies, both outside
and inside the U.S., foreign trade information, various
government data, other industry sources, and a BCC evaluation
and extrapolation of the hard data to those areas for which
data were scarce. BCC in-house resources were consulted and
utilized where appropriate.<P>

This study was conducted over a 2-month period ending in
February 1993. Dollar market projections are given in constant
1992 dollars unless otherwise noted.<P>

<B>ABOUT THE PROJECT DIRECTOR/AUTHOR</B><P>

Dr. Bryant is the director of the Optics/Electro-Optics
Div., and heads the Western Regional Div. of Business
Communications Co. (BCC), El Prado, NM. He has been
with the company since April 1985. During his tenure at BCC he
has written and published technical/economic analyses in the
areas of advanced materials, including special high-
performance metals and alloys; advanced composite materials
(polymers, metals, intermetallics, and ceramics); advanced
ceramics; inorganic coatings and finishes; engineered
surfaces; advanced optical-related studies, including element
and substrate materials; nonlinear optical materials; sensors
and detectors; optical thin-film coatings; advanced organic,
metallorganic, and biomolecular optical materials; technology
transfer; and, technologies for the Strategic Defense
Initiative.<P>

In addition, Dr. Bryant has conducted numerous
custom research studies for individual clients in the areas of
advanced structural and component materials (metal matrix
composites, intermetallics, ceramics, superalloys, aluminum,
titanium, and copper); and a number of studies investigating
specific advanced optical materials and electronic substrates.
In addition, he is the editor of the industry
newsletter, Optical Materials & Engineering News, and a
contributing editor of Industries in Transition. He has
published articles and papers in professional and trade
journals, including Journal of Metals; Science; Advanced
Materials & Processes;  Materials & Processing Report
(Elsevier/MIT), Laser Focus World, Sensors, and OE Reports
(SPIE).<P>

Dr. Bryant is a member of the American Society for Metals
(ASM International), the Institute of Electrical and
Electronics Engineers (IEEE), and the  Optical Society of
America (OSA).<P>


