<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-146  THE FUTURE OF LOCAL TELEPHONE COMPANIES IN THE U.S.
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-146  THE FUTURE OF LOCAL TELEPHONE COMPANIES IN THE U.S.
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS RUSH
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

There seem to be many avenues of investment open to local exchange
carriers (LECs), each with perhaps different issues, regulatory
concerns, and potential for revenue return.  Our goal in preparing
this report was to analyze the key markets in the U.S. that could
attract LEC investment, to predict their potential for success in
those strategic markets, and to size all opportunities.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

We have witnessed some LECs asking for relief from regulatory
prohibition to enter the long distance market.  We have seen LECs
buying cable television franchises.  Some LECs are announcing plans
to provide fiber to residential neighborhoods and offer interactive
television.  Some LECs have trumpeted in the press the idea of
personal communications networks and related wireless applications.<P>

With all these diverse interests and expressed key opportunities by
the local telephone operators we wished to review these many
opportunities to understand which would have more potential both
from an operating as well as from a gross revenue standpoint.  It
is our purpose to provide a document that both the LECs and other
related businesses can use to plan for the oncoming revolution in
the local telephone company.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE DOCUMENT AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report is intended to show how the local telephone business
may evolve into related communications technologies.  It offers a
complete profile on all regional Bell operating companies, and
acknowledges their role as leading the independents into the next
century.  It takes a realistic view at sizing the key opportunities
for all potential providers, and then discusses the potential for
LECs to capture some share of that market.  The LEC share is then
sized, based on stated assumptions.  A ten-year forecast period is
used.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

We cover the key local telephone companies' potential in the next
ten years with sizings, assumptions behind the sizings, and issues
related to the market for all contenders.  We cover the areas of
local network services, long distance, and wireless as they have
been defined by tariffs and regulatory agencies, and then cover in
some detail our assessment of the evolution of television in the
residence, noting key opportunities for LECs and sizing three forms
of television revenue: 1) subscription, 2) pay-per-view, and 3)
interactive television.  Our general format is to give both
background, present, and predicted future applications of the
technology, along with ten-year forecasts that are based on 1993
U.S. dollars.  The overall scope of this report is limited to U.S.
opportunities.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

All of our forecasts include sufficient assumptions to enable the
reader to disagree with an assumption and to recalculate the
forecast.  We use various methodologies in forecasting, carefully
recognizing past history, and forecasting each year into the
future, and only then do we calculate an average annual growth
rate, which is shown for all predictions.  Not all opportunities
sized in this report show a positive growth rate, as we are
cautious to understand how one new technology might replace an
older one.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Interviews, trade shows, press releases, FCC reporting, other
writers' views, and our own expertise went into the preparation of
this report.  BCC has extensive in-house expertise in the fields of
wireless, cable television, and local telephone company operations
that were all brought to bear in compiling the analyses and
predictions embodied in this report.<P>


<b>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Within the last two years BCC has prepared reports entitled,
"Telecommunications' Retail Opportunities," "Long Distance Markets,
2001," "Wireless Communications," "Video Communications into the
21st Century," and "Delivery Alternatives for Residential
Television."  This report is consistent with those previous
reports, and forecasts agree with each other, or we state what new
information has occurred to alter our outlook.  Our report on video
communications has been referenced in publications all over the
world as being a key contribution to the outlook for all forms of
video.<P>

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
