<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-147  DELIVERY ALTERNATIVES FOR RESIDENTIAL TELEVISION
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-147  DELIVERY ALTERNATIVES FOR RESIDENTIAL TELEVISION
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS RUCH</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

There has been considerable discussion concerning the technology, even the
form of the organization, that will be in prime position to carry subscription
television into the home of tomorrow.  This report delves into the technology,
the businesses, the organizations, and the issues surrounding the future for
Delivery Alternatives for Residential Television.  It deals only with the
subscription form of television.<P>

Subscription television can be delivered to the home via wires from the
telephone company, over-the-air via microwave radio, through-the-air from
satellites direct to the home antenna, and, traditionally, via cable from
cable system operators.  The preceding diagram seeks to illustrate these
alternatives.  This report answers the question, "Who wins the race for the
delivery of subscription TV to the residence?"<P>

There has been an enormous amount of activity recently associated with various
forms of delivering television to the home.  The media has been announcing a
new merger, technology, alliance,  trial, or service nearly daily for the last
six months. It is our goal to sort through all of these announcements and put
them in perspective of the total business.<P>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

There is significant change underway in all aspects of delivering television
to the home.  The world of fiber optics offers manifold increases in capacity
for wired systems.  New technologies and frequencies are changing the world of
microwave delivery.  New, more powerful satellites offer considerable
economies for receiving television in the home without the cost of laying any
wire.  The telephone companies have been allowed to offer "video dial tone,"
and are aggressively pushing to obtain approval to enter subscription
television businesses.  Meanwhile, the telcos are buying into existing cable
franchises outside the telco area of operation.<P>

Any one of these changes might suggest that the world of home delivery of
television will be altered significantly -- but together, they form a
different picture.  It is our intent in publishing this study to offer the
reader a platform for understanding the industry that can be used to assess
any of the announced or yet-to-be-announced changes.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

We cover all aspects of delivering video to the home, including the video
store rental or purchase.  We further develop scenarios based on past history,
experience, and sound business principles for the world of subscription
television ten years from now.  We avoid speculating on outside influences
such as court, legislative, or regulatory rulings or proceedings.  In this
context we offer reasoned forecasts that have all assumptions thoroughly
discussed.  These scenarios and forecasts are intended to be of assistance to
vendors of video equipment, providers of video programming, and suppliers of
video services as they assess their future business opportunities and plans,
recognizing a changing world of competition and technology.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report focuses on the subscription television business in the United
States.  All figures are based on 1993 U.S. dollars.  We address the
underlying technologies with discussions on general benefits, and then
incorporate these technological changes into the past, present, and future of
each of the categories of service for delivering television: subscription (for
a fee), pay-per-view, and interactive video.  There is a strong recognition of
the market forces that may accept or reject technological change.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

We take into account technological change, economic factors, history, market
acceptance factors, and competition in deriving our forecasts.  All
assumptions are discussed thoroughly so that the reader may alter any
assumption and derive a revised forecast.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC has compiled this report from research of available literature, interviews
of leading industry experts and vendor representatives, attendance at seminars
and tradeshows, and combined that input with the experience of the author, who
has been personally involved with the television delivery industry and all
aspects of video communications.<P>

<B>OTHER BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

This is the first BCC report on the specific subject of delivery of television
to the home, but several related reports have been published recently by BCC,
including: Report G-134, VSATs, in which the subject of satellites is
thoroughly addressed; Report G-109, ISDN, that assesses the many attributes of
digital transmission; Report G-136, Long Distance, covering the gamut of long
distance opportunities; and Report G-138, Video  Communications into the 21st
Century, that addresses all of the markets for various forms of video
communications.<P>

