<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-150: THE FUTURE FOR TELECOMMUNICATIONS/    
ELECTRONIC SUPERHIGHWAYS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-150: THE FUTURE FOR TELECOMMUNICATIONS/    
ELECTRONIC SUPERHIGHWAYS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Bertile Lindberg
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>


Electronic superhighways is the buzzword of the day. Everybody talks about it 
but few know anything about it. The objective of this study is to enlighten 
the readers about broadband data networks, their technology and markets. 
Future telecommunications networks are likely to be integrated, i.e., they 
will carry voice, data, pictures and video intermingled. Thus, the study 
covers these aspects as well.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P> 

The study is presented at this time because of the rapid developments in 
broadband telecommunications. A year ago few people had heard about the 
subject. By 1996 they will be in wide usage. The study will prepare vendors, 
providers and users for this event.<P> 


<b>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P> 

The report is the first extensive study of the future markets for broadband 
terminals, transport channels, and equipment, with estimates going all the way 
to the year 2010. The study is aimed at vendors, providers and potential users 
of broadband networks and equipment.<P>  


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P> 

The scope of the report is to describe sources of information that generate broadband bitstreams, the characteristics of these bitstreams, the required transmission links between sources and sinks, and the future overall broadband 
network.  A summary follows this introduction. The third section covers the background and includes an overview of the changing demands for bandwidth, the related policy of the Clinton-Gore administration, and brief descriptions of the existing telecommunications and cable television industries.<P>
In the fourth section the different future markets demanding broadband transmission facilities are discussed. The economic aspects, such as the expected revenues from broadband traffic, the estimated investment requirements, and the future markets for equipment are covered in a separate section.<P>
The sixth section describes the existing networks. The future technology is described in the seventh section. Different networks are described, as are broadband access, transmission and switching systems. A separate section covers the activities 
of the government and of regulatory agencies. The structure of the relevant industry, such as providers of the infrastructure, service providers, and vendors of equipment are covered in the ninth section. Activities overseas also are covered in this section. The companies and authorities mentioned in the report are listed with addresses, telephone numbers, and contacts in the 
end of the report. A list of acronyms also is included.<P> 

Actual data for 1992 are presented in the report, as are estimates for 1994, 
1998, 2002, 2006 and 2010.<P> 


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P> 

In forecasting the developing technologies, standard procedures were used. 
These include those described by Joseph P. Martino in the third edition of his 
book Technological Forecasting for Decision Making. The author of this report, 
Bertil Lindberg, is an adjunct associate professor at the Polytechnic 
University in Brooklyn, New York, where he currently teaches a graduate course 
in Technological Forecasting. Lindberg has followed technology and market 
trends in the telecommunications industry, and researched and published 
numerous reports during some 40 years.<P> 

The demand for bandwidth and traffic is calculated as follows. The number of terminals equipped for a certain service is determined for each type of workplace including schools and homes. Then the average number of minutes per day to be demanded by an average user is determined. The number of users is multiplied with the average usage to obtain the annual national demand in minutes by required bandwidth. Finally, the demand in bits per unit of time for each type of channel by bandwidth is obtained by multiplying the usage time by the maximum bandwidth of that type of channel. The demand is calculated for each of today's standard channels: 64 kbit/s, 1.544 Mbit/s, 51.84 Mbit/s, and 155.52 Mbit/s.<P>
Even though a certain demand may not require the full bandwidth of a channel, the entire channel will be occupied. Within 
the time span of the report, i.e., to 2010, the demand for channels with 
bandwidths over 155.52 Mbit/s is expected to be insignificant and is not 
covered in this report. Detailed calculations are made for each of the even 
years between 1990 and 2010. Due to lack of space, data for all years are not 
presented in the tables. However, the charts show data for all the even years.<P> 

The forecasted market data are based on future market predictions that can be 
made today.  This implies that the actual values will come close to the 
predicted ones if the government, regulatory authorities, and the market allow 
it to happen. The forecast predicts that users' demand for telecommunications 
services will remain at a value of 2% of gross domestic product through 2010.<P> 

The fact that data are shown with an accuracy to the last digit of a number in 
the report does not by any means indicate that the data are accurate at that 
level. The reason for presenting the data as shown is to give the reader the 
opportunity to compare data across the report and to reduce rounding errors in 
the totals.  Rounding errors in the last digit still occur.<P> 


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P> 

In preparing this report the literature was researched and scanned. Among them 
are the FCC Statistics of Common Carriers and the Federal Communications 
Commission (FCC) unpublished database report 43-07. At the completion of this 
report, FCC data through December 31, 1992 were available. Knowledgeable 
persons among vendors, providers and users were interviewed. International and 
national standards were reviewed, as well as standards work in progress.<P> 


<b>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS INCLUDING
WORK DONE BY OTHER AUTHORS</B><P>

BCC Report G-147 covers the delivery of television program to residences by other means than broadcast and cable television. The report, Delivery 
Alternatives for Residential Television, by Thomas Rush, was researched and written independently of this Electronic Superhighway report.<P> 

<CENTER>
<H3><I>SUMMARY</I></H3>
</CENTER>


The information age is at our doorsteps. New information is generated in great 
volume. The public is demanding access to large amounts of information. This 
creates a demand for transportation of large volumes of information between 
suppliers and users. Not only is the volume of information requiring 
transportation increasing, the requirements for bandwidth are growing, too. 
Among new activities with large bandwidth requirements are video-on-demand, 
multimedia applications, videoconferencing, digital facsimile and high-speed 
data transmission. These new demands create a demand for improved broadband 
communications facilities.<P> 



<CENTER><B>TABLE 1<P>

                 GROWTH OF THE NETWORK BUSINESS<BR>
                      (Billions of Dollars)</CENTER></B><P>
<PRE>
AAGR, %
                      1992    1994   1998   2002   2006  2010  1994/   2002
                                                               2002    2010

TOTAL                  113     126    163    188    191   365  5.1      8.7
of which local
carriers                42      45     55     68     91   146  5.2     10.0
long distance
 carriers               71      81    109    120    100   218  5.0      7.8

Fastest growing by market in local carrier revenue

Video                   0       0      0      0      11   62   67.6   105.1
Data                    4       7     15     27      36   43   18.9     5.5
Fastest growing local carrier revenues by bandwidth
155.52 Mbit/s           0.1     0.1    0.5    2      11   49   36.0    54.1 
51.84 Mbit/s            0.2     0.4    1      4       9   15   32.2    19.0
1.544 Mbit/s            1       2      7     15      22   31   28.5      9.3


</PRE><P>

Presuming a completely free market, the revenues of telecommunications for local exchange carriers and other entities handling access lines are expected to grow from a total of $45 billion in 1994 to $68 billion in 2002 and to reach $146 billion in 2010, or 2.1% of the gross domestic product (GDP). The revenues of providers of local services, shown, refer to net revenue and do not include access charges of about $26 billion annually. Table 1 shows the fastest growing segments by bandwidth of access lines and by type of traffic.<P>

In addition, long distance carriers and similar entities connecting local exchange areas are facing a potential market growing from $81 billion in 1994 to $120 billion in the year 2002 and to reach $218 billion in 2010. The 
revenues of long distance service providers include the $25-27 billion that 
they have to pay to the local carriers in access charges. Currently, one 
quarter of all traffic passes through long distance carriers and with the 
growth of the local traffic, the long distance traffic will also grow.<P>  

Most of the new traffic will be generated by video transmissions that have the potential of generating revenues of $62 billion in 2010.<P> 


<CENTER><B>TABLE 12<P>


       GROWTH OF THE EQUIPMENT MARKET FOR NEW ACCESS LINES<BR>
                      (Billions of Dollars)</CENTER></B><P>

<PRE>
                                                                       AAGR, %

                          1992     1994    1998   2002    2006  2010  1994/ 2002
                                                                      2002  2010

TOTAL                      26       33      38     41      92    258   2.8  26.0
Local carriers             21       27      32     35      75    232   3.4  26.5
Long distance
carriers                    5        6       5      6      17     26   0.9  20.5


</PRE><P>

To handle the growing amount of traffic, the current infrastructure has to be 
improved. Equipment vendors will be facing an annual market growing from $32 
billion in 1994, to $41 billion in 2002 and $258 billion in 2010 as shown in 
Table 2. In 2010 over 60% of the equipment market will be generated by access 
lines with a bandwidth of 155 Mbit/s and more.<P> 

In addition to the local carriers, long distance carriers will experience growth in revenues as stated earlier. Thus, vendors of equipment to long distance carriers will also face a growing market. The investment in equipment by these carriers will grow from an annual amount of $5.5 billion in 1994 to $5.9 billion in the year 2002 to reach $26.3 billion in 2010. <P>

Traffic within enterprises does not generate revenues for any 
telecommunications providers. Thus, such revenues are excluded from the 
revenues listed in this report. However, revenues generated by dedicated (or private) lines passing through public networks are included.<P> 

Because the network products required to handle the new demand for broadband services essentially are new, the suppliers of broadband equipment will not necessarily be the conventional ones. Rather, the market is open to a wide range of new and old suppliers.<P> 

The best solution to handle voice and video over the same broadband facilities seems to be asynchronous transfer mode (ATM). While this technology was conceived for use in worldwide public networks, it has initially been applied to local and private networks. As the ATM switches required for these small networks are inherently small, and consequently the demand for large ATM switches is slow to materialize, manufacturers of small ATM switches got a 
head start.<P>  

While U.S. providers of networks and network services have been slow in 
advancing broadband services such as those depending on ATM, the Europeans are 
advancing in the deployment of ATM based services. This fact may lead to a 
situation where the Europeans will get an advantage over U.S. suppliers.<P>  

For many years the telecommunications and cable television industries have 
been working on improvements of their networks, and on merging them. Providers 
of telephone service want to add broadband data and video services, while 
providers of cable television want to add telephone and data service to their 
networks. International and national standards bodies have been working on 
integrated and broadband networks for a long time. Obviously, equipment 
manufacturers are involved. All see the need for broadband digital networks in 
the future and all want to be in on it.<P> 

The need for electronic superhighways in the United States was mentioned as a 
campaign issue in a press release from the Clinton-Gore campaign headquarters 
on September 21, 1992. Since the election the point has mainly been carried by 
Vice President Gore. What he has in mind is a broadband digital network 
similar to the narrowband data networks operated by the government and by 
universities.<P> 

The providers of public telecommunications services, i.e., the conventional telephone companies, are considering transmission links that can carry 2.5 gigabit/s (Gbit/s, 109 bit/s, thousand million bit/s), and switches for those bitstreams.  The current limits are in the accessing of these broadband networks. Practically all existing access lines consist of twisted copper wire pairs that are designed and built to carry voice traffic. With a developing technology called asymmetric digital subscriber lines (ADSL), copper-based 
loops will be able to carry bitstreams at up to 6.3 Mbit/s to subscribers.<P> 

The cable television industry has cable networks that reach 60 million homes in the U.S. and are passing by another 30 million homes for a potential 90 million homes wired for cable television. These networks are designed to 
deliver television programs to homes, but only a few are built for transmissions the other way. Thus, they cannot be used for two-way communications today. Further, they have been prohibited from entering the telephone business by the government. However, the cable television industry has its eye on going into the telephone market, especially two-way broadband services.<P> 

The telephone companies are currently prohibited from transporting television programs to users. However, both parties are petitioning the FCC and lobbying Congress to obtain the right to enter each other's traditional markets. In some individual cases they have already succeeded, and the trend seems to go towards granting full competition in the same markets for telephone and cable 
companies.<P> 

The FCC is considering applications from telephone operating companies to 
offer "video dialtone." This refers to switched broadband services. Twenty-two 
telcos have applied for permission to offer video dialtone to 4.5% of U.S. 
homes.<P>

