<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-151  DIGITAL VIDEO NETWORKING
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ANAND RAO
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Our goal in conducting this study is to evaluate the results of
recent developments in digital networking and computing
technologies and how they affect the multimedia networking
industry.<P>

Technological innovations in digital video computing and
communication are generating new opportunities for those who are
already in the industry and for newcomers.  While some giants
dominate the industry, some of the more interesting developments
are generated by small and medium sized entrepreneurs.  The
industry is intensely software-oriented with no known hardware
vendor who can provide a direction.  Participants in the industry
include such diverse groups as vendors of microprocessors, servers,
desktop computers, network components, interfaces, and telephone
service providers, etc.  Our report ties together some of the more
active sectors of the industry and presents a comprehensive
analysis of the opportunities offered in each group.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study was undertaken to measure growth prospects and direct
business possibilities that are generated for the vendors and
suppliers of select components and services for the digital video
computing and networking industry.  Our analyst was made aware of
the differences between the direct and indirect business
opportunities that may result because of developments in this
industry.  While the overall opportunities may exceed several
billion dollars, only select sectors of the industry that provide
opportunities for the vendors and suppliers of equipment and
services will be focused on.  Our goal is to analyze the
opportunities that are most attractive for these sectors.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION FOR THIS STUDY AND FROM WHOM</B><P>

This study is based on information carefully compiled from
interviews with industry experts and officials of Federal agencies,
data excerpted from questionnaires mailed to industry specialists
and other informed individuals, and analysis of a wide variety of
information generated by the industry press and technology
journals.  Additionally, selected industry experts were approached
more than once to clarify several related issues.<P>

Information generated from vendors and statistics generated from
select agencies was matched to produce estimates of the most viable
areas of business opportunities.  A consensus was developed to
focus on the most productive areas of the technology.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study covers the projected growth of select areas of
technologies that contribute to the digital video computing and
networking industry.<P>

Each projection was based on current industry statistics, opinions
from industry experts, and analysis of information available from
several industry sources.<P>

Where applicable we have taken a general average of the projections
provided by various industry sources and have matched them with the
volume of current business reported from Federal agencies and
associations.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC has surveyed over 100 sources to obtain data for this study.
These included the Federal Communications Commission, the
Department of Commerce, consultants, vendors, users, and others.
Major industry publications, reports from industry associations,
and major financial publications were also consulted.<P>

