<HEAD><TITLE>G-153 INTERNETWORKING: THE KEY TO THE NATIONAL
INFORMATION INFRASTRUCTURE 
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-153 INTERNETWORKING: THE KEY TO THE NATIONAL
INFORMATION INFRASTRUCTURE</H2>
<HR><P>
<I>THOMAS RUSH</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>


<P>A wealth of media attention has been given to the Information Highway.  Our goal
in writing this report is to offer the reader both a road map and a definition of
segments and alternatives for achieving the Information Highway result.  We offer
10-year assessments of the forecasts, issues, and drivers for each segment.  This
report is a sequel to G150, The Future for Telecommunications/Electronic
Superhighway, which analyzed the demand side of the telecommunications
business through the year 2000.  This report emphasizes the specific technologies
that are going to make it all happen.</P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B>

<P>The convergence factors that have brought computers and communications
together are more crisply definable than ever before.  Computers are moving into
the home and adding multi-media and/or video capability.  The microelectronics
evolution has made it possible for the set-top converter for cable television to be
a computer in itself.  Communications via fiber optics offer tremendous capacity,
and the microelectronics to drive fiber have brought both additional capacity and
flexibility to the transmission scenarios.  Our reasons for doing this study are to show
that now is the time to forecast how all these alternatives work together, and how
internetworking is the key to the Information Highway.</P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B>

<P>This study is a result of BCC offering individual studies on all the aspects of the
Information Highway in recent years.  This study pulls these individual efforts
together with one overriding theme -- internetworking.  It is intended as a planning
guide for all organizations in the internetworking businesses of providing service,
databases, transmission, access, and equipment for all forms of voice, data, and
video communications.</P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>This study views all components of the Information Highway under the umbrella of
internetworking.  It is limited to a top-level view of the subject, recognizing that
each element is worthy of an individual study.  It includes forecasts for each
segment that is based on 1995 dollars.</P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>Assumptions are noted with all forecasts, along with potential issues and drivers.  We
look for synergistic forces, pricing trends, and convergence factors to derive future
acceptance of technology and information.</P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES AND OTHER BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B>

<P>Much of the research for this report comes from previous efforts by BCC.  We have
noted that many of our previous forecasts on subjects such as Video
Communications, LAN Systems, Private Networks, Local Telephone Companies, and
the like, have been extremely accurate both in the assumptions behind our
forecasts as well as the numerical values of our forecasts.  Additionally, we use
sources from the press, conference speakers, interviews, and trade shows for our
verification of data.</P>




