<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-154: EARLY BUSINESS OPPORTUNITIES IN 
INTERACTIVE TELEVISION
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-154: EARLY BUSINESS OPPORTUNITIES IN 
INTERACTIVE TELEVISION
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Anand Rao
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Our goal in conducting this study is to evaluate the market
potential for products and services in the emerging markets of
interactive television in the United States.  This report focuses
on the business and home entertainment sectors of the interactive
television industry.  Our objective is to highlight main areas of
programs both by types and production, transmission techniques,
home and business reception areas, products used in the areas of
program production, transmission and reception.<P>

<b>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study was undertaken to measure the growth prospects and cross
influences that the network and cable television, phone, satellite,
coaxial cable and fiber optic industries have on each other in the
emerging world of interactive television.  Additionally, the
results of current interactive television tests, FCC standards and
licensing procedures, and strategic alliances between leading
industry partners have high impact on the growth prospects of the
interactive industry.  While the available reports cover "some
specific areas" of the industry, we believe that this study
includes comprehensive all important technology and business
sectors of the industry in the U.S.<P>

This report also analyzes the various approaches adopted by the
sponsors of various interactive trials that are currently going on
in several locations in the country.<P>

The researchers were made aware of the conflicting and
contradictory information currently being generated in the industry
about the projected technical and business problems and other
issues in the interactive industry.  Some industry experts have
projected very high growth rates for all sectors of the interactive
TV industry, while others predict unusually poor growth prospects
for the industry.  Our goal for the study was to evaluate the
"real" growth potential for both program production, transmission
and reception, as well as products required for all three areas,
and arrive at realistic projections.<P>


<b>CONTRIBUTION FOR THIS STUDY AND FROM WHOM</B><P>

This study is based on detailed information generated from
interviews with vendors, users, consultants, officials of industry
associations and federal government agencies, sponsors of various
trials, and other industry experts.  Additionally, a variety of
published information from governmental, trade press, associations,
research organizations, the Federal Communications Commission and
other sources were analyzed. Over 100 vendors from around the
country were approached for detailed information on their
activities and the data generated was carefully analyzed.<P>

Information generated from various sources was matched to produce
an "actual deployment prospects vs projected installation"
scenario.  Furthermore, a consensus was developed to eliminate the
most vexing problem facing the industry - whether interactive
television is technically viable, cost-effective, and whether the
viewers will be ready to pay for the services.  A median cost
crossover ratio was developed to arrive at a reasonable deployment
scenario.<P>


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study covers the major products, program types and
transmission technologies, as well as products and components that
are likely to be used in the interactive television industry.  The
analysis focuses on all three major sectors of the industry -
program production, transmission, and reception.  Each segment is
analyzed, focusing on the current state of the technology and
developments, major technology and business trends influencing the
development of the industry.  A brief overview of the technology
and interactive procedures is presented where appropriate.<P>


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis, by each major technology, product,
services, and programming group segment, focusing on its relevance
to the overall industry structure.  The projections for each
segment evaluate the per-year growth during the next five years.<P>

Where applicable, the volume of growth is presented in dollars,
number of hours of programming, likely subscribers and program
sponsors.  Each projection was based on current industry
statistics, opinions from industry experts and analyses available
from several sources.<P>


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P> 

BCC has surveyed over 300 sources to obtain data for this study. 
These included manufacturers of equipment such as cameras,
recorders, etc., major studios, cable and phone companies,
advertising agencies, industry associations, officials of the
Federal Communications Commission, and other industry experts. 
Major industry publications, reports from the Federal
Communications Commission, National Telephone Industries
Association, Cable Television Association and financial press were
also included.<P>


