G-182 PERSONAL NAVIGATION SYSTEM
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-182 PERSONAL NAVIGATION SYSTEM
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS RUSH</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

There have been many specialized uses of the Global
Positioning System (GPS) of satellites, primarily in the
military and maritime navigation markets. Our goal in
writing this report is to size the market for consumer
products and services, particularly those markets that
utilize GPS for positioning to aid in either personal
navigation or tracking of vehicles or personnel. We reach
that goal by assessing the various suppliers' abilities to
address the consumer market with the proper products.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Our early assessment of this market showed that forthcoming
is a convergence of the several product areas of technology,
namely: digital mapping, CD-ROM implementation in computers,
GPS receivers, and microelectronics. All are on a downward
spiral of pricing, and put together they offer a strategic
package that allows for in-vehicle permanently installed
systems as well as handheld products. In doing this study we
assess how all of these technologies can come together to
offer a package of convenience and key value to the
consumer.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

It is our intention that this study is a guide to the
suppliers of products and services in developing business
plans to address the consumer market. Our forecasts,
statements of assumptions, and discussion of issues serve as
a compendium of backup data for individual business plans.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

All aspects of the personal use of GPS positioning systems
are covered in this report. It does not include GPS uses for
nonpersonal applications such as military, marine, or
commercial vehicles. It covers forecasts and assumptions for
the United States, using a 10-year forecast that is
developed from a "bottoms up" method of forecasting price
and units.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Assumptions are noted with all forecasts, along with the key
drivers and potential issues. We look for both value-added
factors and consumer convenience factors in developing
drivers for the forecasts. We look for pricing trends,
industry leaders, representative products and services, and
convergence factors to derive future acceptance of this
technology and digital database contribution.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES AND OTHER BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

BCC is a leader in supplying market planning information to
the computer and communications industries. Our reports on
wireless communications and mobile satellites as early as
1990 have addressed the potential of the automatic vehicle
location application. We have been consistent in predicting
rapid acceptance of microelectronics in all forms, primarily
based on ever-increasing functions at an ever-decreasing
price. This report is written from information garnered
through trade shows, trade press literature, marketing
literature, and interviews of industry sources, along with
the experience of our staff.<P>


