<HEAD><TITLE> G-185 THE FUTURE OF PORTABLE COMPUTING AND
COMMUNICATIONS DEVICES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> G-185 THE FUTURE OF PORTABLE COMPUTING AND
COMMUNICATIONS DEVICES </H2>
<HR><P>
<I>MARC FAVREAU</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>


<P>Many segments of the portable computer industry are in full stride. 
Propelled by highly capable machines offering easy portability as well
as the ability to access data remotely, the portable computer market is
becoming the fastest growing segment of the industry.  Remote access
has further produced the newest industry buzzword, convergence. 
The discussion of this topic revolves around the fusion of computers
with communications, computers with communications and
entertainment technology, voice with video and data communications,
etc.  Additionally, there also exists a convergence of differing
computing devices as their functions and markets begin to overlap.</P>  

<P>Whether for the home, business or research communities, the overall
vision revolves around computers, stationary or portable, gaining the
ability to interface with essentially any technology which can transmit
information or entertainment, be it by voice, video, or data over a
wire or through the airwaves.</P> 

<P>This BCC report presents a detailed analysis of the current and future
markets for the large variety of portable computing applications, from
the notebook and subnotebook computer form factors to handheld
computers primarily for data handling, as well as those still-evolving
devices loosely called PDAs.  The study also addresses the potential
impact of the latest wireless communications systems on the market. 
Forecasts are presented that project sales and product evolution
through the year 2000.</P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B>

<P>The study is presented at this time because of the rapid development
of the mobile computing market.  A second generation of PDAs has
been introduced and the FCC auction of bandwidth for new wireless
communications systems promises to bring change to both the
communication and computer industries.</P>

<P>Until recently, factors such as high costs, large size and weight, high
power consumption, and poor capability have frustrated mobile
computer users.  However, portability has improved dramatically and
prices are falling due to increases in both component supply and
competition.  In addition, the largest form factors, the notebook and
subnotebook computers, can now boast virtually identical capabilities
as desktop machines.</P>

<P>Current trends indicate that the markets for most portable devices will
continue to grow as more and more people seek the ability to be
productive away from the office.  Continuing evolution of the
smallest devices will eventually bring them into line with market
requirements.</P> 

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B>

<P>Portable computers are already a strong and rapidly growing segment
of the overall computer industry.  However, a great deal of activity is
concentrated in the development of new materials, components, and
methods that will be required to successfully implement the new ideas
being suggested for a wide variety computing and communications
applications.</P>

<P>This report provides an analysis of those segments of the portable
computing industry and markets which involve devices weighing 8
pounds or less, both by function and end use, through the year 2000. 
The structure of the industry is discussed, and company profiles of the
major players in each of the industry's three main segments are
presented.  An analysis of the impact that this market will have on the
bulk of components that make up portable systems is also included. 
The report is directed to decision makers in the portable computing
industries and markets as well as those of the related electronics
packaging and materials fields.  They include:</P>

<UL>
   <LI>Portable computer developers
   <LI>Communication device developers
   <LI>Peripheral equipment developers
   <LI>Software application developers
   <LI>Electronic material suppliers
   <LI>Integrated circuit and other component suppliers
   <LI>Printed circuit board suppliers
   <LI>Equipment manufacturers


   <LI>Marketplace managers
   <LI>Merger, acquisition, and investment executives.
</UL>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>This report is an analytical business tool whose primary purpose is to
cover the growing portable computer industry in terms of application
and end-use markets.  A summary follows this introductory section
and is followed immediately by an overview of the history of portable
computing and the development of the market.  The ensuing segments
are analyses of the current and future market trends. </P> 

<P>The final segments address the industry's structure as well as an
analysis of the portable computer's impact on bulk product
components from which portable computer products are built.</P>

<P>The appendices include directories of pertinent associations and
conferences, as well as an extensive directory of related vendors and
manufacturers of all types of portable computing devices.</P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>The material presented is based on information gathered from
personal contacts with participants within the portable computing
industry as well as a thorough review of the technology gathered from
technical papers and industry conferences.  Our final analyses and
projections are based on a combination of a consensus among the
primary contacts combined with our understanding of the impact of
trends from a historical perspective.</P>

<P>Additional data was obtained from extensive reviews of secondary
sources.  These include trade publications, trade associations,
company literature, and online data bases.  This was done to
supplement our understanding of applications, markets, and trends in
the portable computing and communications industries.</P>  

<P>All dollar projections presented in this report are in 1995 constant
dollars.</P>


<B>RELATED BCC RESEARCH CREDENTIALS</B>

<P>BCC has been a leader in market research and consulting to the
electronics and materials industries since 1971.  Over the last several
years, BCC has produced in-depth analyses of technologies and
business opportunities in materials and components for advanced
computer systems, such as thick and thin film in microelectronics,
electronic integrated circuit and component packaging, printed circuit
board manufacturing, surface mount technology, multichip modules,
and deposition technology.  Some reports of interest are:</P>

<UL>
   <LI>G-067X    Printed Circuit Boards: Markets &
Opportunities
   <LI>G-118     Surface Mount Technology in Electronics
   <LI>G-152     PCMCIA Technology: Impressive Growth Through
               2000, Uncertainty Beyond
   <LI>GB-121R   Electronic Ceramics
   <LI>GB-128R   Thick and Thin Film in Microelectronics
   <LI>GB-138R   Multichip Packaging & Base Chip Systems
   <LI>GB-156    Advanced Electronic Packaging Systems
   <LI>GB-160    Magnetic/Opto-Magnetic Storage: Technology
               Through 2000
   <LI>GB-171    The Changing Display Industry: CRT and Flat
Panel
</UL>

<P>Appendix IV contains a more complete list of related BCC reports as
well as their dates of publication and prices.</P>



