<HEAD><TITLE> G-189 SUPPLYING THE VIRTUAL HOME OFFICE: MARKETS FOR EQUIPMENT,
SUPPLIES AND SERVICES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> G-189 SUPPLYING THE VIRTUAL HOME OFFICE: MARKETS FOR EQUIPMENT,
SUPPLIES AND SERVICES </H2>
<HR><P>
<I>CAROLYN GREENE MILLER </I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>


<P>From the employees who are scheduled to work at home, to the after hours 
worker, and including the self-employed home office worker, home offices have 
been in existence for years.  Within the past year or so, manufacturers have 
recognized the significance of the home market which includes users from 
children working on their homework, using the online services to gather 
information, to their parents balancing their checkbook, and lastly the home 
office worker.</P> 

<P>Throughout this report, the home office market will be referred to as such and 
should not be confused with the overall home market.  Although, in many cases, 
home office workers purchase their home office products with the rest of the 
family in mind and therefore the line between home usage and home office usage 
becomes somewhat fuzzy. Therefore, in some cases, the home office market 
becomes a subsegment of the overall home market.  Only recently have the home 
office workers become in vogue and their needs have just begun to be addressed 
by office equipment manufacturers. Manufacturers' production and 
implementation of products have only begun to scratch the surface of the 
requirements of the home office population.</P> 

<P>This segment requires computers, peripherals, software and office products.   
However, this segment may require specialized equipment in terms of fully 
configured products that can be accommodated within smaller spaces, as the 
typical home office is in the basement or in the corner of the living room or 
may be even in a spare bedroom.</P> 

<P>BCC has prepared this report to show the viability of the home office segment 
of the workforce in terms of demographics, computers, peripherals, software, 
office products and ancillary services.  BCC has recognized the significance 
of this market whereas no other research or marketing source has.  BCC has 
delved into a myriad of specific areas of products to determine current and 
future unit and value trends of the home office market, whereas others have 
merely suggested broad-based needs to the home office worker such as a guide 
to working at home.</P> 



<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>The research for this report included personal contacts with key management 
and marketing professionals within the leading competitors in each product 
segment.  Additional contacts were made to people within these industries that 
are on the client side, the actual users of these products.  Further contacts 
were made to home office workers, be they telecommuters or self-employed home 
office workers.</P> 

<P>The basis of the trends and forecasts were determined from the aforementioned 
contacts, combined with information gathered from secondary sources such as; 
trade publications, trade associations, on-line databases, company literature 
to supplement our understanding of the markets, applications and trends 
impacting the future of telecommuting, working from home and the home office 
environment.</P> 

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B>

<P>Although this segment of the work force has been evolving for the past few 
years, acknowledgement by the very manufacturers that could benefit from new 
workers have been slow on the upstart.  This analysis should be used by these 
companies to further understand the demands of this exceptionally viable 
segment of the workforce and to forecast production of their products based 
upon information gathered from their own sources and in conjunction with this 
report.</P> 





