<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-170C:  TRADING WITH MEXICO: CONSUMER ELECTRONICS
AND TELECOMMUNICATIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-170C:  TRADING WITH MEXICO: CONSUMER ELECTRONICS
AND TELECOMMUNICATIONS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>FRANK RENAUD
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report focuses on two industries, namely, the
telecommunications industry and the electronics and computer
industry.  It has two objectives: first, to analyze in detail the
changes in the trade relationships between the U.S. and Mexico
brought about by the approval of NAFTA; second, to present
forecasts for U.S. exports to Mexico for each of those industries.<P>


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

After heated debates, a heavy dose of political arm twisting, and
much hand wringing, the U.S. Congress approved, last November, the Bush Administration's trade agreement with Mexico.  The North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), has now been approved by all three governments and took effect on January 1, 1994.<P>  

The treaty has been hailed as the most promising trade agreement
ever signed, of even more importance than the agreement linking the
European countries into a Common Market.  Canada, the U.S., and Mexico now represent a market with a combined GDP of over $6.3 trillion, with a population of some 370 million people.  Even though Mexico is the economic weak member in this agreement, it is believed the dismantling of trade barriers will give a boost to its economy.  NAFTA will provide it with the much needed stable environment that should attract the foreign capital it requires to modernize its industries.  It will also allow Mexico to focus more on updating its physical and social infrastructure and less on protecting its inefficient industries.<P>

NAFTA is also expected to create additional trade opportunities
for the U.S.  In this third of a three-report series, we examine
the impact the NAFTA will have on opportunities for additional U.S.
exports for two industries: telecommunications and electronics and
computers.  The first previously published report focused on autos
and auto parts and the second analyzed prospects for additional
trade in crude petroleum, natural gas, petrochemicals, and
plastics.<P>


The telecommunications system as personified by Telefonos de Mexico
(TELMEX) is the pride of Mexico's economy and rapidly becoming one
of its most important industries.  Since its privatization in 1990,
it has established itself as a crucial element in bringing Mexico
closer to its industrialized neighbors to the North.  It is rapidly
extending Mexico's telephone network throughout the country and it
is modernizing and expanding its long-distance links with the
outside world.  It has also attracted the attention of the
investment community and has become the darling of investors.<P>   

Mexico's indigenous electronics and computer industry has suffered
setbacks in recent years due to the stiff competition from imports. 
It is small in comparison to other sectors and Mexican
manufacturers are relatively inefficient versus those found in the
U.S. and Canada.  The indigenous industry compares unfavorably with
the 500+ maquiladora plants involved in the manufacturing and
assembling of electronics and computer products.  Those in-bond
plants, set up mostly by U.S. producers to reap the benefits of low
wages for their labor-intensive operations, promise to flourish
under NAFTA as their outputs are allowed to be sold more freely
in the Mexican market.  The manufacturing of more sophisticated
computer equipment, however, may continue to remain in the U.S. as
the industry is suffering from overcapacity and cutbacks, not
expansion.<P>



<b>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

The study is aimed at those groups and individuals directly and
indirectly connected with the two industries covered in this
report.  They are the most affected by NAFTA and they will have
to decide within the next few years whether or not to develop plans
to take advantage of NAFTA.  We are offering these interested
parties our insights into possible developments in Mexico over the
next 10 years.  Decisions whether to begin or expand business
programs should always be done with as much information as
possible.  By providing our customers with a well reasoned
analysis, we believe that the quality of their decision-making
process can be greatly enhanced.<P>


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study is divided into two sectors covering the
telecommunications equipment and the electronics and computer
industries.  It focuses first on the changes brought about by 
NAFTA, changes mostly in the investment rules and tariff structure
for each sector.  It then proceeds to analyze the demand for
equipment and services for those two sectors in Mexico.  We analyze
the present structure and provide a 10-year forecast for both
industries, with emphasis on imports for U.S.-made products.<P>



<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

This study relies on a wide variety of sources.  We are thankful to
those industry experts contacted during the course of this study
who have been willing to share their thoughts with us.  We have
also made use of publicly available sources of information such as
the numerous studies published over the last two years on the
potential impact of NAFTA on the various sectors of the U.S.
and Mexican industries.<P>



<b>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

<UL>GB-008N   The Competitive U.S. Market for Autos Parts<BR>
GB-170A   Trading with Mexico: The Automobile and Auto Parts
          Industry<BR>
GP-170B   Trading with Mexico: Crude Petroleum, Natural Gas,
          Petrochemical, and Plastics<BR>
P-2000    Opportunities for Plastics in the 1990s<BR>
G-148     Worldwide Telecommunications<BR>
GB-162    Advanced Transportation Control Systems
          Industries in Transition, a monthly newsletter<P></UL>

