<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-050  UNIINTERRUPTIBLE POWER SUPPLY SYSTEMS:
Continuous Data and Network Service
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-050  UNINTERRUPTIBLE POWER SUPPLY SYSTEMS:
Continuous Data and Network Service
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ROBERT MORAN
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

BCC's goal in conducting this study was to determine the current
worldwide status of the market for uninterruptible power supply
(UPS) systems, and to assess their growth potential over a 5 year
period from 1992 to 1997.  We were particularly interested in the
impact on the market brought about through new technology.  We were
also interested in the types of batteries used in UPS devices, and
the software produced by the industry.<P>

Our major objective was to present a comprehensive analysis of the
current uninterruptible power supply market and plot its future
course.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

Over the past several years, advances in technology have changed
the size and structure of UPS systems.  Smaller, more powerful
devices are being sold to meet the requirements of markets in
transition.  The move away from central computing and large
mainframes to decentralized personal computers and workstations has
changed power management demands.  Electronic instruments have
replaced electromechanical devices in the laboratory and
industrial environment, expanding the need for smaller UPS systems.<P>


BCC decided to examine the current status of UPS systems.  We were
interested in finding out how they were evolving and what specific
changes were taking place.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

We assembled a study of the two basic UPS technologies: standby and
online.  We present a worldwide industry structure, examine the
competitive aspects of the industry, analyze the current markets,
and project shipments for each major technology to 1997.  The study
will be of interest to those who manufacture UPS devices,
electrical and electronic equipment, batteries, and cables.  It
will also interest those who manufacture computers, communications
network equipment, laboratory and process control devices, and
security systems.  Producers of software will also find it useful.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of our study encompasses the four types of standby and
online UPS systems, the types of batteries used to support them,
and the kinds of software that enable users to diagnose power
problems, communicate with UPS devices, and monitor and control
their operation.  We also project UPS systems by power range and
present the relative positions of the systems by technology.
Growth potential is analyzed for the four types of systems:
traditional standby, UPS card, double conversion online, and
line-interactive.  Also discussed is the growth of UPS systems by
application areas: data processing, communications, industrial,
medical and laboratory, utility, and security.  We present forecasts
to 1997.  Technological issues and trends are reviewed.  Other
influential factors such as past growth and the effects of the
economic climate, are also discussed.<P>

Because this is a worldwide industry, BCC analyzes the domestic and
international regulatory and standards situations and their impact
on the UPS business.  The economic environment and its effect on
the business is also reviewed.  BCC presents an analysis of the
market factors within the UPS industry and among various end-user
industries, and looks at their impact for the future.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis of UPS shipments and their value by major
category.  Our estimated value is what manufacturers and  material
providers have paid in current dollars.  Then, based on our
surveys, we analyze UPS applications by major technology, calculate
estimates for growth, and forecast shipments of UPS systems and
their value, and the value of batteries and software for 1997.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC surveyed approximately 65 companies to obtain the data for this
report.  Included were manufacturers of UPS systems, batteries and
software providers.  We surveyed distributors of UPS systems and
companies that use these devices in various industries, such as
data processing, telecommunications, medical and laboratory
equipment, and process control.  We also included several trade
associations, the U.S. Department of Commerce, and data from
financial and industry sources.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Several other reports are related to this topic.  They are: 

<UL>GB-086R
The U.S. Battery Industry<BR>
G-133 Telecommunications Retail Opportunities<BR>
G-137 Long Distance Markets, 2001<BR>
G-138 Video Communications into The 21st Century</UL><P>

BCC also publishes <i>Battery & EV Technology</i>, a monthly newsletter.<P>

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
