<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-070N  GROWTH OPPORTUNITIES IN WIRE, CABLE & FIBER OPTICS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-070N  GROWTH OPPORTUNITIES IN WIRE, CABLE & FIBER OPTICS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ROBERT MORAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

BCC's goal in conducting this study was to determine the current
worldwide status of the insulated wire and cable industry, and
assess the growth potential over a five year period from 1990 to
1995.  We were particularly interested in the uses of the more
traditional types of wire and cable in comparison with fiber optic
cable.  In addition, we were interested in the potential market for
key insulation materials, such as resins and rubber-
based compounds, and newer materials used for high-temperature
applications and non-toxic flame retardation.<P>

Our major objective was to present a comprehensive analysis of the
current wire and cable industry and plot its future course.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

Wire and cable is a mature business that is experiencing flat
growth.  In recent years, however, demand for electronic, data and
telecommunications functions has increased.  In addition,
requirements for high temperature and flame-retardant, non-toxic
wire and cable products has stimulated demand for newer, more
functional insulation materials.<P>

BCC decided to examine the current position of the various wire and
cable technologies to see how these demands were being met.  We
were interested in determining the competitiveness of the various
types of wire and cable and their insulating materials.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

We assembled a study of the nine major types of wire and cable
products, their technological trends, and the major materials used
for their insulation.   We present a worldwide industry structure,
examine the competitive aspects of the industry, analyze the
current markets, and project shipments for each of the nine product
categories for 1995.  This study will be of interest to those who
make electrical and electronic devices, construct industrial,
institutional and residential buildings, design and install
communications systems, and those in the utility business.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of our study encompasses the nine major types of wire and
cable products: electronic, telephone and telegraph, power
distribution, control and signal, building, apparatus, magnet,
"other," and fiber optic.  BCC explores each technology, makes
an assessment of its current market status, examines its influence
on future markets, and presents forecasts of growth to 1995.
Various technological issues, including new kinds of materials, are
discussed.  Other influential factors, such as past growth
performance, usage by industry sector, and the functions of power
transmission versus communications, are also discussed.<P>

Because this is a worldwide industry, BCC analyzes the domestic and
international regulatory environments and their impact on the wire
and cable business.  We also assess various international economic
indicators and their possible impact on the industry.  BCC
presents an analysis of the driving forces within wire and cable,
and evaluates the market growth factors for the future.<P>

We also review the use of materials such as the conventional
polymers used to insulate the bulk of wire and cable products.  In
addition, we review the fluorocarbons, low-halogen and other newer
compounds being used to provide high-temperature and flame-
retardant properties.  Future costs and consumption of these
materials, and their percentage of total wire and cable costs, are
also estimated.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis of the value of wire and cable shipments
by each product category.  We also present the value of materials
used in the production of each wire and cable product.  Our
estimated value is what manufacturers and materials providers have
paid in current dollars.  Then, based on our surveys, we analyze
applications for each of the nine major products, and calculate an
estimate for growth, and forecast shipments for 1995.<P>

We present the kinds and values of insulation materials used for
wire and cable in 1990.  Based on technological trends and
application growth, we project materials consumption for 1995.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC surveyed approximately 70 companies to obtain the data for this
report.  Included were manufacturers and distributors of wire and
cable, major users of these products, and suppliers of materials.
We also included the U.S. Department of Commerce, several trade
associations, and data from financial and industry sources.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Several other reports are related to this topic.  They are:<P>
<MENU>
C004U  Flame Retardant Chemicals<BR>
G089R  Advanced Building Control Systems<BR> 
G074N  Exploding Local Area Network Marketing<BR>
G131   Wireless Communication<BR>
G129   LAN Connectivity</MENU><P>

