<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-089R  ADVANCED BUILDING CONTROL SYSTEMS AND DEVICES:
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> G-089R  ADVANCED BUILDING CONTROL SYSTEMS AND DEVICES:
</H2>

<HR><P>


<I>JAMES STOTTER</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>



<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This study analyzes and forecasts both the product and end-use
markets for advanced building communication and control systems and
devices (or ABCs). Briefly, the markets for products are divided
into two broad types of ABCs:<P>

--DEVICES, which are individual control products such as those used
for security, HVAC, and lighting; and<P>

--SYSTEMS, which are centrally controlled products including those
used for security, HVAC, lighting, and telecommunications.<P>

The markets for end-users fall within the four conventional
classifications of buildings: Residential, Commercial, Industrial,
& Institutional.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR WRITING THIS STUDY</B><P>

There are dramatic changes occurring in the markets for products
that make it easier to manage buildings and for products that
improve production through enhanced telecommunications. Some of
these products are the ABCs examined in this study. (Essentially
there is no difference between a building fully equipped with ABCs
integrated as one system and an intelligent, or smart, building.)
The ABC industry is now beginning to blossom into a respectable and
interesting business. Thus, many questions have to be answered:<P>

* Which types of buildings tend to be equipped with which types of
ABCs?<P>

* What are product preferences by type of building?<P>

* What are the different ABC product forecasts?<P>

* Does all the initial hype and subsequent bad press on the concept
of intelligent buildings now,have implications in the marketing of
ABCs?<P>

* To what extent is there consumer education regarding ABCS, and
what does that suggest for the future?<P>

* How is the diffuse industry structure of the firms which
manufacture ABC products broken down?<P>

The study was undertaken also to determine the impact of all the
related trends and patterns on the future of ABCs. Among these
trends are: rapidly advancing technologies, deregulation, growing
concern over social issues, the slowing of inflation, declining
prices in electronic Products, the increasing number of elderly,
declining household size, merger & acquisition activity, and the
growing use of intelligent buildings in other developed nations.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF STUDY</B><P>

This study is unique in eight ways -- that is, it makes eight
contributions to understanding the so-called business end of the
building control industry. They are:<P>

* The study develops and organizes a useful classification system
which simplifies understanding what products perform what
functions. This is useful in two ways:<P>

--determines where a firm and its competitors fit into the overall
picture
--Articulates or defines markets to determine strategy<P>

* The marketing of intelligent buildings in the U.S. is studied for
its impact on why product demand has developed so differently here
than in other industrial democracies. Included in this are the
implications for ABCs, as industries fight to survive by
modernizing.<P>

* Market size, forecasts, and growth rates are detailed by eight
product types, as well as two broader product groupings. This
includes developing the ratio between expenditures on ABCS and
expenditures on building construction. This study is designed
especially for manufacturers and users of the products discussed.
Others, such as industry analysts and consultants should also find
the study helpful.<P>

* The study analyzes why the eight different product groups are
growing at different rates.<P>

* The four basic groups of end-users are studied for trends that
affect their respective demand for ABCs.<P>

* The industry structure is investigated for its global
implications. Both foreign firms, as well as recent M&A activity,
are included.<P>

* The hype of earlier years has had its negative impact. This and
other marketing issues--especially consumer education--are
analyzed.<P>

* The impact on ABCs of financing, leases, government actions, and
technology are examined.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study is laid out according to the following table of
contents, with special features of each
section noted:<P>

<B>ENVIRONMENTAL FACTORS</B><P>

These are primarily:<P>

1. Economic which emphasizes GNP, interest rates, and construction
activity. Of particular interest here is a series of ratios,
discussed more below, relating ABC expenditures to construction
expenditures.<P>

2. Demographic with special attention to trends such as fewer
persons per household and more elderly.<P>

3. Regulatory which focuses on issues which include (but are not
limited to) government actions, technical standards, health
concerns, building codes, and taxes.<P>

<B>MARKETING</B><P>

This section examines marketing issues, paying special attention
to:<P>

1. Financial, and Leases for their impact on demand for ABCs.<P>

2. Consumer Education, which is also discussed elsewhere in the
study because of it's importance.<P>

3. OEM Demand for ABCs versus Retrofit Demand.<P>

4. Channels of Distribution, especially retail or residential,
compared to non-residential or business.<P>

5. Technical and Perceived Problems with ABCs.<P>

6. Other Nations' use of ABCs and intelligent buildings.<P>

7. Profile of Existing Intelligent Buildings.<P>

<B>END-USE MARKETS</B><P>

This section examines trends that affect the demand for the
following four conventional classes of buildings which form the
end-use markets: Residential, Commercial, Industrial, &
Institutional.<P>

When certain generalizations apply, a two-way classification of
Residential & Non-residential is used.<P>

<B>INDUSTRY STRUCTURE</B><P>

This section includes market shares of leading manufacturers both,
overall and by the two broad groups of products (devices &
systems). There is also a discussion of the leading firms and
recent M&A activity.<P>

<B>PRODUCT OVERVIEW</B><P>

Included in this section are:<P>

1. R&D and Technology<P>

2. Service aspects of ABCs<P>

3. "Organizational table" of the ABC industry. The table then forms
the basis for the next two sections which respectively examine and
forecast the device markets and the system markets.<P>

DEVICES:<P>

1. Safety<P>

Security
Fire
Medical
Other Hazards

2.Heating\Ventilating\Air-Conditioning (HVAC)<P>

3. Lighting<P>

4. Other<P>

SYSTEMS
1. Central Coordinating Units (CCUs)<P>

Switches
Power Line Carriers
Phone Line Carriers
Computers
Modular Plugs<P>

2. Communications Media (media)<P>

Conventional Wire ~ Cable
Fiber Optic Cable
Wireless<P>

3. Sensors<P>

4. Other System Components (OSC)<P>

Devices and Systems are then discussed in their own sections
following the product overview.<P>

Technology and Marketing are also discussed in other sections as
appropriate.<P>

The APPENDIX outlines the real estate or building industry defining
the roles of various types of players, such as builders,
developers, etc.<P>

METHODOLOGY Forecast methods include standard statistical methods
such as analyzing trends, ratios, and growth rates. The final
forecasts represent an integration of numerical results, review of
the literature, and comments made during the interviews.<P>

Because this study will be released very early in 1990, it was
thought appropriate to estimate 1989 values. Thus, 1989 is the base
year. 1988 data are included because that is the last year for
which "solid data" are now available. The computations for the
compound average rate of annual growth (noted in the tables as
"AAGR") are figured from 1989. The forecast years are 1991 and
1995. The backcast year is 1985 which was the first year for
significant activity in intelligent buildings. Also, in the
industry structure section 1988 revenue figures are used because
1989 data were not available when work was completed.<P>

The data are measured in terms of current dollars -- that is,
unadjusted for any inflation or deflation. The data are also
"shipments" which refers to the value of the products as they leave
the factory. Shipments should give the reader a clearer picture of
how much is actually being produced. Costs such as transportation,
marketing, etc. are included in "sales" figures which are not in
this report. That difference can be considerable, especially for
those buying retail.<P>

Important to these forecasts are a series of ratios relating
dollars of building construction expenditures to dollars of ABCS
shipped. This is discussed in the section on environmental factors
and is referred to.several other times.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

* Standard U.S. Government data on GNP, prices, population, and
construction<P>

* Company literature, especially annual reports, lOKs, & product
information<P>

* Business publications, notably the The Wall Street Journal &
Business Week<P>

* The daily press, particularly The New York Times & USA Today<P>

* Trade publications, such as Sensors, Telephony, & Buildings<P>

* Phone & personal-interviews with: manufacturers of ABCS,
architects & engineers, builders, realtors, developers, authors,
and The Intelligent Building Institute. Many of the interviews
included: (l) open-ended questions. Some particularly striking--not
necessarily nice--quotes are used, especially when they epitomize
views repeated in a somewhat subtler fashion. (2) The probing of
answers which appeared to contradict statements from other sources.<P>

* A "shopping trip" was made to outlets such as Sears, Radio Shack,
and Zenith (now Bull's Heathkit). The salespersons were not aware
that the conversations they were conducting were interviews for
this study. The purpose was to find out what a typical person who
had heard of "smart homes" and other high-tech building management
products might encounter.<P>

* Sensors's "Expo" was visited as an additional source of
information.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The project manager has written studies for BCC on the following
industries:<P>

* Intelligent Buildings
* Security Systems
* Insulated Wire & Cable

Other related BCC studies include.<P>

