<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-100R SMART CARDS
A Technical Marketing Analysis
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-100R SMART CARDS
A Technical Marketing Analysis</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>FRANCIS DUFFY, Jr.</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

By the year 2000, the installation base of smart cards and
readers in the U.S. will have a dollar volume of $3.38 billion.
The goal of this study is to present a comprehensive analysis of
the smart-card industry of the 1990s, its structure, market
dynamics, technologies and customer bases, and to examine
exactly how today's $75.23 million embryonic marketplace will
experience rapid growth in the 1990s.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

*  This study presents a thorough but succinct review of all
major smart card applications up and running in the U.S. as of
1990, as well as a synopsis of major activity worldwide.<P>

*  A census conducted by BCC especially for this study pinpoints
quantitatively the actual number of smart cards in the U.S. in
circulation circa 1990.<P>

*  New strategic directions have been charted by smart-card
makers since VISA's decision against smart card deployment. This
study identifies and explains what these strategic directions
are and how they will be implemented.<P>

*  Even though the industry is still in its infancy, a number of
major competitors are vying today for significant market shares.
This study highlights the efforts to date in this regard by
AT&T, Data Card, Micro Card Technologies, Schlumberger, Smart
Card International and others.<P>

*  Smart cards involve not one but three major advanced card
technologies.  A layman's technical overview of each is
presented along with product descriptions.<P>

*  Intel Corp. expects to bring to market a semiconductor chip
with one hundred million transistors on it by the year 2000.
This study outlines the probable course of future technological
change and its impact on the smart card.<P>

*  Cost-pricing data and projections are made in the study for
1990, 1995 and 2000 for all major smart card types and their
accompanying readers.<P>

*  No less than 15 separate market segments await significant
smart card penetration.  Several of these segments will be
"megamarkets" involving hundreds of millions of cards and
millions of card readers. This study catalogues each of these
market opportunities and presents concrete quantitative data
about the potential card universe of each.<P>

*  Likely card and reader populations for each segment are
forecast for 1995 and 2000. Financial projections of the dollar
volume of cards and readers for each segment are also made.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

The U.S. smart-card industry in its entirety, past, present and
future, is detailed and analyzed in one volume.  This study is
thus an invaluable aid to market researchers, strategic and
information systems planners, industry analysts and consultants,
and executives at major smart card concerns.<P>

It can provide invaluable information and capacity-utilization
projections for  plastic card and electronic terminal
manufacturers, banks, transaction processors, telecommunications
networks and other satellites of the mag stripe and smart card
industries.<P>


<B>SCOPE, FORMAT AND METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This BCC study surveys every major aspect of smart card
deployment in the U.S., such as reasons for its delay, present
card populations, major market segments of promise, product
positioning by smart-card makers, likely scenarios of rapid
growth that will make small niches today mass markets by the
turn of the century, and quantitative capacity projections and
financial forecasts.<P>

As a study, this volume is divided into three parts.  In the
first, an in-depth examination of the U.S. smart card industry
today and major worldwide activity is presented.  In the second,
market structure and competitive factors are analyzed and
profiles of market leaders are presented along with a simplified
technical explanation of cards and readers.  In the third, every
promising market segment is carefully evaluated as to its
potential card population, and specific projections are made of
card and reader populations and their dollar volumes in 1995 and
2000.<P>

This study's methodology is straightforward.  It outlines the
conceptual underpinnings to present-day smart-card marketers,
outlooks and strategies, the exact nature of current products
and services, the likely ways card populations will finally
achieve the critical mass necessary to promote major growth, and
the
end-result of this growth in terms of market development and
financial return.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Preparation for this study entailed an exhaustive search of
secondary source materials, in-depth review and synthesis of the
proceedings of major smart card industry conferences, and the
knowledgeable input of executives of major smart card
manufacturing concerns and end-user companies and organizations.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK</B><P>

This study is BCC's fourth major survey in the card technology
and electronic banking fields published in the last three years
along with an impressive list of publications in the
electronics, computer and telecommunications fields.<P>



<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
