<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-117 NEURAL NETWORKS, NEUROCOMPUTERS & BEYOND:
A Technical Marketing Analysis
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> G-117 NEURAL NETWORKS, NEUROCOMPUTERS & BEYOND:
A Technical Marketing Analysis</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Cort Wrotnowski</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>
INTRODUCTION

The goal of this report is to provide the most detailed and comprehensive study
ever of neuroengineering and its commercial potential.  The objectives include
a thorough coverage of the underlying technological issues of the developing
hardware and software tools of neuroengineering as well as assessments of
newand potential products.<P>

Thus, another important objective is to provide realistic market data on the
product areas for which the future neuroengineering products are expected.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The main reason for doing the study is that in the last two years there has
been a sudden growth of interest in the applications of neural network models
and neurocomputers.  The surprisingly broad interest among scientists and
engineers in different disciplines matches the equally surprising breadth and
depth of possible commercial applications of this technology.<P>

Furthermore, there has been a rapid increase in the number ofplayers, as well
as the areas they are investigating.  While many observers say that it is too
early to predict whether or not the first generation products will be
commercially successful beyond the R&D market, there are indications that, in
some applications, they are  successful beyond all expectations.<P>

Among the claimed advantages of neural networks and neurocomputers over
conventional forms of computation are demonstrations of adaptiveness, learning,
associative memory, optimization and classification of information. The
more interesting claims are for systems that can do all this without the aid of
a human intermediary.  Just by providing a neural network model with examples
of the problem situation, and training the model through repeated trials with
the information, it forms a matching pattern of the information and its
relations. Then, the neural network models are able to respond to
new information by either matching it in specified ways to the earlier
information or creating new categories to accommodate uniquely new information.<P>

By repetition of new and old information, a neural network model is then able
to adapt and perform an appropriate response to the information, whether it be
to move a robot arm to a unique position, find a subtle pattern in financial
trading data, or to distinguish between different images of a person.  These
more complex forms of information processing portend a role for computers quite
unlike that which has been envisioned for conventional computers. And, that is
part of why there is so much excitement.  While a number of researchers do not
like to openly admit it, there is the feeling among some in the community that
neural network models and neurocomputers are one step closer to creating an
artificial mind.  The shortcomings and disappointments with artificial
intelligence have tempered researchers expectations.  But, still, some
find these new demonstrations getting uncomfortably close to mimicking capabilities
that define human beings.<P>

It is interesting to note that some financial houses and individual investors
are  purportedly already realizing small and growing fortunes in stock and
commodity trading (there is supposedly more success with commodities than with
stocks), in sports forecasting, and other areas involving assessment
of uncertain and changing environments.  It appears that in just such
complex environments even the current types of neuroengineering products seems
to thrive.<P>

The study investigates the claims that neural networks and neurocomputers are
purportedly better than more conventional kinds of software and hardware.  The
study assesses the commercial implications for suppliers as well as end-users.
This includes an analysis of the types of applications that have been mentioned
above, along with consideration of the significance of adaptiveness, learning,
and other features.  This includes addressing such questions as:  In what ways
can adaptive properties be put to use?  What kinds of learning do neural network
models address?  How extensively can they be used in control systems, data
analysis, pattern recognition, and other applications?  What are the likely
markets that could result? How will they affect other markets?<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of the report is comprehensive.  It covers the many issues concerning
the merits and future prospects of neuroengineering.  It covers the technology
as well as the applications that are under development and discussion.
It covers the hardware development issues that so many regard as critical to the
development of a neuroengineering industry.  The report discusses the prospects
for suggested applications, and projects the likely size and growth of the
markets that will probably result.  There is also extensive analysis of the
marketshares of suppliers, along with sales projections that are segmented in a
variety of ways.<P>

The start-up firms are discussed in terms of their products,their services,
their strengths and their weaknesses.  The role of the major corporations are
considered as well.<P>

The report also looks at the varieties of basic research, product development
and commercialization that are  going on in universities, and government both
in the US and abroad. Competitive aspects are discussed, including the
activities of Japanese firms that are getting involved in neuroengineering.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study provides the most complete accounting of the ongoing developments in
neural networks and neurocomputing.  It provides the most thorough and up-date
assessment to be found anywhere on the subject.  No other study has as complete
a listing of applications that are under development or that have
beensuggested.

The study also provides extensive quantification of many important facets of
the market developments for neuroengineering. This, in turn, contributes to
determining what kinds of strategies firms need to adopt in order to compete in
this emerging marketplace.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

We first conducted an exhaustive search for the literature on neural networks
and neurocomputing. Secondary sources included trade literature, databases, and
various government sources. Then, there were over 150 formal and informal
interviews, and discussions with leading researchers, graduate
students, government officials, presidents of start-up firms, as well as their
associates, end-users, various suppliers, analysts, venture capitalists, life
scientists, computer scientists, engineers, mathematicians, and many others.
the range of interviews and discussions reflected the breadth and depth of
neuroengineering in its combined use of neurobiology, design in
computer architectures, and abstract conceptual models as well as otherareas.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK</B><P>

Many of the studies from the Electronics Group are related to this study on
neuroengineering.  Supercomputers, the software industry, the artificial
intelligence marketplace, voice recognition and synthesis technology, and a
number of other studies, provide important information.<P>


