<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-124  MICROSENSORS FABRICATION AND APPLICATIONS:
A Technical/Marketing Analysis
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> G-124  MICROSENSORS FABRICATION AND APPLICATIONS:
A Technical/Marketing Analysis</H2>

<HR><P>
<I>ANAND V RAO</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Our goal in conducting this study was to determine the impact of
micromachining technology in the manufacture of microsensors and
the market potential for the various types microsensor
applications.<P>

While other studies focus on the market potential for sensors, we
felt that there was a need to address the business implications
that micromachining technology has on solid state silicon sensors.
We believe that this is the only study that relates various
micromachining techniques, to  several types of silicon sensors
used in end-user applications.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

It is common knowledge in the industry that silicon sensors are
making a large headway in various industrial and other
applications.  However, we found that very little information
exists on how developments in micromachining techniques affect
silicon sensors application by the type of variables they measure
in various industries.  The impact of developments in
micromachining techniques will continue to be felt far beyond the
integrated chip manufacturing or silicon sensors industry.  These
developments will influence  testing and measuring applications in
several industries.<P>

BCC decided to examine major trends in micromachining technology on
the type of silicon sensors that are produced and how they are used
in several end-user applications, as well as present projections on
market opportunities and growth potential in each type of industry.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS TO THIS STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

A number of sources from several industrial, academic, research,
business and other fields were researched for this study.  We have
analyzed available information from various sources and matched it
with interviews with several industry experts.  Additionally,
available information from industry associations, federal agencies, trade and technical
journals has been matched with trends in the industry and with
other factors that influence the opportunities in the trade.<P>

This study covers the use of micromachining technology in producing
silicon sensors in aerospace, process control, medical, industrial
automation, medical and consumer applications.  This study is aimed
at manufacturers of silicon manufacturing equipment (SME),
manufactures of silicon sensors/transducers/transmitters, Original
Equipment Manufacturers (OEM) who use silicon sensors in various
testing and measuring equipment, investors, bankers and others who
are directly or indirectly involved with the industry.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study covers all major sectors of the micromachining and
sensors industry.  BCC analyzes each segment, discusses the current
status of the technology, examines the influences that developments
in the micromachining industry will have on each end-user segment
that uses the products and on the OEM market that forms the largest
component of the business.<P>

We have taken care to examine those aspects that directly affect
the industry as a result of developments in  micromachining
technology and have presented a realistic assessment of the
opportunities that are likely to arise in each industry.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis, by each technology/industry segment, of
the current status in that segment, potential impact of the
development of micromachining technology, and projections of a
number of variables that are expected to influence the industry for
the next five years.<P>

We present the volume of potential growth, where applicable, in
dollars and quantities for each industry.  Each projection made was
based on current industry statistics, opinions from industry
experts, and analysis of information made available from  several
industry sources.  Where applicable we have taken a general average of the projections
provided by various industry sources and have matched them with the
volume of current business reported from federal and trade
agencies.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC surveyed approximately 100 sources to obtain data for this
study. These included manufacturers of semiconductor manufacturing
equipment, manufacturers of sensors, end-users in various
industries, experts in federal and other agencies, consultants and
other relevant sources.<P>


