<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-129 PC LAN CONNECTIVITY TECHNOLOGY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-129 PC LAN CONNECTIVITY TECHNOLOGY</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ANAND RAO</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Our goal in conducting this study is to evaluate the results of the
current trends in LAN connectivity technology and make projections on the
market potentials for LAN connectivity products in light of increasing use
of personal computers in the work place.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study was undertaken to measure the relative growth prospects and
cross influences that fiber optics and traditional LAN media have on each
other.  The researchers were made aware of the conflicting and
contradictory information currently being generated in the industry about
the projected effects of FDDI on the LAN connectivity market.  Some
industry experts have painted a rosy picture of high growth for LAN
connectivity technology in general and FDDI in particular.  Our goal for
this study was to evaluate the "real" markets and the "real" growth
potential, and to estimate realistic projections while eliminating gross
over-projections.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION FOR THIS STUDY AND FROM WHOM</B><P>

This study is based on information carefully generated from interviews
with industry experts, data excerpted from replies to the questionnaires
mailed to industry experts and other informed individuals, and analysis
of a wide variety of information generated by the industry press and
technology journals.  Additionally, select industry experts were
approached more than once to clarify several related issues.<P>

Information was generated from vendors as well as users and matched to
produce a "the availability vs need" scenario.  Furthermore, a consensus
was developed to eliminate the most nagging problem facing the industry -
 the definition of a PC LAN.  A definition of an average LAN was created
from the various definitions that are floating around in the industry.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study covers the major products and systems that influence the PC LAN
connectivity markets.  Each segment is analyzed, focussing on the current
state of the technology, major trends that influence the sales of the
product group, and marketing methods, along with a brief overview of the
technology. </B><P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis, by each major technology/product group segment,
focussing on both hardware, software and the media that make up the PC LAN
industry.  The projections for each sector focus on the current and per-
year growth during the next five years.<P>

Where applicable, the volume of growth is presented in dollars and
quantities.  Each projection was based on current industry statistics,
opinions from industry experts, and analysis of information available from
several industry sources.<P>

Where applicable we have taken a general average of the projections
provided by various industry sources and have matched them with the volume
of current business reported from federal and trade agencies.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC has surveyed over 100 sources to obtain data for this study.  These
included the manufacturers of LAN systems, hardware, software, media and
consultants.  Major industry publications, reports from the Department of
Commerce and other federal agencies, industry associations and major
financial publications were also consulted.<P>

PC LAN technology, while being relatively young, is undergoing tremendous
changes.  These changes have been generated by the overall improvements
in PC, network, software technologies and by user demands.  Taking
advantage of the developments in the network technology, especially the
techniques that enable speedier transmission of data, the PC LAN industry
has managed to match it with the overall developments in PC technology -
such as increased memory and faster processing in each PC.<P>

This combination has enabled PC LAN developers to provide data access and
transmission facilities and sophisticated applications, processing, etc.,
that were hitherto confined to mainframe and mini computers.  And PC LAN
has additional advantages - cheaper installation and management costs,
portability, ease of use, and easier to manage technology.<P>

The business and industrial users have started a gradual shift  towards
PC-based data processing facilities by downsizing their mainframe and mini
computing systems.  This has naturally given an impetus to the growth of
PC-based LAN systems.<P>

To this end the world-wide LAN market is now at an impressive
$6.53 billion.  By 1995, the market is expected to reach a level of $12.02
billion - a reflection of an 16.5 per cent average annual growth rate.
Most of this will be due to the large number of non-fiber optic LANS which
are expected to grow from a $5.66 billion level to $10.09 billion in 1995.<P>
Fiber optic LANs which are now at an $865 million level and which
represent 13.2 per cent of total LAN sales will reach $1.92 bilion in
1995, at which time they will account for 16.0 per cent of the total LAN
sales.<P>

The U.S. accounts for close to 60 per cent of the total LAN market.  This
report finds developments in PC LAN technology in various applications as
follows:<P>

<B>PC LAN MARKETS SHOW HEALTHY GROWTH TRENDS</B><P>

The demand for PC LANs will show healthy growth trends between 1991 and
1995.  The worldwide revenues from PC LANS will increase from $6.53
billion in 1991 to $12.02 billion in 1995, registering an aggregate growth
of 18.40 per cent per year.   The growth will be fuelled by an increasing
move towards downsizing, connecting more and more end-users to databases
through LANS and an overall increase in the use of PCs in work places.
Hardware will account for two-thirds of the revenues followed by software
and media.<P>


<B>NON-FIBER PC LANS STILL DOMINATE THE MARKET</B><P>

PC LANS that are supported by non-fiber media, such as copper
wire and co-ax still dominate the markets.  Their position is being
challenged by fiber optic-based PC LANS.  However, the large installed
base of non-fiber optic LANs will not be easy to dislodge in the
foreseeable future.   The revenues from non-fiber optic PC LANS will
account for $5.66 billion in 1991 and will increase to
$10.09 billion in 1995 registering an aggregate annual growth of 15.66 per
cent.  The demand for copper-wire based PC LANS will be higher than the
demand for co-ax supported systems.<P>


<B>FIBER OPTIC PC LANS: ENJOYING INCREASING MARKET SHARE</B><P>

While the use of fiber optic media is increasing in wide area networks and
telecommunication links, as yet, it is not replacing traditional media in
PC based LAN systems in large numbers.  This is due to the high cost of
the fiber optic cables and installations.  The current worldwide revenues
from fiber optic PC LANs is around $865 million and is expected to grow
to $1.92 billion by 1995, registering an annual aggregate increase of
22.20 per cent.  While other industry sources project much higher
aggregate growth, we believe such optimistic growth rates cannot be
maintained due to the current recession, overall cost-cutting and other
factors.<P>


<B>NUMBER OF NON-FIBER OPTIC LANS: CONTINUING TO INCREASE</B><P>

The installed base of twisted copper wire and co-ax based PC LANs will
continue to increase despite a strong challenge from fiber optic-based PC
LANS.  As explained earlier, the traditional LANs still enjoy cost
advantages; the benefits offered by fiber optic based LANS cannot be
utilized by all users.  The number of traditional PC LANs installed in
1991 will be around 648,020 and will increase to 877,653 by 1995.  These
estimates include complete LAN systems that incorporate servers, primary
and secondary nodes.<P>


<B>THE MARKETS FOR PC LAN MEDIA: CONTINUE TO SHOW HEALTHY GROWTH TRENDS</B><P>

The media used in PC LANS is difficult to isolate as some PC LANS are
connected through WAN facilities.  By limiting the media to the segment
used within a building to connect nodes to servers, the demand for media
can be quantified to a considerable degree of accuracy.  The demand for
all types of media used in PC LANS will grow to $328 million during 1991
and will reach $527 million by 1995, registering an annual aggregate
increase of 12.79 per cent during the period.  This includes twisted
copper-wire, co-ax and fiber optic media.<P>



<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
