<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-136  FIBER OPTICS TECHNOLOGY:
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-136  FIBER OPTICS TECHNOLOGY:</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ANAND V. RAO</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Our goal in conducting this study is to evaluate the market
potential for the use of fiber optic cables and products in the
United States and principal countries in Europe and Asia.  This
report focuses on the use of fiber optic cables and products in the
telecommunications industry, which accounts for over 90 per cent of
the market.  Our objective is to highlight main areas of usage,
volume, and value of cables and products used in major
applications.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study was undertaken to measure the relative growth prospects
and cross influences that the fiber optics and telecommunications
industries have on each other.  While some reports currently
available cover "some areas" of the industry, we believe that this
study includes a comprehensive coverage of the major sectors of the
industry in the U.S.A. and abroad.  Additionally, it includes
export prospects for fiber optic products from the U.S.A. to
principal markets outside the country.<P>

This study also analyzes markets in the U.S.A., some countries of
Europe and East Asia by application, products and fiber optic
cables.<P>

The researchers were made aware of the conflicting and contradi-
ctory information currently being generated in the industry about
the projected efficacy of fiber optics in telecommunication
applications. Some industry experts have projected very high growth
rates for fiber optics in all aspects of telecommunications.   Our
goal for this study was to evaluate the "real" growth potential for
fiber optic applications in telecommunications and arrive at
realistic projections.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THIS STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study is based on detailed information generated from
interviews with vendors, users, consultants and other industry
experts.  Additionally, a variety of published information from
governmental, trade press, associations, research organizations and
other sources were analyzed.  Over 300 vendors from around the
world were approached for detailed information on their activities,
and the data generated was carefully analyzed.<P>

Information generated from various sources was matched to produce
an "actual deployment vs projected use" scenario.  Furthermore, a
consensus was developed to eliminate the most vexing problem facing
the industry--whether fiber optics is actually cost effective. A
median cost cross-over ratio was developed to arrive at a
reasonable deployment scenario.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study covers the major products and cable types that are used
in fiber optic systems in telecommunication applications.  The
analysis focuses on the end-user market applications as well as
select products that are used in the industry.  Each segment is
analyzed, focusing on the current state of the technology and
deployment, major trends that influence the sales of the product,
and marketing systems.  A brief overview of the technology is
presented where appropriate.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis, by each major technology/product group
segment, focussing on the components and cable systems.  The
projections for each product and application evaluates the current
and per-year growth during the next five years.<P>

Where applicable, the volume of growth is presented in dollars,
fiber-kilometers and units.  Each projection was based on current
industry statistics, opinions from industry experts, and analysis
available from several reliable sources.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC has surveyed over 300 sources to obtain data for this study.
These included manufacturers of fibers, cables and a variety of
components, users, consultants and other industry experts.  Major
industry publications, reports from the Department of Commerce, the
Federal Communications Commission, Bureau of Census, various
associations, and financial publications were also consulted.<P>


