<CENTER><H2>G-152: PCMCIA TECHNOLOGY:IMPRESSIVE GROWTH THROUGH 2000, 
UNCERTAINTY BEYOND 
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Marc Favreau
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Over the last several years PCMCIA, an acronym for the Personal Computer Memory
Card International Association, has become a buzzword in the mobile computing
industry.  The Association is a standards and special interest group devoted to
developing the nonproprietary PCMCIA/PC card technology as well as the Card's
potential market.  Aside from the most seasoned portable computer users and the
industry itself, PCMCIA still remains somewhat of a mystery.  However, 
indications are that this is changing, and the PCMCIA/PC Card will soon become 
as commonplace as the floppy disk or compact disk.<P> 

This BCC report presents a detailed analysis of the current and
future markets for the large variety of PCMCIA/PC Card applications, from
communication to data storage cards as well as data acquisition and global 
positioning cards.  The study also addresses the impact on the personal 
computer industry.  Market forecasts are presented that project sales to the 
year 2000.  In addition, a short discussion is presented indicating the 
possible future for the various markets into the early 21st century.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The study is presented at this time because of the rapid development of the 
mobile computing market.  This market is being strongly influenced and 
facilitated by the credit card sized PCMCIA/PC Card, which can provide truly 
mobile solutions to the mobile computer user.<P>  

Until recently, factors such as high costs, large size, high power consumption,
proprietary systems, and poor capability have kept much needed computer 
peripheral equipment out of the hands of mobile computer users.  In addition, 
many of the same problems coupled with operational and interoperational 
problems held the promising PCMCIA/PC Card market at bay as well.  However, 
diligent work by the PCMCIA has at last resolved most of the major issues and 
created new opportunities for card designers.<P>

Current trends indicate that 
the PCMCIA/PC Card interface will take its place as the peripheral and upgrade 
solution of choice across all computer lines well into the 21st century.  
There are also strong indications that the form factor will spread to 
virtually every corner of the electronics market, from automobiles to 
television.<P> 
       

<b>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

PCMCIA/PC Cards are a small but rapidly growing segment of the overall computer
industry.  A great deal of activity is concentrated in the development of the 
materials, components, and methods required to successfully implement the 
large variety of card applications.<P> 

This report provides an analysis of the complete PCMCIA/PC Card industry and
markets, by card function and end use, through the year 2000.  The structure 
of the industry is discussed, and company profiles of the major players in 
each of the industry's segments are presented.  The report is directed to 
decision makers in the PCMCIA/PC Card as well as the related electronics 
packaging and materials industries and markets.  They are:<P> 

<UL       Card application designers<BR>
       Electronic material suppliers<BR>
       Integrated circuit and other component suppliers<BR>
       Printed circuit board suppliers<BR>
       Equipment manufacturers<BR>
       Marketplace managers<BR>
       Merger, acquisition, and investment executives</UL><P>


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report is an analytical business tool whose primary purpose is to cover the
emerging PCMCIA/PC Card industry in terms of application and end use markets. 
A summary follows this introductory section and is followed immediately by an
overview of the history of the card and the development of the market.  The 
ensuing segments are analyses of the current and future market trends.<P>  

The final segments address the industry's structure, analysis of the card's 
impact on electronic packaging, and a patent analysis which addresses the 
areas of high patent activity as they pertain to PCMCIA/PC Cards. 

The appendices include not only directories of pertinent associations and 
conferences, but also the most extensive directory of PCMCIA/PC Card related 
vendors and manufacturers available with close to 450 entries.<P> 


<b>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The material presented is based on  information gathered from personal 
contacts with participants within the PCMCIA/PC Card industry as well as a 
thorough review of the technology gathered from technical papers and industry 
conferences.  Our final analyses and projections are based on a combination of 
a consensus among the primary contacts combined with our understanding of the 
impact of trends from a historical perspective.<P> 

Additional data was obtained from extensive reviews of secondary sources such as
trade publications, trade associations, company literature, and on-line 
databases. This was done to supplement our understanding of applications, 
markets, and trends in the PCMCIA/PC Card industry as well as the closely 
related personal computer industry.  All dollar projections presented in this 
report are in 1995 constant dollars.<P> 


<b>RELATED BCC RESEARCH CREDENTIALS</B><P>

BCC has been a leader in market research and consulting to the electronics and
materials industries since 1971.  Over the last several years, BCC has 
produced in-depth analyses of technologies and business opportunities in 
materials and components for advanced computer systems, such as thick and thin 
film in microelectronics, electronic integrated circuit and component 
packaging, printed circuit board manufacturing, surface mount technology, 
multichip modules, and deposition technology.  Some reports of interest are:<P> 

 <UL>  G-067-X--Printed Circuit Boards: Markets & Opportunities<P>
        G-118--Surface Mount Technology in Electronics<P>
        GB-121-R--Electronic Ceramics<P>
        GB-128-R--Thick and Thin Films in Microelectronics<P>
        GB-138-R--Multichip Packaging & Bare Chip Systems<P>
        GB-156--Advanced Electronic Packaging Systems Technology
                           through 2000<P>
        GB-160--Magnetic/Opto-Magnetic Storage: Media and 
                        Materials<P></UL> 

Appendix V contains a more complete list of related BCC reports as well as their dates of publication and prices.<P>

