GB-138R  MULTICHIP PACKAGING AND BARE CHIP SYSTEMS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-138R  MULTICHIP PACKAGING AND BARE CHIP SYSTEMS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>BRENT J. KNIPFER
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objective of this BCC study is to ascertain the 1993 standing
of multichip packaging worldwide.  Providing for a standard five-
year planning cycle, estimates are given for 1998.  This study
defines the multichip module in all its variations. It analyzes the
technology options, determines the current applications multichip
modules in which (MCMs) are being shipped, defines and graphically
analyzes MCMs from many perspectives, categorizes and profiles the
companies involved, defines the unique nomenclature, and lists
organizations, conferences, authors, and consortia.<P>

This report is a steering mechanism for its readers so multichip
packaging will be a loss leader or profit maker rather than a
loser, whether MCMs are the company's sole product or one
electronic packaging option.<P>

Multichip modules are to single chip modules what HyperMart is to
WalMart; what Incredible Universe is to Radio Shack; what a
supermarket is to the corner mom and pop market.  How the market
place is understood and marketed to will determine each company's
staying power and success.<P>

<b>REASONS FOR MULTICHIP PACKAGING STUDY</B><P>

The multichip packaging area is dynamic and capital intensive.
Multichip packaging requires the integration of design control over
the whole package.  In this way the bare die, substrate, and
interconnections are integrated together.  The most successful
companies have been vertically integrated, but even these companies
have had to move toward concurrent engineering and strategic
partnering to address the cost of doing business in next generation
electronics.<P>

Electronic packaging must now address more complex mixed-mode
designs that require thermal management, higher performance, faster
response, and smaller size.<P>

Multichip packaging is synergistic.  Designed as part of a complete
system, multichip packaging will give next generation performance
with presently available subsystems of chips, substrates and
interconnects.  To successfully produce a multichip package, a
business concern must pull formerly separate technology avenues
together.<P>

The multichip packaging market is largely undefined and misunderstood.  MCMs are at the heart of many technology changes.  In fact
multichip packaging is at the crossroads of many technologies.
Everyone agrees multichip packaging is the way to achieve the
highest performance and/or density.  IBM has proven that multichip
packaging can leverage the next-level chip integration for applications demanding it sooner than the chip houses can deliver.<P>

The result is a profit-making window unattainable by competition
not using MCM technology.<P>


<b>VALUE OF MULTICHIP PACKAGING STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

In this venue multichip packaging can make anyone mastering it a
technology leader.  The performance level for multichip packaging
has now dropped to the level of the personal computer.  For
example, Austek Microelectronics has a pluggable replacement to
turn the 286 CPU-based computer into a 486 CPU-based state-of-the-art personal computer.  The result is cost savings to the customer
and profit for the company using MCMs as a solution.<P>

From personal to super-computers, every sector of electronics will
begin using MCMs.  For some applications it will be a viable or
competitive option to other packaging methods; in other application
areas MCMs will be the required packaging technology to survive in
the marketplace.<P>

This BCC report contributes to the advancement of the developing
MCM industry.  The MCM marketplace is dynamic and subject to over-
and underestimation.  The reader will find herein a conservative,
fact-based analysis of multichip modules as an electronic package
from 1993 through 1998.<P>

<b>MARKETING MANAGERS</B><P>

Marketing managers will use this report to assess the competition
and identify customers.<P>

<b>MANAGEMENT CONSULTANTS</B><P>

Management consultants will determine whether companies divest or
invest in MCM technology based, in part, on the market projections
and competition strengths revealed in this report.<P>

<b>EQUIPMENT MANUFACTURERS</B><P>

Equipment manufacturers will develop or modify existing products to
address MCM manufacturing concerns that are emphasized in this
report.<P>

<b>MATERIALS SUPPPLIERS</B><P>

Materials suppliers will implement beta programs with key companies
to strategically place themselves early in the MCM development
cycle, based on the applications projected for growth or high
profit margin found in this report.<P>


<b>VENTURE CAPITAL MANAGERS</B><P>

Venture capital managers will identify target companies for investment, merger, or acquisition from those identified and described in
this report.<P>

<b>STRATEGIC PLANNERS</B><P>

Strategic planners will identify other companies with critical
strengths to strategically partner with so they can share in
overall MCM market growth projected in this report.<P>

<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This BCC business opportunity report covers with a critical eye the
multichip module marketplace as it really exists.  Future projections take into account actual market growth based on company
revenues and as part of the overall electronic industry.<P>

The format is provided in easy to follow sections that overview the
subject, define the technology, segment the market by manufacturing
technology, method, application and region, profile the companies,
define the terminology, and identify the technical community.<P>

This BCC report is a one-stop source for serious players in the
emerging multichip module industry.<P>

<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Material and data presented in this report were obtained from
personal interviews at the 1993 International Conference and
Exhibition on Multichip Modules, telephone interviews of marketing
and engineering personnel at a majority of the companies profiled,
catalogs obtained from the companies, and a literature search of
1993 articles on MCMs from around the world.<P>

<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Specific sources of multichip module information include the
International Society of Hybrid Microelectronics, authors of
technical papers, company advertisements and technical periodicals.<P>

Competitive marketing reports were considered where applicable.<P>

<b>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

Since 1971 BCC has been a leader in market research and consulting
to the electronics and materials industries.  Over the past six
years, BCC has conducted in-depth analyses of technologies and
business opportunities in materials and components for advanced
computer systems; thick and thin film in micro-electronics,
electronic integrated circuit and component packaging; the printed
circuit board industry; surface mount technology; deposition
technology for micro-electronics, and now a second report on
multichip modules.  The following reports are available from BCC:<P>

<UL>GB-064N   Piezoelectric Materials<BR>
GB-128R   Thick and Thin Films in Microelectronics<BR>
GB-160 Magnetic/Opto-Magnetic Storage: Media and Materials<BR>
GB-156 Advanced Electronic Packaging Systems Technology Through
2000<BR>
GB-148 Electronic Connector Materials<BR>
GB-121 Electronic Ceramics in the 1990s<BR>
GB 154 Smart Materials: A Technology Assessment<P></UL>

Also available from BCC are monthly newsletters that cover
electronic materials and related subject matter.<P>

Electronic Materials Technology News covers new materials and
specialty chemicals.  Each month, this newsletter brings you timely
analyses of new products, patent and industry trends in this major
new market for the chemicals and materials industries.  Manufacturers, materials suppliers and end users will all benefit from late-breaking news in the rapidly evolving electronics materials
industry.<P>

Surface Modification Technology News reports on the rapidly
evolving advanced engineered surface materials industry covering
the processes, substrates, materials, and characteristics in all
the industries involved--chemicals, processing, polymers, electronics, tooling, metal working, optical, biotechnology, materials,
separations and analytical.<P>

Diamond and Structural Carbon News keeps you up-to-date on crucial
information on: trends in materials, technology, systems, concepts;
who is making, buying, testing and using what; international
developments; industry analysis, including business & economic
trends; patents; mergers, acquisitions; joint ventures; new
applications and contracts; and a wealth of other salient news.<P>

Optical Materials & Engineering News will keep you informed on
who's doing what, mergers, acquisitions, joint ventures, developing
technology, business and economic trends, patents, new applica-
tions, contracts, and a wealth of other salient information.  This
newsletter is the synthesis of insider news from a fragmented industry.<P>

High-Tech Ceramic News discusses materials, products and processes
in electronics, automotive, cutting tools, superconductors,
membranes, filters, piezoelectrics, heat exchangers, coating, wear
parts, and armor reinforcements.  Readers are kept up-to-date on
product descriptions, evaluations, and comparisons; company
activities and industry restructuring; who is making, buying,
testing and using what; developments in Europe, Japan and developing countries; and supply and demand for new materials and
chemicals.<P>

Another BCC information product is Patent Reviews and Analysis.
This new BCC product provides relevant worldwide patent information, organized and analyzed in numerous helpful formats.  Each
patent report represents a ten-year search with year-by-year
quantitative counts, geographic analysis of patent ownership
reflecting global R&D activities and an assessment of technological
trends.<P>

