<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-148  ELECTRONIC CONNECTOR MATERIALS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-148  ELECTRONIC CONNECTOR MATERIALS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>KARYN L. THOMAS</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This study provides a comprehensive assessment of the market
for electronic connector materials as well as an analysis of
the connector industry, its end-use markets, foreign trade
and the connector industry's changing structure.  It provides
a concise look at the individual types of connectors, the
types of materials they use and the future for each connector
type.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING STUDY</B><P>

Electronic connector materials represent an important
industry, both economically and strategically.  Although many
of the materials that are used by the industry find other
end-uses, many have been designed specifically for the
connector industry.  Over the past decade, major changes have
taken place in the connector industry, both technologically
and structurally.  These changes are impacting material
producers in a major way.  With years of effort developing
technologically advanced materials at stake, the time has
come to take a hard look at these changes and how they will
impact the future of electronic connector materials.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study provides a detailed look at the competitive
materials used in the electronic connector market.  It also
examines which materials are noncompetitive and what the
future is for those materials.  By examining each specific
connector type and its end-uses, it becomes clear where the
market is headed for the different connector materials.
Whether you produce ceramic ferrules, plastics for D-
subminiature military connectors, or high-performance
beryllium copper contact materials, this study will provide a
clear outlook for your market.  If you are a connector
manufacturer, this study provides the latest developments for
the industry with realistic, well-balanced forecasts and
conclusions.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of this report is extensive and includes:<P>

<MENU><LI>Connector shipments by type<P>

<LI>Connector end-use markets by type<P>

<LI>Connector imports/exports - plus a worldwide overview of theconnector industry<P>

<LI>Connector materials shipments, including plastics, contactmaterials, ceramics, composites and others<P>

<LI>An examination of the electronic connector industry structure and its trends<P>

<LI>Electronic connector and material company profiles</MENU><P>


All the individual electronic connector types are examined
and detailed in terms of applications, end-use markets and
types of materials used.  All the various connector types,
including rectangular, circular, coaxial, printed circuit
board (PCB), planar, hermetically sealed, fiber optic,
special purpose, connector parts and IC sockets are covered.<P>


The five major connector end-use markets are discussed,
including transportation, communications, military, computer
and others.  Shifts in market share and new end-uses are also
analyzed.  Particular attention is given to the all-important
military market and its impact on the connector industry.<P>

The section on foreign trade provides an overview of some of
the most compelling factors in the connector market -
offshore manufacturing, offshore sourcing and
imports/exports.<P>

Over one-third of the study is dedicated to connector
materials and all the factors shaping and changing the
market. Surface mount technology (SMT), high pin counts
connector designs, miniaturization, multilayered PCBs and
many others are discussed.  Competitive materials are studied
and analyzed b y performance and costs to the manufacturer.<P>

The electronic connector industry structure entered an era of
consolidation during the 1980s.  Changing needs and demands
from OEMs, overcapacity and intense competition have had a
dramatic impact on the industry.  The study reviews all these
issues and pieces together many of the mergers and
acquisitions over the past five years and their impact.<P>

Following the industry structure, more than 30 company
profiles of leading connector and connector material
producers are presented.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The conclusions of this report were derived through a number
of independent steps.  The first observations were made by
carefully examining the various connector types and the size
of each market.
For the most part Government data were used.  This
information was used partially to formulate the size of the
end-use markets, the second step.  Certain connector types
appear more frequently in some markets than in others.  Of
course, the trends of the products within the end-use markets
served were also carefully examined.  Estimated sales of
major producers to various markets were also weighed.
Interviews of connector industry spokespeople revealed
similar opinions as to the size of various end-use markets.<P>

The third step involved establishing the different types of
materials used in the connector industry.  Each material,
whether it was a plastic or a contact material, was evaluated
in terms of its individual properties and characteristics
vis-a-vis other materials used in similar applications.  The
materials were also evaluated in terms of new applications
and their consequences on market share.  The size of this
market was developed through government data, industry
interviews and by establishing the types of materials used
most frequently by different connector types and then
comparing the data to the size of each market.<P>

The fourth step was to conscientiously examine what
international factors are having an impact on the electronic
connector market.  Foreign trade, offshore manufacturing and
the overall globalization of the industry were studied and
their impact on U.S. world market share. The structure of the
connector industry was examined along the same lines.  The
electronic connector industry structure has undergone
tremendous changes over the past six years.  A shakeout began
in 1985, and subsequently led to an era of consolidation.
Vendor reduction by OEMs, just-in-time (JIT) manufacturing,
application tooling and other factors have also been steadily
creating major industry changes.  Given all these factors,
forecasts were then developed for the connector markets,
products, foreign trade and, finally, the materials.<P>

The data in this study are reported in current dollars. An
average annual inflation rate of 4 to 5 per cent throughout
the decade should be included when evaluating the forecasts.
While this may be low, it reflects the historical trend of
the past decade.<P>

Many elements were considered when examining the economy, its
future recovery and its impact upon the electronic connector
industry.  Issues included the nation's banking industry
problems, the S&L crisis, the Persian Gulf events, the
country's budget deficit, the balance of trade, the upcoming
free market alliances of Europe and the U.S.-Canadian free-
trade policy.  The impact of a free market economy in the
Soviet Union was given some weight, although when or how this
will develop is very questionable.  The relatively strong
performance of the stock market and the fluctuating dollar
were also analyzed.  Current economic indicators still point
to a very slow recovery from the recession; however, with
many companies reporting less than robust third-quarter
earnings, weak housing sales, and still high unemployment
rates.  Given all these factors, only a moderate recovery is
forecast for 1992.  In the longer term, as the economy begins
to pull away from the damning effects of overspending, etc.,
a strong economic turn-around should be well underway by mid-
1993 and will favorably impact the connector industry growth
rate, sending it above the historical rate.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The data for this study were compiled from government
sources, trade associations and extensive interviews of
connector manufacturers and material suppliers.  The U.S.
Department of Commerce was the basis for connector shipment
and import/export data.  Forecasts and market trends were
based on interviews with connector product specialists,
marketing personnel, engineers and others.  Interviews of the
connector material producers were used to estimate shipments
for plastics, contact materials and other materials.
Databases were searched for up-to-date literature, and
related articles were studied.  Along with expert technical
assistance from industry personnel, numerous technical books
on both electronics and materials were used as technical
references.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

<MENU>GB-041U--Powder Metallurgy<BR>

