<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-156  ADVANCED ELECTRONIC PACKAGING SYSTEMS TECHNOLOGY
THROUGH 2000
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-156  ADVANCED ELECTRONIC PACKAGING SYSTEMS TECHNOLOGY
THROUGH 2000
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>JOSEPH CASTROVILLA</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This BCC report describes the technology, processes, materials, and performance
criteria for state-of-the-art electronics packaging with a view toward future trends, in
order to meet the "slim-fast" requirements of higher speeds and densities, smaller size,
and higher heat.

This BCC industry study presents a detailed analysis of current and future
developments in electronic packaging in micro-electronics.  Electronic packaging is the
dynamic process of physically locating, connecting, and protecting electronic
components.  The packaging of today's electronic equipment has become a major
factor in the design and manufacture of the total system.  The major technologies of
multichip modules, tape automated bonding, and chip-on-board for integrated circuits
are analyzed and market forecasts are revealed by individual materials and equipment
application segments from 1992 through the year 2000.  Case studies of technology
applications as well as worldwide materials market size, growth and usage trends
through the years 2000 are featured.  Additionally, leading suppliers and strategic
partnerships are profiled worldwide.  This unique strategic planning tool will show
suppliers to the industry the paths to business opportunity while end-users will
benefit from knowing about the new products, processes, and their suppliers.<P>



<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Until recently, advanced packaging and interconnection systems have been kept from
wider implementation by their high cost, limited supply, lack of standards and testing,
complexity, and lack of an industry infrastructure.  However, the growing demand for
higher performance, faster signal transmission, less energy usage, and ever smaller
systems are breaking down these barriers.  Essentially, three types of interconnection
and packaging are at the leading edge:  tape automated bonding (TAB), chip-on-board
(COB), and multichip modules (MCMs).  These technologies are being devised,
developed and evaluated by the worldwide electronics industry because they offer
solutions to many of the advanced device and electronic packaging challenges relating
to high density, high speed, and high heat of current and future electronic systems.<P>

Significant technological advancements are taking place today, despite the current
worldwide economic recession.<P>

Electronic components with very high functional density and performance
requirements demand unique and innovative approaches which address electrical,
thermal, and mechanical packaging material concerns.  Current indicators show that
electronic semiconductor packaging technology consisting of TAB, COB, and MCM will
be the advanced packaging approached for the 1990s through the 21st century.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This BCC report analyzes worldwide trends in advanced systems, packaging, and
interconnection by type and relationship to electronic industry sectors.  Production
trends are highlighted, with industry consumption by material, device, interconnect,
and electronic equipment applications through the year 2000.  Activities of materials
suppliers, components, and electronic equipment suppliers are profiled.<P>

This BCC study provides a thorough analysis of the electronic packaging and device
market and industry, and then provides a comparison of advanced materials and
processes.  The study discusses the global electronic packaging and materials industry
structure, describing activities of the major suppliers in the U.S., Europe, and Asia.
Worldwide material consumption is tabulated and the market forecasts are provided
by type of material through the year 2000.  Case studies and winning strategies are
presented with an eye to the 21st century.<P>

This report is directed to the following decision-makers who need strategic
information on the electronic packaging and materials industry and its markets:<P>

<UL><LI> electronic material suppliers<BR>

<LI> suppliers of polymers, dielectrics, substrates, and metals<BR>
<LI> suppliers of printed circuit boards<BR>
<LI> electronic and electrical equipment manufacturers<BR>
<LI> merger and acquisition and investment executives<P></UL>



<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This BCC analytical business tool covers the new electronic packaging technologies
in terms of materials, processes, and applications.  The report reveal the emerging
technologies and then make analytical market and industry forecasts that identify
paths to new and profitable business opportunities.  An extensive directory of
suppliers provides a one-stop source for micro-electronic components and material
needs.<P>



<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Data is based on a thorough review and appraisal of electronic packaging and
materials technology, culled through a systematic review of developments through
telephone and in-person interviews and an extensive data base of technical and
marketing sources.<P>

Additional data for this document was obtained from an exhaustive review of technical
papers, and from discussions and in-depth interviews with a representative sample of
vendors, end-users, and trade associations.  All dollar projections in this report are in
1992 constant dollars.<P>



<B>RELATED BCC RESEARCH CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Since 1971, BCC has been a leader in market research and consulting to the
electronics and materials industries.  Over the past five years, BCC has conducted in-
depth analyses of technologies and business opportunities in materials and
components for advanced computer systems; thick and thin film in micro-electronics,
electronic integrated circuit and component packaging; the printed circuit board
industry; surface mount technology; multichip modules; and deposition technology for
micro-electronics.  BCC continues its in-depth analysis with the current volume.  The
following reports are available from BCC:<P>

<UL>C-148     Electronic Imaging Chemical<BR>
          GB-147    Electronic Connectors<BR>
          G-067U    Printed Circuit Board Industry<BR>

          GB-138    Multichip Modules in Electronics<BR>

          GB-104    Tape Automated Bonding (TAB)<BR>

          GB-128    Thick and Thin Film in Electronics<BR>

          G-118     Surface Mount Technology in Electronics<BR>

          GB-121    Electronic Ceramics<P></UL>

Also available from BCC are two monthly newsletters that cover electronics materials and optics:  Electronic Materials Technology News and Optical Materials & Engineering News.<P>

Another BCC information product is Patent Reviews and Analysis.  This new BCC
product provides relevant worldwide patent information, organized and analyzed in
numerous helpful formats.  Each patent report represents a ten-year search with year-
by-year quantitative account, geographic analysis of patent ownership reflecting global
R & D activities and an assessment of technological trends.<P>

