<HTML><HEAD><TITLE> GB-160  MAGNETIC/OPTO-MAGNETIC STORAGE: MEDIA AND MATERIALS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-160  MAGNETIC/OPTO-MAGNETIC STORAGE: MEDIA AND MATERIALS</H2>
<HR><P>
<I>ROBERT MORAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

BCC's goal in conducting this study was to determine the current
worldwide status of the market for magnetic and optical storage
media and materials, and to assess the growth potential over a
five-year period from 1991 to 1996.  We were particularly
interested in the changing composition of storage media brought
about by new technology and the effect on materials consumption.
<P>
Our major objective was to present a comprehensive analysis of the
current magnetic and optical storage media and materials industry
and plot its future course.
<P>
<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

Over the past decade, advances in technology have changed the
structure of computer- and consumer-oriented storage devices and
media.  Disk storage drives have become smaller while storage
capacity has increased.  The compact disk has replaced the
traditional vinyl long-playing record.  The changing use of storage
products has altered the requirements for materials, particularly
in computer and consumer media.<P>

BCC decided to examine the current position of the materials used
in magnetic and optical media.  We were interested in finding out
what kinds of substrates, coatings, and covers are being used to
meet the demands of a changing environment.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B>
<P>
We assembled a study of materials used in three major parts of
storage media: disk and tape substrates, coatings, and protective
covers and devices.  We present a worldwide industry structure,
examine the competitive aspects of the industry, analyze the
current markets, and project shipments for each of the material
categories to 1996.  The study will be of interest to those who
manufacture storage drives, disk and tape media, and the various
materials used in media composition: metals, plastics, glass,
ceramics, magnetic coatings, and thin films.  It will also interest
those who apply coatings.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>
<P>
The scope of our study encompasses the drives used for computer and
consumer storage, the various kinds of storage media, and the
materials consumed in the manufacture of media.  We analyze the
major components of media: substrates, coatings, and covers.  We
also analyze the growth potential of the eight major technologies
used for computer and consumer storage: the hard and floppy disk,
tape, and optical computer storage; and the videotape, audio tape,
compact disk, and videodisk.  We present forecasts to 1996.
Technological issues are reviewed.  Other influential factors, such
as past growth and the effects of the economic climate, are also
discussed.<P>

Because this is a worldwide industry, BCC analyzes the domestic and
international regulatory and standards situations and their impact
on the magnetic and optical storage business.  The economic
environment and its effect on the business is also reviewed.  BCC
presents an analysis of the driving forces within the magnetic and
optical storage industry and looks at the impact of these forces
for the future.<P>

Since this study concerns the computer and consumer electronics
industries, we discuss factors effecting both parts of the
business.  Computer products consumption is discussed separately
from consumer demand.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis of the shipments and value of storage
drives and media by major category.  The value of materials used in
the production of magnetic and optical media is detailed by
function and type.  Our estimated value is what manufacturers and
materials providers have paid in current dollars.  Then, based on
our surveys, we analyze storage applications, calculate an estimate
for growth, and forecast shipments of drives and media and the
value of materials for 1996.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B>
<P>
BCC surveyed approximatey 75 companies to obtain the data for this
report.  Included were manufacturers of disk and tape drives,
videotape equipment, audiotape devices, optical drives and media,
plastic, metals, glass and deposition equipment.  We also included
several trade associations, the U.S. Department of Commerce, and
data from financial and industry sources.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B>
<P>
Several other reports are related to this topic.  They are: G-104R
"Optical Disks: Markets, Technologies, Materials," GB-149A
"Permanent Magnetic Materials," GB-149B "Soft Magnetic Materials"
GB-130 "Chemical Vapor Deposition (CVD): Trends in Technology and
Materials," GB-133 "Physical Vapor Deposition (PVD)," and GB-134
"Ionic and Molecular Surface Modification."<P>

