<HTML><HEAD><TITLE> 
G-185 HOT MARKETS: THERMAL MANAGEMENT TECHNOLOGY FOR ELECTRONICS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="LogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-185 HOT MARKETS: THERMAL MANAGEMENT TECHNOLOGY
FOR ELECTRONICS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>MARC FAVREAU</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Integrated circuit (IC) designers are in full stride.  It seems that every day 
brings an announcement of a new, more highly integrated device touted as the 
future for all the computing and communication devices anyone will ever need.  
The fury with which these devices are being introduced is being matched by 
software and hardware makers alike, whose responsibility it is to keep these 
devices operating regardless of the temperatures they must endure.<P> 

Thus an expansion of the thermal management marketplace was and is inevitable.  
Only a handful of the players involved have recognized its importance and 
moved to capitalize.  For the most part, the expansion is taking place within 
existing market segments. However, in some cases, brand new markets and 
products have arisen.<P> 

This BCC report presents a detailed analysis of the current and future markets 
for the large variety of thermal management products, from heat sink hardware 
design and materials to the future growth of highly conductive substrate 
material.  The study also addresses the potential impact of the latest design 
and fluid dynamics software available for assessing thermal problems. 
Forecasts are presented that project sales and product evolution through the 
year 2001.<P> 




<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The study is presented at this time because of the rapid development of highly 
integrated circuits and modules.  New generations of processors are being 
introduced every 6 to 9 months. Whereas just a few years ago, keeping 
components cool was a relatively simple matter, massive increases in 
integration have complicated the matter.<P> 

Until recently, an optimized IC design revolved around area and performance 
rather than power consumption.  The popularity of portable systems has further 
enhanced the need to design low power chips, not only to ensure that the 
components in these machines can be kept cool, but also to maximize battery 
life.<P>  

Current trends indicate that the markets for virtually all products designed 
for thermal management will continue to grow as the overall electronics 
continues to expand.  In addition, new products and product designs will be 
introduced into the marketplace.<P> 


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

The cooling of electronics is a necessary evil, but the industry has been 
largely ignored.  For the most part, solutions are enormously inexpensive, 
reliable, and easy to procure and implement.  However, in recent years, chip 
designers and computer OEMs have been caught unawares by overheating ICs and 
the subsequent breakdown of computer systems.  Thermal issues, and the players 
responsible for them, must now be faced.<P> 

This report provides an analysis of those segments of the electronics industry 
bent on keeping devices cool, from such simple devices as heat sinks and fans, 
to the more complex areas of thermal management software and thermally 
conductive substrates. This work also predicts the future use of liquid 
cooling technologies and evaluates new technologies now under development. The 
major players in the largest sectors of the market are also identified and 
profiled and a patent analysis is offered.<P> 

The work is directed to decision makers in the segments of the electronics 
industry concerned with thermal management issues and markets, as well as 
those of the related electronics packaging and materials fields.  They 
include:<P> 

<UL>
   <LI>Computer and communication device developers
   <LI>Heat sink and fan manufacturers and developers
   <LI>Software application developers
   <LI>Electronic material suppliers
   <LI>Integrated circuit and other component designers and suppliers
   <LI>Printed circuit board suppliers
   <LI>Equipment manufacturers
   <LI>Marketplace managers
   <LI>Merger, acquisition, and investment executives.
</UL>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report is an analytical business tool whose primary purpose is to cover 
the growing portable computer industry in terms of application and end-use 
markets.  A market summary follows this introductory section and is followed 
immediately by an overview of thermal management.  Following this segment is 
an extensive review of the technology, which is then followed by analyses of 
the various market segments involved.  The ensuing segments include a patent 
analysis covering the first half of 1990 and an analysis of the industry's 
structure.  The appendices include an extensive directory of related vendors 
and manufacturers of all types of thermal management-related devices and 
products.<P> 


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The material presented is based on information gathered from personal contacts 
with participants within the portable computing industry as well as a thorough 
review of the technology gathered from technical papers and industry 
conferences.  Our final analyses and projections are based on a combination of 
a consensus among the primary contacts with our understanding of the impact of 
trends from a historical perspective.<P> 

Additional data were obtained from extensive reviews of secondary sources.  
These include trade publications, trade associations, company literature, and 
on-line databases.  This was done to supplement our understanding of 
applications, markets, and trends in the portable computing and communications 
industries.  All dollar projections presented in this report are in 1995 
constant dollars.<P> 


<B>RELATED BCC RESEARCH CREDENTIALS</B><P>

BCC has been a leader in market research and consulting to the electronics and 
materials industries since 1971.  Over the last several years, BCC has 
produced in-depth analyses of technologies and business opportunities in 
materials and components for advanced computer systems, such as thick and thin 
film in microelectronics, electronic integrated circuit and component 
packaging, printed circuit board manufacturing, surface mount technology, 
multichip modules, and deposition technology.<P>
  
Some reports of interest are:<P> 

<UL>
   <LI>G-067-X   Printed Circuit Boards: Markets & Opportunities
   <LI>G-118     Surface Mount Technology in Electronics
   <LI>GB-121-R  Electronic Ceramics
   <LI>GB-128-R  Thick and Thin Film in Microelectronics
   <LI>GB-138-R  Multichip Packaging & Base Chip Systems
   <LI>GB-156    Advanced Electronic Packaging Systems
   <LI>GB-160    Magnetic/Opto-Magnetic Storage: Technology Throug  2000
   <LI>GB-171    The Changing Display Industry: CRT and Flat Panel
   <LI>GB-173    Diamond, Diamond-Like Carbon and CBN Films and Coated              
                        Ceramics
</UL> 

Appendix  III contains a more complete list of related BCC reports as well as 
their dates of publication and prices.<P> 


