<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-186A THIN LAYER DEPOSITION: HIGHLIGHTING CVD
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-186A THIN LAYER DEPOSITION: HIGHLIGHTING CVD
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ROBERT MORAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

BCC's goal in conducting this study was to determine the current
status of the market for chemical vapor deposition (CVD)
equipment, services and materials deposited and assess the growth
potential over a five-year period from 1995 to 2000.  We were
particularly interested in the types of equipment and kinds of
materials being used for industrial and consumer applications.<P>

Our major objective was to present a comprehensive analysis of
the current CVD industry and project its future course.<P>

This study is part of a three part service:  GB186A - Thin Layer
Deposition: Highlighting CVD, GB186B - Thin Layer Deposition:
Highlighting PVD, and GB186C - Thin Layer Deposition:  Plasma,
Epitaxial.  Pages 1 through 54 are the same for all reports.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

CVD has expanded significantly over the past several decades.
More sophisticated manufacturing and fabrication techniques and
miniaturized products have broadened the demand for vapor-
deposited materials.  A variety of new and existing materials
requires properties that can best be delivered by chemically
deposited thin films on a wide variety of surfaces.<P>

BCC decided to examine the current position of CVD technologies
and materials used in key industries.  We were interested in what
materials and types of CVD systems were being used to meet the
demands for more sophisticated products.<P>




<B>CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

We assembled a study of the types of CVD equipment and materials
used in five major industry groups.  We present an overview of
deposition technologies and future trends, and a worldwide CVD
industry structure including leading manufacturers of equipment
and service providers.  Within each industry segment, we present
an overview of key applications, the advantages of using the CVD
process, analysis of market factors that will impact demand and
project shipments of equipment, materials and services to 2000.
This study will be of interest to those in the microelectronics
business, manufacturers of cutting tools, medical instruments and
devices, and makers of automotive and aerospace products.  It
will also be of interest to companies engaged in the manufacture
of deposition equipment and materials, and to surface coaters.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of this study encompasses CVD technologies and
materials in terms of applications, properties and processes.
BCC analyzes the major types of CVD systems and materials used to
manufacture  products in the five key industries.  The
applications are discussed, as are the properties imparted
through CVD.  Trends in demand for various products are also
reviewed and their impact on the CVD process is discussed.<P>

Market drivers within each industry segment are identified.  The
materials deposited by CVD are analyzed by their basic functions
such as dielectrics, conductors, and resistance to abrasion and
wear.  The value of CVD equipment shipments is projected within
each industry by type of reactor.  Material shipment values are
also projected as are CVD services revenues.  Technological
issues and trends are reviewed and other influential factors such
as economic conditions and standards are discussed.<P>

Because this is a worldwide study, BCC analyzes the domestic and
international technological issues and economic considerations.
BCC also presents an analysis of market factors and examines
their impact on the future.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis of the values of CVD systems, materials
deposited, and services provided by type of reactor, material and
industry segment.  Our estimated value is what manufacturers and
material providers have paid in current dollars.  Then, based on
our surveys, we analyze industry growth in relation to the growth
of CVD technology, calculate estimates for growth, and forecast
shipments for 2000.<P>



<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC surveyed approximately 125 companies to obtain the data for
this report.  Included were manufacturers of CVD equipment,
materials, deposition service providers, industrial and consumer
product manufacturing companies, and various end users of the CVD
process.  Additional data for this report was obtained from
government information, trade associations, industry and
financial sources, and an exhaustive review of technical papers.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Several other BCC reports are related to this topic.  They are:
GB180 - Markets for Metallizing Technologies, GB186 - Thin Layer
Deposition: Opportunities for the Future, GB173 - Diamond,
Diamond-Like Carbon and CBN Films and Coated Products.<P>


