<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-186C THIN LAYER DEPOSITION: HIGHLIGHTING IMPLANTATION AND
EPITAXY, PLASMA, THERMAL AND ION
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-186C THIN LAYER DEPOSITION: HIGHLIGHTING
IMPLANTATION AND EPITAXY, PLASMA, THERMAL AND ION
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I> ROBERT MORAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

BCC's goal in conducting this study was to determine the
current status of the market for implantation and epitaxy
equipment (including plasma, thermal and ion), services and
materials and assess the growth potential over a five-year
period from 1995 to 2000.  We were particularly interested
in the types of equipment and kind of materials being used
for industrial and consumer applications.<P>

Our major objective was to present a comprehensive analysis
of the current implantation and epitaxy market and project
its future course.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

These technologies have expanded significantly over the past
several decades.  More sophisticated manufacturing and
fabrication techniques and miniaturized products have
broadened the demand for implanted and vapor deposited
materials.  A variety of new and existing products require
properties that can best be delivered by implanting or
vacuum depositing thin films on a wide variety of surfaces.<P>

BCC decided to examine the current position of implantation,
epitaxy and related technologies and materials used in key
industries.  We were interested in what materials and types
of systems were being used to meet the demands for more
sophisticated products.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

We assembled a study of the types of implantation and
epitaxy equipment and materials used in five major industry
groups.  We present an overview of deposition technologies
and future trends, and a worldwide implantation and epitaxy
industry structure including leading manufacturers of
equipment and service providers.  Within each industry, we
present an overview of key applications, the advantages of
using a particular technology, an analysis of market factors
that will impact demand and project shipments of equipment,
materials and services to 2000.  This study will be of
interest to those in the microelectronics business,
manufacturers of machine tools, automotive and aerospace
parts, and medical device makers. It will also be of
interest to companies engaged in the manufacture of
deposition equipment and material and to surface coaters.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of this study encompasses implantation and epitaxy
technologies and materials in terms of applications,
properties and processes.  BCC analyzes the major types of
implantation, epitaxy  and related systems such as plasma
deposition and thermal spray, and materials used to
manufacture products in five key industries.  The
applications are discussed, as are the properties imparted.
Trends in demand are also reviewed and their impact on these
implantation and deposition technologies is discussed.<P>

Market drivers within each industry are identified.  The
materials deposited by implantation and epitaxy are analyzed
by their basic functions such as wear-resistance, thermal
control and lubricity.  The value of implantation and
epitaxy equipment shipments is projected within each
industry by type of system.  Material shipment values are
also projected, along with service revenues.  Technological
issues and trends are reviewed and other influential factors
such as economic conditions and standards are discussed.<P>

Because this is a worldwide study, BCC analyzes the domestic
and international technological issues and economic
considerations.  BCC also presents an analysis of market
factors and examines their impact on the future.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis of the values of implantation and
epitaxy systems, materials implanted and deposited, and
services provided by type of system, material and industry
segment.  Our estimated value is what manufacturers and
material providers have paid in current dollars.  Then,
based on our surveys, we analyze industry growth in relation
to the growth of implantation and epitaxy technology,
calculate estimates for growth, and forecast shipments for
2000.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC surveyed approximately 120 companies to obtain the data
for this report.  Included were manufacturers of
implantation, epitaxy and related equipment and materials,
service providers, industrial and consumer product
manufacturing companies, and various end users of the
implantation and deposition process.  Additional data for
this report were obtained from government information, trade
associations, industry and financial sources, and an
exhaustive review of technical papers.<P>


