<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-007U  THE U.S. ENERGY FUTURE:
ENVIRONMENTAL/SOCIAL COSTS QUANTIFIED
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-007U  THE U.S. ENERGY FUTURE:
ENVIRONMENTAL/SOCIAL COSTS QUANTIFIED
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>
CHRISTIANNE TOENNE</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

With our society's ever increasing use of energy, it has become
apparent over the past few years that serious consideration must be
given to the influence this has on our environment. Although short-lived crises like the recent Gulf War once again emphasized the
dangers of reliance on imported fossil fuels, the ongoing question
is much broader: Can we afford to go on using energy without paying
attention to the damage that unbridled energy consumption will do
to the environment? Be it acid rain and smog caused by the burning
of fossil fuels, the danger of using radioactive materials, or the
large scale destruction of wildlife and native populations'
habitats by changing the flow of major waterways, it has to be
weighed against the goal of increasing our industrial productivity
as well as our personal comfort.<P>

This report addresses these issues that have come to the forefront
in many discussions in the recent past. While no universal solution
can be offered, various directions can be pointed out, and
technological as well as political solutions can be considered. How
can we balance the seemingly contradictory demands of preserving
and improving our standard of living while at the same time not
destroying the place in which we live.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

In the 19 years following the Arab oil embargo of 1973, the U.S.
annual electric generation has increased by 1 trillion kilowatt
hours. Over the same period, oil and gas generation declined by
almost 200 billion kilowatt hours, meaning that over 1.2 trillion
kilowatt hours of "new" electricity were needed to meet economic
growth and to replace oil and gas fired power. Of that total, 59%
came from coal, 36% from nuclear power, and only 5% from other
sources.<P>

The National Energy Strategy is designed to address several
potentially serious energy-related problems:<P>

<UL>-    Pollution and global warming trends. Evidence is mounting of
     environmental damage caused by acid rain and "greenhouse
     gases."<P>

-    Growing dependence on fossil fuels and consequent vulnerability to supply disruptions - a trend dramatically underscored by
     the Gulf War. U.S. net daily consumption of imported oil will
     reach 10 million barrels a day by the end of the decade,
     according to the U.S. Energy Information Administration.<P>

-    A lack of alternatives to fossil fuels. Through the 1980s,
     support for commercialization of alternative energy technologies withered, forcing many developers out of business. At the
     same time, the U.S. nuclear industry suffered a series of
     shocks and has not been able to expand beyond 20% of U.S.
     electricity production.</UL><P>

It is also hoped that the strategy will strengthen U.S. competitiveness by bolstering the country's position in emerging clean
energy technologies that could become the basis of multi billion 
dollar industries as countries expand their efforts to reduce
pollution and greenhouse gases.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study pulls together achievements in energy technologies and
efficiencies during the eighties. It analyzes the limits and
opportunities for alternative energy sources for the decade of the
nineties. Based on previous usage patterns and technology developments, we then forecast potential use patterns for the nineties
and, in some cases, beyond. Many scenarios exist for the potential
of alternative energy sources and their ability to replace fossil
fuels, as evidenced by materials published by a variety of
organizations. This report summarizes and compares pertinent
scenarios, and we use the most likely scenario for our own
forecasts. We also take into consideration the role of energy
conservation and efficiency, the amount of energy saved in the past
decade using such technologies, and the likely amount of energy not
needed in this decade with new technologies.<P>

We discuss how fossil energy sources impact the environment, in
terms of global warming as well as habitat protection for wildlife
and indigenous people's traditional way of life, and how the use of
alternative fuels and conservation can contribute greatly in our
efforts to preserve the environment. Lastly, we attempt to quantify
the impact of environmental and socioeconomic factors and
incorporate their cost into the price for the different fuel
sources, to create a more balanced comparison of actual costs.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study is limited to the role of energy used in non transportation applications. These include residential, commercial, and
industrial use, both as direct use of a resource as well as use of
electricity generated by such resources. The study includes
"traditional" fuels as well as "alternative" fuels and the
contribution of energy conservation and efficiency. Whenever
applicable and possible, forecasts are made for the next 5-10
years, based on historical patterns and the consensus of industry
and government experts. As far as available and applicable, various
scenarios are presented, either for different price assumptions or
different policy assumptions. For the overall overview and
prediction, "middle of the road" scenarios are chosen.<P>

The report is presented in three major sections: Fossil Energy
Sources, Renewable Energy Sources, and Conservation. Within each
section, the role of different energy sources is presented and
their impact on the environment is investigated, both from a
qualitative and a quantitative point of view.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

In assembling this report, published data from various governmental
and private sources were considered for historical purposes.
Projections were established by BCC taking into consideration
projections made by published sources as well as industry consensus
and external influences such as demographic data and likely
political developments.<P>

In calculating environmental and social costs, a number of sources
were considered. A series of articles published in Contemporary
Policy Issues in July 1990 by the Western Economic Association
International examined the topic of social and private cost of
various energy technologies. Another set of articles relating to
the damage of air pollution to agriculture, fishing, and forestry
was published in the American Journal of Agricultural Economics in
May 1986. We adopted some of their findings and, as necessary,
updated them to current price and cost levels. We expanded on some
of their assumptions, which were too regional in nature, by using
data from the Census Bureau and the U.S. Federal Highway Administration to extrapolate to national levels. An example of this is
the impact of acid rain, which was calculated in the above
publications for the Los Angeles Basin only.<P>

Further data were obtained from the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
(concerning the social cost of nuclear energy) and the U.S.
Government Accounting Office (various publications dealing with the
impact of nuclear and hydro energy), the North American Electric
Reliability Council (concerning hydro energy), the Solar Energy
Research Institute (concerning geothermal and biomass energy), and
the Electric Power Research Institute (concerning biomass energy
and conservation). For potential energy savings through conservation, we also relied on reports and findings published by the Rocky
Mountain Institute.<P>

Using these data, we have attempted to quantify, in as much detail
as possible, the environmental and social cost of the different
energy sources. By adding these expenditures to the actual market
price of the energy category, we thus arrived at actual cost
levels. Further consideration was given to the fact that, in using
fossil fuels for electricity generation, about two-thirds of the
energy input is lost. By factoring in the portion of a given fossil
fuel that is used for electricity generation, we then were able to
calculate the total weighted cost for each energy source.<P>

Given that many of environmental and social costs are difficult to
quantify, these environmental price calculations must, by necessity, be incomplete and can only be considered the best possible
approximation given present information. Nevertheless, this is the
first document that quantifies these costs and provides all the
difficult to gather and analyze data in one place. It is an
indispensable tool for today's energy analyst who must consider
energy planning in the context of environmental and social cost.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

This study relies heavily on the input provided by experts in the
field as well as on the vast scientific and popular literature that
is available. The topic of energy versus the environment is being
addressed by a variety of interested parties, ranging from the
major oil and gas companies to government agencies and environmentalists. It is the subject of controversies and intense practical
and theoretical research. We have attempted to incorporate the
latest thinking on the subject and are grateful for the input of
all those contacted. Data were provided by the U.S. Energy
Information Administration and the U.S. Department of Energy and
its various agencies as well as independent research associations,
trade associations and environmental groups.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

BCC has been active in the field of energy research for more than
15 years. It publishes the following monthly newsletters: Energy
Conservation News, Enhanced Energy Recovery, and Battery/Electric
Vehicle Technology as well as Energy Magazine which appears five
times a year. In addition, the following recent reports should be
of interest to BCC clients:<P>

<UL>LE-0070   Alternatives to Foreign-Based Energy Sources<BR>

LE-043R   Utilities, Cogeneration, and Small Scale Power<BR>

LE-049    Air Pollution and the Markets for Monitors and Sensors<BR>

LE-052    Environmental Services for Indoor Air Pollution<BR>

LE-053    Waste to Energy: Impact, Directions, Trends<BR>

LE-036    Solar, Thermal, and Photovoltaic: World Growth Markets<BR>

YE-054    New Directions in Transportation Fuels</UL><P>


