<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-036N SOLAR THERMAL AND PHOTOVOLTAICS: WORLD GROWTH MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-O36N SOLAR THERMAL AND PHOTOVOLTAICS: WORLD GROWTH
MARKETS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ROBERT MORAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

BCC's goal in conducting this study was to determine the current
worldwide status of solar thermal and photovoltaic energy and
conventional solar hot water heating and assess their growth
potential over a 6 year period from 1994 to 2000.  We were
particularly interested in the kinds of equipment being used for
each technology and their costs relative to the more conventional
sources of energy.<P>  

Our major objective was to present a comprehensive analysis of
the current solar energy markets and project their future
direction.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

Concerted efforts to develop solar energy began during the oil
shortages of the 1970s.  When oil prices stabilized, however,
major incentives to use solar systems, such as investment and tax
credits, abated and government funding for research was reduced. 
Despite these changes, development efforts, especially in
photovoltaics, continued.  In the 1990s, R&D funding and industry
activity has increased and solar energy again offers promise for
the future.<P>  

BCC examined the solar industry in 1990 (Report E-036R "Solar
Thermal and Photovoltaics: World Growth Markets) and projected
its growth to 1995.  We were interested in looking at the
industry again, analyzing the key competitive factors, and
looking at its growth prospects to the end of the decade.<P>  


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

We assembled a study of the three major types of solar energy. 
We present the industry structure, current and emerging
technologies, market factors, key applications, and then project
shipments of solar energy systems for 1994, 1995 and 2000.  We
present forecasts of photovoltaic modules, solar thermal energy
and industrial systems, and solar water heating equipment.  This
study will be of interest to those who make solar energy and
heating products and related materials, semiconductors, thin
films, electrical devices, and deposition equipment.  It will
also interest utility companies, construction firms, and
companies involved in large scale manufacturing.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of this study encompasses the three major types of
solar energy systems in use: photovoltaic modules, solar thermal
generating systems, and solar hot water heating equipment.  BCC
analyzes each technology, assesses its current market status,
examines its impact on future markets, and presents projections
of growth over a 6 year period.  Various technological issues,
such as new kinds of materials, are discussed.  A thorough
economic analysis of each technology and its impact on future
growth is also presented.<P>  

BCC analyzes the industry on a worldwide basis, including
manufacturing capability, consumption and shipping activity.  We
examine government support, industry activities and standards in
the major regions of the world.  We also discuss the utility
grid-connected and stand-alone potential of the electric
generating capability of photovoltaics and solar thermal
technology.<P>  

Projections of shipments by technology and applications are
presented for each of the three solar systems.  A discussion of
thin films for photovoltaics is included in that market section.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis, by each solar technology, of the number
of systems shipped in 1994.  Our estimated value is what
manufacturers have paid in undepreciated dollars.  Then, based on
our surveys, we analyze the potential market for each technology,
and forecast shipments for 1995 and 2000.<P>  

We also analyze the costs involved in each kind of solar system
and present an estimated value of shipments for each technology
over the forecast period.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC surveyed approximately 100 companies to obtain data for this
study.  Included were manufacturers of photovoltaic cells,
modules, arrays and supporting equipment, makers of solar thermal
collectors  for high temperature generating systems and low-to-medium water
 heating systems, manufacturers of structuralequipment and related materials.
We also spoke with companiesspecializing in deposition of thin films.  In addition,
wecompiled data from current financial and trade information and government
sources.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Several other reports are related to this topic.  They are:<P>
<UL>
<LI>E-074, "World Electrical Power Activities," 
<LI>E-073, "The Impending Electrical Vehicle Market," 
<LI>GB-086N, "The U.S. Battery Industry: Update."
</UL>
       


