<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-054R NEW DIRECTIONS IN TRANSPORTATION FUELS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-054R NEW DIRECTIONS IN TRANSPORTATION FUELS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>KEVIN SWIFT
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report provides a detailed and comprehensive multi-client study of the
U.S. market for alternative transportation fuels and potential business
opportunities.  The document includes a thorough coverage of the underlying
social, political, economic, energy, and environmental issues driving the
alternative transportation fuels business, as well as assessments of new and
potential fuels.  Furthermore, the study provides realistic market data and
forecasts for alternatively fueled vehicles (AFVs) and related technologies.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

During the past five years there has been growing concern about the
environment in the United States.  This has manifested itself in the emergence
of Green political initiatives and an expanding number of environmental
standards, air emission targets, and regulations.  For the alternative fuels
business, the most important of these have been the Clean Air Act Amendments
of 1990 and the Energy Policy Act of 1992.  Recent directions in the
legislative and regulatory arena indicate that environmental and energy
conservation pressures--despite the recession--remain important to the
public and legislators.   Lately this has manifested itself in the
Administration's proposed but failed Btu tax.  It is assumed that these
pressures will intensify in the years to come, engendering further changes in
the alternative transportation fuels business.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The alternative transportation fuels industry is not a precisely defined
sector and has not yet been assigned in any of the major economic
classification codes or activities.  As used in this report, alternative
transportation fuels are those fuels developed as alternatives to the
traditional fuels -- gasoline and diesel fuel -- used in automobiles, light
trucks, vans, other trucks, and buses.  Included are ethanol, methanol,
liquefied petroleum gas (LPG), compressed natural gas (CNG), and other fuels,
in addition to electric propulsion systems for motor vehicles.  The report
also includes reformulated gasoline (RFG) and certain additives used in
gasoline to reduce air emissions.  This includes oxygenates such as methyl-tertiary-butyl-ether (MTBE) and various alcohols, among others.   Many of
these fuels are used in other non-fuel purposes such as the catalytic vapor
phase oxidation of methanol into formaldehyde.  Revenues associated with
these other non-fuel uses are not included within the scope of this report.
Other non-motor vehicle modes of transportation--rail, air, inland
waterways, marine, etc.) are also not included within the scope of this
report.<P>

It should be pointed out that the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and
the Energy Information Administration (EIA) of the Dept. of Energy (DOE)
have recently initiated efforts to develop statistical reporting programs in
the area of alternative fuels and alternatively fueled vehicles.<P>

The scope of this report is comprehensive, covering the present status of, and
future prospects for alternative transportation fuels in the U.S.
It covers the many issues concerning the merits and future prospects of the
alternative fuels business, including alternatively fueled vehicles (AFVs) and
the numerous sociopolitical, economic, energy, and environmental issues that
so many regard as critical to the industry's current state of change.  The
report provides a review of the alternative transportation fuels industry, its
structure and the many companies involved in supplying these products.   The
competitive position of the main players in the market and the strategic
options they face are also discussed, as well as such competitive factors as
marketing, technology, distribution, and operations.  The report also looks at
the varieties of basic research, product development, and commercialization
that are being conducted in the area of alternative transportation fuels
technology.  The report also examines the state of alternatively fueled
vehicle (AFV) technology, markets, and industry structure.<P>

Unless noted otherwise, all figures represent the consumption of these
transportation fuels (and additives) in either millions of gallons or barrels per day.  The value of consumption (or revenues) for alternative fuels--in millions of U.S. dollars--represents the value of the product sold for motor vehicle fuel purposes.  This value reflects the net sales price, f.o.b. plant or refinery, to the distributor/marketer of the fuel, net of discounts, allowances, and freight charges.  The value of intracompany transfers (e.g. MTBE at an oil refinery) is also included.  For the value of reformulated gasolines (RFG), the value of oxygenates is excluded to eliminate duplication.  As a result, figures associated with RFG represent their processing value.<P>

As used in this study, the term consumption is equivalent to, and used
interchangeably with, the terms demand and sales.  During the discussion of the individual market segments, consumption of fuels (and to a lesser extent revenues) are related to indicators in the tables that are used for comparative purposes.  They do not imply that the indicator used represents the sole market for that product.  In addition, the sum of individual components within a column of a table may not agree with the reported sum at
the top of the table due to independent rounding of the components.<P>

All growth rates mentioned in the tables and in the text are based on the
average annual rate of growth from 1993 through 1998 or from 1998 to the year
2003.  The compounding method of calculating growth rates is used.  Because
current dollar  measures are used in reporting revenues, these growth rates
thus reflect the growth in volume or real growth in addition to growth
including the effects of price changes and changes in product mix.  The
effects of inflation are eliminated by presenting unit consumption data or by
the use of price indexes to provide measures of real growth.<P>




<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study provides the most complete accounting of ongoing alternative
transportation fuel developments in the United States currently available in a
multi-client format.  The study also provides extensive quantification of the
many important facets of market developments in the United States for
alternative transportation fuels, vehicles, and technologies.  This, in turn,
contributes to the determination of what kind of strategic response companies
may adopt in order to compete in this dynamic market.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Initially, a comprehensive and exhaustive search of the literature on
alternative transportation fuel technology was conducted.  These secondary
sources included technical journals, technical books, marketing literature,
other product/promotional literature, annual reports, security analyst
reports, and other publications.  In addition, there were formal and informal
interviews with oil refiners, chemical additive producers, light vehicle
manufacturers, technical experts, government officials, trade association
officials, and personnel of the companies themselves.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Founded in 1971, Business Communications Co., Inc. (BCC) is known throughout
the world for its technical-economic reports and services.  The company has
studied major market, economic, environmental, and technological developments
that have characterized industry during the past two decades to produce
reports, newsletters, and conferences.  In the process, BCC has focused on
advanced materials, high-technology systems and components, and novel
processing methods, since the development and marketing of these phenomena
assert a profound influence on manufacturers and users on a worldwide scale.
BCC clients include almost every major corporation in the U.S.,
Canada, Western Europe, and Japan.<P>

Of related interest to the subject of alternative transportation fuels are such BCC reports as:  
<UL>Vehicular Fuels: Substitutes & Additives for the Future<BR>
The U.S. Battery Industry<BR>
Air Pollution Control Techniques, Equipment, and Services in Europe<BR>
Air Pollution and the Market for Monitors and Sensors<BR>
Electric Utilities:  New Directions<BR>
Solar Thermal and Photovoltaics<BR>
The U.S. Energy Future:  Environmental/Social Costs Quantified<BR>
Waste-to-Energy: Impact, Directions and Trends<BR>
Catalysts for Organic Synthesis.<P></UL>

The company has also conducted reports on a wide variety of environmental and energy issues.  BCC also publishes the monthly newsletters Battery and EV Technology, Atmospheric Pollution and Abatement News, Energy, Enhanced Energy Recovery News, and Energy Conservation News.<P>

