<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-059A  BRIDGE AND HIGHWAY MAINTENANCE:
THE CHANGING INFRASTRUCTURE
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-059A  BRIDGE AND HIGHWAY MAINTENANCE:
THE CHANGING INFRASTRUCTURE</H2><P>
<H3>Volume 1</H3>

<HR><P>

<I>ANAND RAO</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The accelerated highways and bridges building programs of the 1960s and 1970s
enabled the nation to build a transportation infrastructure that covers most of its
needs.  While the nation is not in a crying need for more new roads, the need to
maintain them has assumed crisis proportions.  One way or the other highways and
bridges will have to be maintained and business opportunities for suppliers of all sorts
will evolve.<P>

The roads and bridges built in the 1960s and 1970s were not designed to
accommodate 18-wheeler rigs and high volumes of business and pleasure traffic.  They
are breaking down at alarming rates and maintaining them to current and projected
future traffic has assumed very high importance.<P>

Our goal in conducting this study is to evaluate the developments that are the results
of the Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act (ISTEA) of 1991 affecting the
highways and bridges construction and maintenance industry.  This report details the
extent of the allotments by type that will be made available to the industry in order
to effect the greatest highway remodeling program in history.  While the overall
funds made available from the act will reach $131 billion between 1992 through 1997,
not all of it will translate into business opportunities.  This report focuses on the
seven programs that will result in direct business opportunities, and details how much
will be spent, the types of projects, regions, usage patterns and the most active states
under each program.<P>

This is the first part of a three-part study that examines the impact of ISTEA on
business and the raw materials used in the industry.  It examines the overall effect
of ISTEA programs on the highways and bridges construction and maintenance
industries, and the type of work and the states that offer most opportunities.  Part
2  examines the opportunities available for the suppliers of asphalt and Portland
cement under the appropriate ISTEA programs.  Part 3 examines the market
potentials for the vendors of other raw materials used in the industry.<P>



<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study measures growth prospects and  direct business possibilities that are
generated by the programs that have been instituted under ISTEA.  Our analyst was
made aware of the difference between the direct and indirect business opportunities
that may result because of ISTEA.  While the overall allotments under ISTEA will
amount to about $131 billion between 1992-1997, a considerable portion of that will
be spent to cover research, experimentation and administrative costs.  Thus, the real
or direct business opportunities will be in some areas only, and our goal is to analyze
the programs that are most attractive for the industry.  This study is a sequel to the
previous studies on the needs of highways and bridges.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTION FOR THIS STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This analysis is based on information carefully generated from interviews with
industry experts, officials of the federal and state agencies, data excerpted from replies
to the questionnaires mailed to industry specialists and other informed individuals,
and analysis of a wide variety of information generated by the industry press and
technology journals. Additionally, select industry experts were approached more than
once to clarify several related issues.<P>

Information was generated from vendors as well as DOTs, and matched to produce
estimates of the most viable areas of business opportunities.  A consensus was
developed to focus on the usage patterns, regional division and most active states in
each category of programs introduced under ISTEA.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This document covers seven ISTEA programs, which are considered the most
attractive areas for business opportunities.  Each program is analyzed, focusing on
the regions, states and usage patterns.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis, by each program, focusing both on the overall
opportunities, as well as opportunities by region, top 10 states and usage patterns as
appropriate.<P>

Each projection was based on current industry statistics, opinions from industry
experts, and an analysis of information available from several industry sources.<P>

 Where applicable we have taken a general average of the projections provided by
various industry sources and have matched them with the volume of current business
reported from federal, state and trade agencies.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC has surveyed over 100 sources to obtain data for this study.  These included
federal highway administration agencies, state DOTs, consultants and others.  Major
industry publications, reports from the FHWA and other federal and state agencies,
industry associations and major financial publications were also consulted.<P>


<B>RELATED STUDIES</B><P>

This study is part of a series.  The other two studies in this series are:<P>

<UL>E-059B The Cement and Asphalt business.<BR>
E-059C Markets for Support/Ancillary Materials, Coatings and Pipe.<BR>
E-027N Bridge and Highway Maintenance Equipment, Materials.
       Published  6/89. <BR>
GB162  Advanced Transportation Control Systems;  Millimeter Wave, Microwave
       and Optical.</UL><P>


