<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-059B  BRIDGE AND HIGHWAY MAINTENANCE:
The Cement/ Asphalt Binder Business<P></H2>
<H3>Volume 2</H3><P>


<HR><P>

<I>ANAND RAO</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Our goal in conducting this study is to evaluate the results of the
developments of the Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act (ISTEA)
of 1991 on the use of Portland cement and asphalt in the highways and bridges
construction and maintenance industry.<P>

This is the second part of a three-part study that examines the impact of
ISTEA on the business and raw materials used in the industry.  Part 1 examines
the overall effect of ISTEA programs on the highways and bridges construction
and maintenance industries and the type of work and the states that offer most
opportunities.  Part 2 (this study) examines the opportunities available for
the suppliers of asphalt and Portland cement under the appropriate ISTEA
programs.  Part 3 examines the market potentials for the vendors of other raw
materials used in the industry.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study was undertaken to measure growth prospects and direct business
possibilities that are generated for the suppliers of Portland cement and
asphalt by the programs that have been instituted under the ISTEA.  Our
analyst was made aware of the difference between the direct and indirect
business opportunities that may result because of the ISTEA.  While the
overall allotments under the ISTEA amount to about $131 billion between 1992
and 1997, a considerable portion of that will be spent to cover research,
experimentation, and administrative costs.  Thus, the real or direct business
opportunities for the suppliers of Portland cement and asphalt will be
focussed in some areas, and our goal is to analyze the programs that are most
attractive for the two industries.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION FOR THIS STUDY AND FROM WHOM</B><P>

This study is based on information carefully generated from interviews with
industry experts, officials of the Federal and State agencies, data excerpted
from replies to the questionnaires mailed to industry specialists and other
informed individuals, and analysis of a wide variety of information generated
by the industry press and technology journals. Additionally, select industry
experts were approached more than once to clarify several related issues.<P>

Information was generated from vendors as well as DOTs and matched to produce
estimates of the most viable areas of business opportunities.  A consensus was
developed to focus on the usage patterns, regional division, and most active
states in each category of programs introduced under the ISTEA.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study covers the projected use of Portland cement and asphalt under
programs instituted by the ISTEA which are considered the most attractive
areas for business opportunities for the respective industries. Each program
is analyzed, focussing on the regions, states and usage patterns that offer
the most opportunities for asphalt and Portland cement industries.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis, by each program, focussing on the overall
opportunities, as well as opportunities by region, top ten states, and usage
patterns, as appropriate for the suppliers of asphalt and Portland cement.<P>

Each projection was based on current industry statistics, opinions from industry
experts, and analysis of information available from several industry sources.<P>

Where applicable we have taken a general average of the projections provided
by various industry sources and have matched them with the volume of current
business reported from Federal, State, and trade agencies.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC has surveyed over 100 sources to obtain data for this study.  These
included Federal highway administration agencies, State DOTs, consultants, and
others.  Major industry publications, reports from the FHWA and other Federal
and State agencies, industry associations, and major financial publications
were also consulted.<P>

