<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-067  NONUTILITY ELECTRICAL POWER GENERATION
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-067  NONUTILITY ELECTRICAL POWER GENERATION</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP AUCHINCLOSS</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Business Communications Company has monitored the electric generation industry
for many years.  Many people consider electric generation and electric
utilities as synonymous terms for this industry.  This report, however,
directs our attention to a newly emerging and rapidly growing segment of this
industry -- the nonutility generator (NUGs).<P>


<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The nonutility generating industry began in the early 1900's.  Manufacturing
firms built their own facilities to supply electricity, as the supply of
electricity from utilities was undependable and often unavailable.  The wide
ranging electric grid system existing today was not in place 90 years ago.<P>

The utility business grew rapidly during the intervening years until the
energy crisis of the 1970's.  Nonutility generating companies existed during
this time but supplied an insignificant quantity of electricity to the
industry.  Nonutility generating facilities began to increase with the passage
of the Public Utilities Regulatory Policy Act of 1978 (PURPA).  This
legislation provided strong incentives for the nonutility field to expand.<P>

Since the late '70's, nonutilities have played an increasingly important role
in meeting this nation's energy requirements.  As of 1993 it is estimated that
NUGs represent some seven % of all installed capacity.  This segment of the
electric generation industry provides a low cost supply of electrical energy
to their captive users and the electrical grid.<P>

Nonutility generating facilities are comprised of a wide variety of
technologies.  Some are as conventional as coal- or gas-fired boilers which
generate steam to drive generators or turbines.  Other technologies, like
solar energy and wind power are still in developmental stages.  Finally, new
fuel sources like biomass or municipal solid waste are becoming more popular
as an answer to environmental problems.<P>

The future growth of NUGs depends upon their continued ability to provide low
cost electricity in a timely fashion, and with low capital costs relative to
electrical utilities. How will the nonutility business fare in the last decade
of the 20th century and the first decade of the 21st?  Are there new
technologies on the horizon?  Which of the existing technologies will grow
rapidly in the next ten years?  These are some of the issues that are
addressed in this comprehensive analysis of the inter-technology competition
and evolving industry dynamics in the nonutility segment of the electric
generation industry.<P>

The objectives of this study include the determination and examination of:<P>

<UL>
<LI>the overall size of the nonutility field in units, dollars, and number of
         facilities;<BR>

<LI>the growth potential for the industry during the next ten years in total  and by segment;<BR>

<LI>the industry structure;<BR>

<LI>the opportunities for suppliers of equipment to this industry;<BR>

<LI>the importance of environmental and legislative issues to the future growth of this industry and its segments;<BR>

<LI>the significant trends affecting the future demand for power generated by
         nonutilities.</UL><P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

The reason for examining the nonutility field is to assess an industry which
enjoyed a successful growth record up to the 1930's and then declined until
the late '70's.  Since then, with the help of congressional legislation, the
industry has accelerated from next to nothing in size until today where it is
a major supplier of electricity.  The questions of concern are:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>"Can the industry maintain the established pace of the last several years?"<P>

     "What will the future bring?"<P>

     ". . . for energy technology?"<P>

     ". . . for each geographical segments of the country?"<P>

     "What are the important market niches, if any?"</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study is intended to serve persons involved in the nonutility field in
their continual assessment of evolving industry technology changes, growth
prospects by sub-markets, and legislative activities.  It is also intended to
guide decision makers about the choices of technology and locations for
nonutilities in the future.<P>

The study provides insights into the coal, natural gas, wind, etc. segments on
such issues as future growth, major producers, and new technology.

The study is intended for nonutility owners interested in determining how
their facilities fit into the industry and learning what may happen to their
segment in the next ten years.<P>

Suppliers to the nonutility industry will find this report helpful in
determining the potential market size for their products, whether they be
machinery or raw materials. Also data are presented on a state by state basis
which is helpful in allocating sales effort and locating customers.

Investors in nonutilities will find this report useful in understanding the
requirements for investment in a nonutility and the legal basis for a
nonutility's existence whether it is a wind farm, solar facility, or coal
fired generator.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report describes the nonutility generating portion of the electric
generation industry. The industry is made up of two segments defined by
various laws.  The electric utilities, the major segment but slowest growing,
are those companies allowed to sell electricity via the electrical grid to
industrial, commercial, and residential customers.  They are subject to a wide
variety of regulations of which the most widely known are the limitations and
procedures for changing the price of electricity through appeals to various
utility commissions.<P>

Nonutility generating firms may only sell electricity to an electric utility.
Their pricing structure is usually based on open market negotiations with the
buyer.  Buyers, however, must purchase electricity from a nonutility at
"avoided cost" or market negotiated higher price.<P>

The report includes domestic data on the United States only.

The report begins with an overview of the nonutility industry showing units,
dollars, and prices.  It then moves on to issues of industry size and
importance.  Characteristics of nonutilities are described to help the reader
understand the various industry segments. The report concludes with an
examination of industry participants and future growth rates.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The research methodology used a combination of telephone interviews with key
industry personnel and experts and a careful search of published data from the
Energy Information Administration, Department of Energy, Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission, and other government sources.  The number of people
contacted is shown in the table below.<P>






 <CENTER>TABLE A</CENTER><BR>
<CENTER>TELEPHONE INTERVIEWS</CENTER><P>

<PRE>
Description                        Number
                              Interviewed


Nonutilities - including project
managers and regulatory affairs
personnel                             27


Government agencies                   24


Manufacturers and marketers of
equipment for nonutilities             9


Industry trade associations            7


Consulting Firms                       2


TOTAL                                  69

Telephone interviewing was conducted during February and March, 1993.</PRE><P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information sources included industry experts, trade associations, and key
personnel at nonutilities themselves.  In addition, information was obtained
from government and trade association data where available.  Sources are
footnoted throughout the report.<P>



<B>MANAGEMENT SUMMARY</B><P>

1.  In 1993, the nonutility industry will have gross revenues of $10 billion
    from the sale of electricity to electric utilities.  This is an increase
    of 18.9 % per year from the 1988 figure of $4.2 billion dollars.
    Electricity sold to utilities was 165 billion kWh (Kilowatthours) in 1993,
    up 18.4 % per year from 1988's figure of 71 billion kWh.<P>

    By the year 2003, the industry is expected to have a gross revenue
    of $18.3 billion on sales of 280 billion kWh to electric utilities.
    The growth in dollars is expected to parallel the growth in kWh as
    prices are not expected to increase at a pace faster than 0.7 % per
    year over this decade.<P>




<CENTER>TABLE B</CENTER><BR>
<CENTER>NUG INDUSTRY ELECTRICITY SALES COMPARED TO TOTAL
ELECTRICITY SALES</CENTER><P>


<PRE>YEAR                     NUGS               TOTAL                  NUG
                                          ELECTRICITY          ELECTRICITY
                                           GENERATED           SOLD AS % OF
                                          (BILLION kWh)            TOTAL
          GROSS REVENUE    ELECTRICITY                          GENERATED

2003F            $18.3            280        3,616                  7.7%

1998F            $13.2            210        3,389                  6.2%

1993E            $10.0            165        3,178                  5.2%

1988              $4.2            71         2,905                  2.4%


                   Five year average annual growth rates

'98 -
'03               6.8%            5.9%           1.4%

'93 -
'98               5.7%             4.9%          1.3%

'88 -
'93              18.9%            18.4%          1.8%</PRE>

    Electricity sold by NUGs to utilities in 2003 will represent 7.7 % of the
    total available for sale to industrial, residential, and commercial users
    of electricity. This percentage is 3.2 times greater than the figure for
    1988 of 2.4 %.  From 1988 NUG sales of electricity will increase more than
    five  percentage points in 15 years.<P>

2.  All the electricity generated by NUGs makes up a significant portion of the
    nation's electrical energy supply.   In 1993, NUGs generated 286 billion
    kWh of electricity which represented 9 % of the total.  This percentage
    will increase to 13.0 % of the total by 2003.  Total electricity generated
    by NUGs will be 473 billion kWh in 2003.<P>





                                  <CENTER>TABLE C</CENTER><BR>
                     <CENTER>ELECTRICITY GENERATED FORECAST</CENTER><P>


<PRE>YEARS               ELECTRICITY GENERATED      NUG PERCENT OF
                        (Billion kWh)              TOTAL


                       NUGS    TOTAL  USA


2003                   473      3,636  13.0%

1998                   365      3,339  10.8%

1993                   286      3,178   9.0%

1988                   148      3,052   4.8%


               Five year average annual growth rates

'98 to '03            5.3%      1.7%

'93 to '98            5.0%      1.0%

'88 to '93            14.1%     0.8%</PRE><P>




2.  Tables B  and C above and D below clearly show a slower growth rate for
    NUGs in the next ten years than in the previous five years.  The demand for
    electricity is expected to slow because the commercial, residential, and
    industrial sectors of the economy are becoming more efficient in the use
    of electrical energy.  Industrial development, a major consumer of
    electricity, is expected to slow further in the decade ahead.  NUGs will
    grow faster than electrical utilities as those utilities will
    use nonutilities as a convenient and inexpensive energy source.<P>

3.  Industry capacity to reach 92 gigawatts by 2003, a gain of about five %
    per year from 1993.  This is a decrease in growth from the 10.2% seen for
    the 1989 to 1993 period as shown in table D below.<P>


                                    <CENTER>TABLE D</CENTER><BR>
                              <CENTER>INDUSTRY CAPACITY</CENTER><P>


<PRE>YEAR                        GIGAWATTS
2003                           92

1998                           71

1993                           56

1989                           38


Average annual growth rates

'98 - '03                      5.3%

'93 - '98                      4.9%

'89 - '93                      10.2%</PRE><P>



    Summary table E on the next page provides information on changes in NUG
    capacity during the next decade.   NUG capacity will increase by 15.3
    gigawatts during the next five years.  This capacity increase represents
    more than 25% of all planned capacity increases during the next five years.<P>

    Almost 90% of all capacity additions from 1993 to 1998 are forecast to be
    cogeneration facilities .  NUG cogeneration capacity will reach 58.7
    gigawatts by 1998.  The percentage of capacity that is cogeneration will
    be 82.7% in 1998 up from 80.8% in 1993.<P>

    Non-renewable fuels will continue to be the major energy source for NUGs
    in the next decade.  About 70% of the NUG capacity is and will continue to
    be driven by non-renewable fuel sources.</PRE><P>


<CENTER>TABLE E</CENTER><BR>
<CENTER>NUG CAPACITY SUMMARY TABLE</CENTER><P>

