capacity (Gigawatts)


NUG non-renewable
capacity as % of total      70.3%       70.6%  70.2%</PRE><P>



4.  Non-renewable energy sources represent the major portion of industry
    capacity. The capacity of natural gas-fired facilities will continue to
    grow at a 7% pace throughout the next decade.  This will be the
    fastest growth in this segment. Natural gas units will continue to be
    installed because of the ease of using gas and little environmental
    problems.<P>

    In the renewable fuel area, waste fired capacity will grow 8% per
    year during the next decade.  While this is the fastest growing type in
    this segment, wind-powered facilities are also expected to grow at similar
    rates.<P>

    Wind-powered capacity will increase 7.5% per year for the next decade.
    These facilities will benefit from new technology using lower profile wind
    generators. Wood-, hydro-, geothermal-, and solar-fired facilities will
    increase less rapidly.<P>

    Waste-fired facilities will continue to grow as the nation seeks
    alternative methods to dispose of municipal solid waste.<P>

5.  The industry has approximately 3,400 separate facilities in 1993.  This is
    an increase of 8.7% per year from 1989's figure of 2,414 facilities.  The
    number of facilities will grow at a slower rate in the future because of
    the prediction that larger nonutilities will be constructed.  These larger
    units are more efficient and reflect the profitability of nonutilities as
    an attractive investment opportunity.<P>

    By the year 2003, an estimated 5,400 nonutilities will be generating
    electricity to meet the nation's slowly growing electrical demand.<P>

6.  This report understates the importance of utilities in sales dollars in the
    U. S. economy.  For example, nonutilities generated 286 billion kWh of
    electricity in 1993.  Only a portion of this amount, 165 billion kWh, was
    actually sold to electric utilities.  The remainder was used to power
    captive facilities at  nonutility plant sites.  In addition, many
    nonutilities are cogeneration facilities.  Information
    on the economic value of this energy stream is not available.<P>

7.  Coal, natural gas, and biomass facilities can be located in any part of
    the country. Hydro-electric facilities can be placed anywhere there is
    water with a sufficient flow rate.  Wind and solar facilities have
    generally been limited to the West South Central, Pacific, and Mountain
    states, to take advantage of the abundant sunshine and natural wind
    patterns.  Geothermal facilities have also been concentrated in
    these three regions to take advantage of the readily available thermal
    energy from below the earth surface.<P>

8.  The price for electricity sold by nonutilities to utilities varies
    considerably by geographic region but averaged 6.1 cents per kWh in 1993.
    This average price is expected to increase only 0.7% per year to 6.5 cents
    per kWh by 2003.  This estimate reflects the slow growth of electrical
    demand and expected increased competition from nonutilities as they seek
    long term contracts from electrical utilities.<P>

    Regionally, the highest prices received by nonutilities are in the New
    England and Pacific region states.  Prices are estimated to be some 15 to
    20% above the national average.  The lowest prices were found in the
    Mountain states at 3 cents per kWh.  These low prices reflect a lack of
    need for additional electrical power
    and utilities being willing to pay only at "avoided-cost."<P>

9.  The West South Central region is the largest in terms of 1993 generating
    capacity. The total for this region is 14.1 gigawatts.  Next in order is
    the Pacific region with 12.6 gigawatts.  The South Atlantic region is
    third with about 8.4 gigawatts of capacity.  These three regions account
    for about two- thirds of all nonutility capacity.<P>

10. Major legislative acts affecting the nonutility industry include:

<UL>. Public Utility Regulatory Policy Act of 1978 (PURPA), which established
         the nonutility category<P>

 .      Electric Consumers Protection Act of 1986, which provides safeguards for
         fish and wildlife affected by hydro facilities<P>

 .      Clean Water Act which addresses the issue of hydro modification<P>

 .      Clean Air Act Phase I and Phase II, whose objective is to reduce sulfur
         dioxide and nitrogen oxide emissions<P>

 .      Energy Policy Act of 1982, which provided tax credits for wind,
        closed-loop biomass, solar, and geothermal facilities<P>

 .      Energy tax proposed at the time of this report<P>

