<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-069  FUEL CELLS: ON THE VERGE
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-069  FUEL CELLS: ON THE VERGE
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>KATHLEEN SLITER</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goals and objectives of this study include a discussion of the background
of fuel cells and how they have been important in the past. This will
introduce the reader to the history of fuel cells, the various types of fuel
cells, and their applications. The study will review the past successful and
unsuccessful uses of fuel cells in various industries.<P>


The study will also look at the technology and use of fuel cells today, the
companies involved in the research and applications, from both a domestic and
international viewpoint, and the reasons for their interest in fuel cells.

The ultimate objective of this study is to reveal the potential for growth of
the fuel cell "industry" and to provide the reader with the information needed
for investment decisions.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR THE STUDY</B><P>

To date, BCC has produced articles in newsletters regarding fuel cells;
however, no full report has yet been published.  This study will attempt to
bring together all current information, from primary and secondary sources,
regarding fuel cells.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF THE REPORT</B><P>

The scope of this report is the subject of fuel cells, their past
applications, future marketability in the United States and in other parts of
the world, concentrating, on Japan and Europe.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The methodology for the study includes an examination of all current
literature for fuel cells, including patents, technical journals, business
journals, BCC's Battery and EV Technology newsletter, and other industry
literature. In addition, certain individuals working in the industry were
interviewed. Future trends as well as current research are discussed. All
resulting information is contained in the study in a manner useful to the
potential investor.<P>

A "value" is assigned to each type of fuel cell and is further categorized by
market segment and application. The value assigned represents the total amount
of dollars exchanging hands, and in most cases is funded research and
development dollars. Since the industry is in the early stages of
commercialization, future sales estimates are not readily available. Budgets
for spending are available. The methodology for determining value is to
consider published spending estimates, verified through conversations with
certain industry experts, and reference to "Value Line" for related industry
information.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Related BCC publications include: 

<UL>GB086R - U.S. Battery Industry<BR>
E036R - Solar Thermal & Photovoltaics<BR>
E047 - Vehicular Fuels: Substitutes & Additives<BR>
E-067 - Non-Utility Generation<BR>
E-007U - The U.S. Energy Future: Environmental/Social Costs<BR> 
E-054R - New Directions in Transportation Fuels.<P></UL>

