<CENTER><H2>E-070: ENERGY-SAVING DEVICES AND EQUIPMENT:
RESIDENTIAL AND COMMERCIAL
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Sandra Grant
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>


The goal of this report is to provide an analysis of the pertinent
technical and economic forces within the energy-saving devices
industry and to provide market forecasts for each of the separate
technologies involved.  Important statistical and analytical
information will be provided for markets, applications, industry
structure, major players, industry dynamics and technology
developments.<P>


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P> 

This guide to the energy-saving devices industry is designed to
benefit those companies already involved in the business either as
users or as providers, or companies contemplating entering the
business.  The study focuses on the U.S. business.  This study
offers trends in energy-saving devices and identifies the current
players and their major products and contributions within the
context of the entire market.  Specifically, the present and future
markets for energy-saving lighting products, appliances, HVAC
products and systems monitoring and control technologies, windows
technologies and motor technologies are evaluated.<P>


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P> 

Market forecasts are made for the energy-saving devices discussed
in this report for a 10-year period.  Analysis covers the market
for the United States, and projections are in terms of constant
dollars.  Historical values are for the year given.  Sales figures
and forecasts are not available at this time for the following
markets: green computers, solar, motors, and low-flow shower heads. 
Figures for energy saved by Demand Side Management programs and
Cogeneration vary greatly from one source to another, therefore
they have not been included in this report.<P>


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P> 

Information for this report has evolved from a variety of sources,
including interaction with companies active within the industry.
Interviews, conferences, and a review of all the technical and
business literature available make this technical/marketing report
a document of unique value and perspective for industry,
government, and R&D.<P>

Sources include a number of business and trade journals,
publications, and newsletters.  Product literature also played an
important role in the creation of this report.  Government sources
such as the U.S. Department of Energy provided insight into
technological developments.  Other government sources such as the
U.S. Department of Commerce and the Bureau of the Census provided
statistical information on sales and usage of energy-saving
devices.<P>


