<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-071: REFORMULATED MOTOR GASOLINE: MARKETS,
                      TECHNOLOGIES, INDUSTRY RAMIFICATIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-071: REFORMULATED MOTOR GASOLINE: MARKETS,
                      TECHNOLOGIES, INDUSTRY RAMIFICATIONS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>J. Charles Forman
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>SECTION 1. INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Reformulated motor gasolines are an increasingly important factor in the U.S. 
(and world) energy equation.  Dictated by environmental and political 
considerations rather than those of the economic marketplace, these gasolines 
(called RFGs) will be required in many of the most populous regions of the 
United States in 1995 and subsequent years.  In this study, BCC presents the 
technical and political background for the manufacture, formulation, and sale 
of RFGs.  This study also includes historical background in RFG components and 
chemicals, especially fuel oxygenates, chemicals which contain oxygen and 
which are claimed to produce cleaner vehicle exhausts when blended into motor 
gasoline ("mogas").<P> 

Primary emphasis is on markets in the U.S., but we also note and 
discuss some of the more important international aspects of RFG supply, 
especially as it affects suppliers and markets in the U.S.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Hardly a day goes by without some item in the media regarding RFGs.  This 
subject is a fascinating combination of politics and technology, and is also 
one which affects most of the U.S. population, since virtually everyone either 
drives a car or lives in a region where the air quality is affected by vehicle 
exhausts.  BCC performed this study to provide a comprehensive reference for 
those interested and/or involved in reformulated gasolines; this is a wide and 
varied group of companies and other interested groups ranging from petroleum 
refiners, process technology/equipment designers and marketers, farmers, 
politicians of all stripes, and the general public. BCC has sorted through and 
condensed information from a large amount of literature and other reference 
materials to compile this report.<P> 


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report is intended to assist those involved in several different segments 
of the reformulated fuels industry.  These organizations and people include 
those who are involved in the design, selection, construction, and operation 
of facilities to produce RFG components as well as the fuels themselves.  
These include process and product designers, purchasing agents, construction 
and operating personnel, market staff, and top management.  BCC feels that 
this report will be of great value to technical and business personnel in the 
following areas, among others:<P> 

<LI> U.S. petroleum refining companies, which must make and sell the new
   reformulated gasolines.<P>

<LI> Companies involved in the design and construction of facilities to produce 
   RFG components, such as MTBE, as well as the finished RFGs themselves.<P>

<LI>  Organizations involved in basic and applied petroleum and petrochemical
   research.<P>

<LI>  Financial institutions which must finance these new and expensive facilities,
   many of which cost hundreds of millions of dollars.<P>

<LI> Personnel in state and federal governments, ranging from the politicians who
   must pass the legislation which makes RFGs mandatory to the environmental and
   other regulators who must implement and enforce the laws.<P>


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study covers the technological, economic, political, and environmental 
considerations in the RFG industry.  It is primarily a study of U.S. politics 
and markets, but because of the global nature of both the petroleum industry 
and the environmental movement, it touches on some noteworthy international 
activities, primarily those which can have an impact on the U.S. market, such 
as imports or MTBE or RFG.  All market forecasts are given in constant 1993 
dollars and growth rates are all compounded.  All market values are rounded to 
the nearest million dollars, gallons, barrels, etc.  Because of rounding, some 
growth rates may not agree exactly with figures in the market tables.<P> 

This report is segmented into 10 sections, of which this is the first.  Other 
sections include:<P> 

<b>SECTION II</B><P>

The Executive Summary, which encapsulates our findings and conclusions, and 
includes the summary market table.  it is the place where the busy executive 
can find the major findings of the study in summary format.<P> 

<b>SECTION III</B><P>

Section III is an overview of the petroleum refining industry:  its history 
and structure, its importance to the economy, and its major products and 
applications.<P> 

<b>SECTION IV</B><P>

Section IV presents the major driving forces for adoption and use of RFGs.  
These are primarily political, driven by the Clean Air Act amendments of 1990.  
State regulations, especially those in California, have made a complex 
technical and marketing problem even more complicated.  This section contains 
the history, current status, and projected future for implementation of the 
laws which require the manufacture and use of RFG.  It includes discussion of 
several important factors which may affect the outcome.<P> 

<b>SECTION V</B><P>

Section V discusses one means of producing the fuel components for RFGs, by 
modifying and adding to existing petroleum refineries for this purpose.  
Equipment and refinery process modifications are required to reduce and 
replace some mogas components, such as aromatics.  In addition, refiners like 
to have control over their production and economics, and in-refinery 
production of fuel oxygenates is a popular and often less expensive and more 
attractive source of supply.<P> 

<b>SECTION VI</B><P>

Section VI covers the other means of supplying RFG components, that of grass-roots facilities outside petroleum refineries.  At this time these are exclusively fuel oxygenates, both ethers and alcohols; the former is best exemplified by methyl tertiary butyl ether (MTBE), while today the latter only means ethanol derived from biomass. It is in this arena that the most intense and interesting political wars are now being fought between the petrochemical and refining industry, which prefers petroleum-based materials such as MTBE, and the U.S. farm lobby which wants to sell grain-derived ethanol as the RFG oxygenate, either alone or in the ether ETBE.  In this section we also discuss alternative vehicles (e.g., electric cars) and engine designs, as well as alternative fuels such as natural gas and methanol.<P> 

<b>SECTION VII</B><P>

Section VII discusses and forecasts the markets for RFGs and their components.  
We look at forecast markets for RFGs themselves and for several of the key 
components which are now, or may in the future, find use in RFGs.  Again, 
today these fall into two groups of chemicals:  ethers and alcohols.  MTBE, as 
the leading RFG additive, receives the greatest attention.  We also discuss 
and forecast U.S. markets for other ethers such as ETBE and TAME, "renewable" 
oxygenates (ethanol), refinery modifications, and reformulated gasolines.  
Forecasts are presented for base year 1993 (before mandated RFG use); 1995, 
the first full year of RFG usage, and 1998.  Because of the great 
uncertainties now hovering over the potential market for RFG and its 
components, BCC uses scenario analysis (optimistic, pessimistic, and most 
likely cases) for several of our market forecasts.<P> 

<b>SECTION VIII</B><P>

Section VIII discusses some important international aspects of RFGs.  Because 
of the importance of MTBE, focus is again on manufacture and use of MTBE 
around the world.  The import and export of RFG components and fuels into and 
out of the U.S. is also discussed.<P> 

<b>SECTION IX</B><P>

Section IX consists of brief profiles of many of the companies which are 
leading the way in the manufacture and adoption of RFGs.  These include 
several petroleum refiners which are currently producing fuel oxygenates in 
their refineries, companies which are currently manufacturing motor fuel 
oxygenates (both petroleum and grain-based) for the merchant market, and some 
of the leading companies in the process technology involved.<P> 

<b>SECTION XII</B><P>

 Section XII is an appendix which lists and defines some of the more important 
terms, abbreviations, and acronyms used in the petroleum refining and RFG 
industry.<P> 

The scope of this study is restricted to fuels for spark ignition internal 
combustion engines, those which power most of the automobiles and light trucks 
in the United States.  The manufacture and marketing of fuels for other types 
of vehicles, especially diesel fuel for heavier trucks and some cars, is a 
different technology altogether, and at this time has been exempted from most 
of the implementation requirements of the Clean Air Act amendments.  As 
appropriate, we note diesel and other fuels as they relate to ordinary mogas.<P> 


<b>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Searches were made of the literature, including many of the leading trade 
publications, technical compendia, and government publications.  Product and 
market information was obtained whenever possible from the companies involved.  
The information for our corporate profiles was obtained primarily from the 
companies themselves, especially the larger publicly owned firms.  Other 
sources included directories and articles.<P> 


<b>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Other BCC reports and newsletters which may be of interest include:<P>

