<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-073: THE IMPENDNING ELECTRIC VEHICLE MARKET:
IS NOW THE TIME? 
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-073: THE IMPENDNING ELECTRIC VEHICLE MARKET:
IS NOW THE TIME? 
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Donald Saxman
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Electric vehicles (EVs) were first built in 1886 and have been in common use 
since the beginning of the century, but have not been seen as a serious 
commercial contender since the 1920s.  For almost as long, there have been 
announcements that an EV revival was forthcoming.  These expectations are not 
unreasonable. EVs, by using electric utility charged batteries, indirectly use 
coal, nuclear or hydroelectric power (rather than gasoline).  Pollution is 
transferred from millions of point sources to more easily abated central 
locations.  EVs may be inherently more energy efficient than internal 
combustion vehicles.  When EV batteries are charged at night, they are an 
excellent load leveling technique.  Ultimately, of course, the world's 
petroleum will be consumed.  Enhanced recovery, synthetic fuel, and biomass 
recovery can only extend fuel supplies so far, and are not themselves immune 
to price hikes.  The question, then, is not whether EVs will be adopted, but 
when.  But is "when" now?<P> 

During the late 1970s, in response to the energy crisis, the DOE sponsored a series of research projects designed to develop EV powertrains, components, 
and especially batteries.  It was hoped that prototypes would be available by 1978, government sponsored pilot fleets by 1980, production prototypes by 1982, and commercial models by 1984.  At the height of the energy crisis, it was predicted that by 2000, 50% of the nation's automobiles would be either EVs or hybrid electric/internal combustion powered.<P>

In 1983, DOE's Argonne National Laboratory predicted a national fleet of 3 million, or approximately 2% of the total.  The Electric Vehicle Development Corp. (a group of North American utility companies) planned on introducing hundreds of commercial battery-powered van fleets by 1993.  In 1989, when oil prices again skyrocketed, it was announced that the "Big Three" automakers were once again planning to commercialize mass-produced EVs.  All these optimistic EV scenarios were predicated on higher oil prices.  Each time, when post-crisis oil prices fell, EV plans were shelved or postponed.<P> 

The 1990s EV revival could be different.  Oil prices have remained relatively stable or even fallen.  There has been little apparent incentive to switch from gasoline to electric power based on cost-effectiveness alone.  Rather, the factors encouraging EV commercialization are based on legislation-backed long 
term goals like EV's pollution reduction potential.  EV commercialization is 
now evolutionary, with incremental improvement that should continue 
irrespective of oil price. Such an EV revival would have a profound impact on the automotive industry, the battery industry, and the electric utility 
industry.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

As battery-powered vehicles become an important component of the nation's transportation infrastructure, automotive, battery, and electric utility players must develop new R&D, marketing, and promotional strategies.  Fundamental realignments in industry structure are possible.  For instance, will EVs be designed and built primarily by the world's internal combustion vehicle companies, or by start-ups specializing in EVs.  Will key EV components, especially batteries, be designed and manufactured by existing automakers or by existing battery makers? What kind of infrastructure will be developed to recharge and service EVs?  Will electric utilities develop a network of retail-level electrical power stations?  And what of the existing gasoline/diesel service infrastructure?<P>  

At the same time these fundamental realignments are occurring, there will also be ample opportunity for competitive relationships to develop within the various EV market segments. Will microcars, sedans, vans, or buses be the optimal sizes for EVs?  What specific battery types will be used, and which materials will be used to manufacture these batteries?  What kinds of battery chargers will be used?<P> 

This Business Opportunity Report is intended to be the most complete technical,
economic and business document of this type on this subject and is designed to
provide information of a professional nature.  The technical data are dependent
on the accuracy of the manufacturers and technical sources that helped make up
the BCC database.  This report is not intended to constitute a legal or 
accounting document, nor is it an endorsement of any given product or process.  
The authors, and BCC Inc. as the publisher, assume no liability for loss or 
damage as a result of reliance on this material.<P>  


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report is intended to provide a unique analysis of the U.S. EV industry and
forecast for the U.S. EV market.  It will be of interest to manufacturers of 
internal combustion and battery-powered vehicles, secondary battery makers, 
and battery charger makers.  This report will also be valuable to the electric 
utility and gasoline/diesel industry.  Existing or potential secondary vehicle 
users, including fleet operators, the government, the military, and public 
transportation providers will all eventually have to consider how EVs will 
impact their operations.  BCC wishes to thank those companies, government 
agencies and university researchers who contributed information for this 
report.<P> 


SCOPE & FORMAT

First, this report provides an overview of EV and EV-related technology, 
including a comparison with internal combustion and alternatively fueled 
vehicles.  Next, an overview of EV industry structure and competitive aspects, 
including a discussion of market segmentation, market forces, concentration 
factors, trade practices, channels of distribution, and purchasing influences.<P> 

Then, this report considers the three components that make up the EV market:<P>

<UL><LI> Vehicles & parts
   <LI>  EV batteries
   <LI>  EV battery chargers</UL><P>

Each of these markets is comprised of different market sub-sectors, and each 
is examined in terms of past, present and future sales.  Retail markets for 
1993 (estimated) and predicted for 1994, 1999, and 2004 are provided for 
several possible development scenarios. Predicted markets and average annual 
growth rates (AAGR) are expressed in constant 1994 dollars.  The overall EV 
market is discussed in terms of regional market influences.<P> 

An extensive set of industry profiles for EV and EV-related companies are 
provided. Appendixes provide a list of EV-related patents, summarize selected 
EV market development plans, and present a battery industry market activity 
chronology.  A discussion of the military EV market, non-battery EV power 
supply developments, EV safety standard developments, and a summary of the 
international EV industry are also presented as appendixes.<P> 
 

<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This report is based on a literature review, patent examination, and 
discussions with commercial and government sources.  Throughout the report, 
past market data is expressed in current dollars, and estimates and 
predictions in constant 1994 dollars.  This report defines the markets as 
sales for 1993 and predicted for 1994, 1999, and 2004.  When appropriate, 
optimistic, pessimistic and consensus scenarios are provided.  Totals are 
rounded to the nearest million dollars.  When appropriate, information from 
previously published sources is identified to allow a more detailed 
examination by clients.<P> 


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The EV battery market assumptions used in this report are based on material 
from BCC's A2GB-086N U.S. Battery Market Business Opportunity Report. The EV 
battery charger market and assumptions used in this report are based on 
material from A3GB-174, The U.S. Battery Charger Industry.  Both reports were 
prepared by this report's author.  Although many segments of the EV are well 
documented, much of this information is based on estimates, not hard facts.  
The distinction between these estimates and hard facts can be vital, and 
wherever possible, sources are identified.  The BCC monthly newsletter 
Battery/EV Technology News provides a valuable secondary source.  The U.S. 
Government Repository Patent Center located at the Fondren Library, Rice 
University, Houston, Texas provided a valuable source of U.S. patent 
information to help characterize the battery charger industry state of the 
art.<P> 


<b>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The report's project analyst, Donald Saxman, writes and edits the BCC monthly 
newsletter Battery/EV Technology News and founded several other BCC 
newsletters.  Mr. Saxman has 14 years' experience in market analysis, 
technical writing and newsletter editing.  Since 1983, he has operated as a 
technical market consultant and subcontractor to BCC.  BCC has also published 
the following related reports:<P> 

<UL> GB-086N--The U.S. Battery Industry<BR>
    E-069--Fuel Cells, On the Verge<BR>
    GB-174--The U.S. Battery Charger Industry<BR>
    GB-008N--The Competitive U.S. Market for Auto Parts</UL><P>


<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
