<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-075 FUTURE OF ELECTRIC UTILITIES: IMPACT OF NEW TECHNOLOGIES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-075 FUTURE OF ELECTRIC UTILITIES: IMPACT OF NEW
TECHNOLOGIES
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>FRANK RENAUD</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report highlights the increasing level of competition 
that is developing between electric utilities and nonutility 
generators.  The primary focus is on the impact new 
technologies will have on the structure of the electric 
power industry over the coming decade.  The report reviews 
recent developments in capacity and generation by type of 
ownership, by technology, and by fuel between 1984 and 1994.  
It stresses such factors as relative fuel prices, 
technological breakthroughs, deregulation, and the 
developments in renewable resources.  A forecast for new 
capacity, generation, and sales by type of ownership and by 
fuel through 2005 is also included.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

For the last two decades, U.S. electric utilities have seen 
their ability to serve an ever demanding public severely 
tested.  For example, because of ever increasing fossil 
fuel, environmental, and construction costs, utilities have 
had to increase the price of their electricity at rates that 
have often outpaced the more general Consumer Price Index.  
With the hope of regaining the upper hand on the efficiency 
front, utilities voted in favor of building mammoth nuclear 
plants, a move that created a public relations nightmare and 
that did little to redress the utilities' deepening 
financial problems.  Then, in the early 1980s, legislators 
decided that it was time to instill some degree of 
competition within one of the last bastions of monopolistic 
fiefdom.<P>

By the early 1990s, it was clear that the electric power 
industry was changing.  Brash nonutility generators, 
empowered by various legislative edicts and often with 
generous government subsidies if they used renewable 
resources, went on a spending spree.  By 1994, they were 
building most of the new electric generating capacity.  
These intrepid innovators were not relying on nuclear power 
nor were they relying on our vast coal reserves to generate 
their new power plants.  They were availing themselves of 
the newest technologies which included the use of renewable 
resources such as wind, solar, and biomass.  Utilities, 
short of cash and of ideas, were taken aback.  Not only were 
they losing the allegiance of large customers to those 
nonregulated entities, they were also obligated to buy 
whatever power those upstarts wanted to sell them.<P>  

Changes in regulatory thinking promise additional turmoil 
over the coming decade.  Now, several states are considering 
following in the footsteps of California to allow customers 
the freedom to purchase power from whichever generator they 
prefer.  Retail wheeling, when it becomes universal in a few 
years from now, will be the last step towards the complete 
deregulation of the generating sector of the electric power 
industry.<P>  

While deregulatory emphasis may now be on the generating 
sector, it is widely believed that the transmission and 
distribution sectors of the industry will not escape drastic 
structural changes.  Competition at the generation level 
will lead to radical changes in the technology of 
electricity generation.  That in turn will have an impact on 
the need for transmission and distribution services.  
Technological breakthroughs such as photovoltaic cell 
systems, fuel cell systems, modular natural gas turbines, 
etc. will soon lead to a distributed generation network with 
or without the participation of utilities.  Such 
developments may obviate the need for more transmission and 
distribution lines or even a curtailment of such activities.<P>  


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

In this report, we aim at answering such questions as how 
much new capacity will be needed over the coming decade to 
meet the increasing demand for electricity?  Who will build 
that capacity and which type of fuel will be used?  Which 
technology will prevail and which ones are on the brink of 
revolutionizing the industry?  We believe that strategic 
planning professionals within the utility and nonutility 
sectors will greatly benefit from our analysis.  The 
information included in this report will prove to be an 
invaluable guide for any analysis of future trends within 
the industry or for planning capital investment projects.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The study beings with an overview of the developments within 
the electric power industry between 1984 and 1994.  Our 
emphasis is on the changes in the ownership of generating 
plants, on the shifts in the use of fuels and of renewable 
resources, and on changes in regulation.  This section is 
followed by a detailed analysis of generating capacity by 
type of fuel such as coal, natural gas, nuclear power, and 
the various renewable resources (hydro, solar, biomass, 
etc.).  In each section, a detailed analysis of past trends 
in capacity and generation is provided, together with 
changes in the industry structure and technological 
developments.  A 10-year forecast for each type of capacity 
is provided, together with an outlook for equipment 
manufacturers.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

This report, like any study of this type, relies heavily on 
hard data and on the expertise of professionals in the 
field.  The insights provided by those experts are most 
appreciated.  We also wish to thank the several trade 
associations that have contributed most generously with 
their data and their interpretation.<P>



