<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
E-078 COMMERCIAL USE OF COAL COMBUSTION BYPRODUCTS: TECHNOLOGIES
AND MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bcc LogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>E-078 COMMERCIAL USE OF COAL COMBUSTION BYPRODUCTS:
TECHNOLOGIES AND MARKETS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>KEVIN GAINER</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This BCC report discusses the production and commercial uses of four specific classes of 
coal combustion by-products (known collectively as CCBs) -- fly ash, bottom ash, boiler 
slag, and flue gas desulfurization (FGD) material. Disposal of CCBs represents a 
significant, and growing, environmental problem, in view of the amount of landfill 
space that is required for disposal. Furthermore, with the increasing numbers of flue 
gas desulfurization (FGD) systems, which produce prodigious quantities of waste, 
finding useful applications for CCBs becomes imperative. The development of viable 
markets for the use of the various types and grades of CCBs is, in many cases, 
economically advantageous for both producers and consumers of CCBs. <P>

Both U.S. and international CCB developments are reported. However, the main focus 
is on CCBs generated by the U.S. electric utility sector, as opposed to industrial boilers. 
Co-managed ash wastes, which are materials resulting from the burning of coal with 
hazardous and non-hazardous wastes are generally not dealt with in this report.<P>

This report provides an up-to-date analysis of the pertinent technical and economic 
forces affecting the commercial utilization of CCBs. The report provides market 
forecasts for each of the separate markets and technologies involved. Important 
statistical and analytical information is provided for markets, applications, industry 
structure and dynamics, major players, and technology developments.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This guide to the commercial utilization of CCBs is designed to benefit those companies 
already involved in the business either as end-users of CCBs or as CCB generators or 
marketers, or companies contemplating entering the business. The study mainly 
focuses on the U.S., however, in view of the growing internationalization of business, a 
section on international developments is included. This study highlights trends in CCB 
production, technical utilization in commercial products, and R&D and identifies the 
current players and their major products and contributions within the context of the 
entire market. Specifically, the present and future markets for CCBs in construction 
and building materials, non-structural flowable fills, mining, agriculture, and waste 
management are evaluated.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Market forecasts and historical data are presented for the CCBs discussed in this 
report for a l0-year period, mainly on the basis of tons of material. Unlike most 
products, no national market exists for CCBs.  The market is extremely localized for the 
most part and most data regarding the value of uses and contracts is closely held, 
particularly with regard to the more novel uses of CCBs. The Department of Energy 
collects only minimal data on CCB production and reuse; no data are collected by the 
government on the value of re-used or recycled CCB materials.<P> 


<B>FORECASTS</B><P>

The study contains forecasts of CCB use (by tonnage) for the major end-use markets, 
including cement/concrete, flowable fill, structural fill, road base, asphalt filler, ice 
control applications, blasting grit, grouting, coal mining, wallboard, waste stabilization, 
and other miscellaneous applications. These forecasts cover these applications in all 
four classifications of CCB, including fly ash; bottom ash; boiler slag; and FGD 
material.<P>

Forecasts for niche market applications, which by their nature are lower volume uses, 
such as certain applications for cenospheres, autoclaved cellular blocks, paints and 
coatings, fillers, ashalloys, and so forth, are dealt with individually in the text of the 
report.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information for this report has evolved from a wide variety of sources, including 
interaction with companies active within the industry. Information gathered from 
telephone interviews and a comprehensive review of all the technical, patent and 
business literature available make this technical/marketing report unique in its global 
perspective of the CCB utilization industry and, hence, valuable to individuals in 
industry, government, and R&D.<P>

Sources include the American Coal Ash Association, the Electric Power Research 
Institute, the Morgantown Energy Research Center of the DOE, the Center for Applied 
Energy Research at the University of Kentucky, the American Ceramic Society, the 
Energy and Environmental Research Center of the University of North Dakota as well 
as hundreds of business, trade, and technical journals and newsletters.<P>


<B>DISCLAIMER</B><P>

The author and BCC assume no liability for the information, conclusions, or projections 
reported herein, or for their use. The developed information is intended to be as 
accurate  as possible and of a professional nature. The author assumes no liability for 
any loss or damage as a result of any reliance on any of the material or any information 
presented. The information was as accurate as possible at press time. However, due to 
the rapidly changing nature of the business, information may become outdated.<P>


