<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-174: THE U.S. BATTERY CHARGER INDUSTRY:
DEVELOPING TECHNOLOGIES AND MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-174: THE U.S. BATTERY CHARGER INDUSTRY:
DEVELOPING TECHNOLOGIES AND MARKETS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Donald Saxman
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

It is a fundamental fact that the market for battery chargers is
driven by the market for batteries.  Batteries are used to accumulate
and transport electrical energy.  These functions--power storage
and power portability--make batteries essential to today's
industrial and consumer-oriented society.  Although simple batteries
have existed for at least two hundred years, the battery industry
traces its roots to the early 1900s.  At that time, the 
commercialization of automobiles and radios created a demand for
automotive (starting, lighting, ignition and generator) batteries and
portable appliance batteries.  These markets, characterized by
primary (disposable) and secondary (rechargeable) batteries, remain
the two areas where most batteries are consumed.  With the growth of
the markets for secondary batteries, especially lead-acid batteries,
the market for lead-acid battery chargers has grown.  Starting in the
1960s, the wider commercialization of sealed nickel-cadmium batteries
and then sealed lead-acid batteries created competition between
primary and secondary batteries for some consumer applications. 
This development also created a market for whole new kinds of
battery chargers.<P>

The U.S. battery market is considered mature, with demand closely
related to the sales of either automobiles or various consumer
products.  Likewise, in many cases, the market for battery chargers is
mature.  During the last few years, there has been a subtle change in
this relationship.  Improved microelectronic battery charger
controller technology is allowing the commercialization of whole new
classes of batteries (notably rechargeable alkaline) and is improving
the marketability of existing battery systems (notably nickel-
cadmium).  This in turn has allowed the commercialization of portable
products that would be impossible without improved battery chargers
(notably portable computers and eventually, electric vehicles or EVs). 
With this in mind, there are areas where the battery charger industry
could experience the explosive growth usually associated with
emerging industries.  Battery designers (mainly electrochemists) and
battery charger designers (mainly electrical and electronics
specialists) will continue to operate together, with new batteries and
battery chargers evolving to produce even higher performance
products.<P>


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Battery and battery charger technical advances and a realignment of
the battery industry players must be matched by new marketing
attitudes. The battery charger market is much more fragmented than
the battery industry it serves.  On the other hand, battery designers
and battery charger designers now must cooperate to meet more
demanding design requirements.  Battery charger customers include
the consuming public, industrial users, and manufacturers who must
consider a charger as an integral part of a product's design.  This
Business Opportunity Report is intended to be the most complete
technical, economic and business document of this type on this
subject and is designed to provide information of a professional
nature.  The technical data are dependent on the accuracy of the
manufacturers and technical sources that helped make up the BCC
database.  This report is not intended to constitute a legal or 
accounting document, nor is it an endorsement of any given product or
process.  The authors, and BCC Inc., as the publisher, assume no
liability for loss or damage as a result of reliance on this material.<P> 


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report is intended to provide a unique analysis of the U.S.
battery charger market, and will be of interest to manufacturers of
battery charger and battery charger components.  This report also
will be valuable to those involved secondary battery development and
marketing, as well as those offering competing non-rechargeable
batteries.  Existing or potential secondary battery consumers,
including the automobile, utility, consumer appliance, computer and
medical industries, as well as the military, can determine existing or
potential battery charger markets.  These end users will learn what
charger designs battery systems will, and will not, allow.  BCC wishes
to thank those companies, government agencies and university
researchers who contributed information for this report.<P>


<b>SCOPE & FORMAT</B><P>

First, this report organizes the battery charger industry into five
markets (based on the type of consumer):<P>

<UL><LI> Consumer battery chargers
<LI> Original equipment market (OEM) battery chargers
<LI> Automotive battery chargers
<LI> Traction battery chargers
<LI> Stationary industrial battery chargers<P></UL>

Battery chargers intended for developmental battery markets are
also discussed.  The battery charger component market also is
discussed.<P> 

In some cases, there is an exact intersection between the market-
based and the technology-based organization.  With this in mind, a
market matrix is provided to compare the market organization with the
technological organization.<P>

Each of these divisions is comprised of different market sub-
sectors, and each is examined in terms of past, present and future
sales.  Wholesale markets for 1993 (estimated) and predicted 1994,
1999, and 2004 are provided.  Predicted markets and average annual
growth rates (AAGR) are expressed in constant 1994 dollars. 
Developmental battery/battery charger systems being developed for
electric vehicles, utility load leveling, and remote power storage
stations are a fourth system.  Advanced military applications are
also discussed.  In some cases, several possible development
scenarios are presented.  A detailed discussion of the companies
involved  in the battery industry is provided in this report's
Industry Profiles section.<P> 


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This report is based on a literature review, patent examination,
discussions with commercial and government sources.  Throughout the
report, past market data is expressed in current dollars, and
estimates and predictions in constant 1994 dollars.  Wholesale
markets for 1993 and predicted 1994, 1999, and 2004 are provided. 
Most market summaries are based on a consensus scenario that
assumes no unanticipated technical advances and no unexpected
legislation.  With this in mind, optimistic, pessimistic and consensus
scenarios are produced for developmental battery/battery charger
system markets.  Totals are rounded to the nearest million dollars. 
When appropriate, information from previously published sources is
identified to allow a more detailed examination by clients.<P>


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The battery market assumptions used in this report are based on
material from BCC's A2GB-086N U.S. Battery Market Business
Opportunity Report, which was prepared by this report's author. 
Although many segments of the battery industry are well documented,
much of this information is based on estimates, not hard facts.  The
distinction between these estimates and hard facts can be vital, and
wherever possible, sources are identified.  The BCC monthly
newsletter Battery/EV Technology News provides a valuable
secondary source.  The U.S. Government Repository Patent Center
located at the Fondren Library, Rice University, Houston, TX
provided a valuable source of U.S. patent information to help
characterize the battery charger industry state of the art.<P>


<b>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The report's project analyst, Donald Saxman, writes and edits the BCC
monthly newsletter Battery/EV Technology News and founded several
other BCC newsletters.  Mr. Saxman has 14 yearsu experience in market
analysis, technical writing and newsletter editing.  Previous
experience includes supervision of a quality control laboratory at a
major secondary lead refinery and experience as an analytical
chemist at a hazardous waste testing service.<P> 

BCC has also published the following related reports:<P>

<UL>GB-086N--The U.S. Battery Industry<BR>
    E-050--Uninterruptible Power Supply Systems: Continuous Data &
    Network Systems<BR>
    E-036R--Solar, Thermal, & Photovoltaic<BR>
    E-069--Fuel Cells, On the Verge<BR>
    C-175--Electrons Are Green, Opportunities in Electrosynthesis<BR>
    E-049N, Air Pollution & the Market for Monitors & Sensors<P></UL>
    

