<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-203 FOOD & FEED ENZYMES: A GLOBAL PERSPECTIVE
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-203 FOOD & FEED ENZYMES: A GLOBAL PERSPECTIVE
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>U. MARZ</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>


<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

As all world markets have become less insular and subject to
increasing international competition and opportunities,  the
need  for international information also is increasing. Many
markets   undergo  important  changes,  as   the   marketing
environment and political framework conditions change.<P>

This  may apply increasingly for the food but also  for  the
animal  feed  market,  and  especially  for  the  respective
ingredient  markets.  With  the  world  split  up  in  major
consumer markets, such as the EU and the NAFTA, and national
regulations  gradually replacing national laws,  the  market
for   food   and  feed  ingredients  is  becoming   complex,
international,  and  competitive.  It  is  more   and   more
essential  for food and feed ingredient suppliers  to  widen
their views.<P>

In  order  to  survive and grow successfully,  organizations
must  not  only take a total view of the market,  they  must
also  be  able  to  digest  greater volumes  of  information
efficiently.  It  is,  however,  not  only  the  volume   of
information  consumed  that will determine  the  ability  to
develop;  it  is  the  need  to have  information  assessed,
interpreted, analyzed, and presented.<P>

The international food ingredient market is composed of many
different  sectors of food ingredients, some  of  which  are
well analyzed. The international feed ingredient market also
is  composed of several different sectors out of which  only
amino  acids, antibiotics and other medicinal feed additives
are well analyzed.<P>


One of the fastest growing sectors, both in food as well  as
in  feed additives, is enzymes. In food, enzymes are used as
processing  aids,  while in feed they  are  used  to  better
digest  feed  stuff. Most of the enzymes used in  feed  have
developed  out of traditional food enzymes such  as  enzymes
used  for  brewing  and  baking.  Therefore  there  is  some
potential for synergies in R&D and production.<P>

Enzyme  production  has  lost some  of  its  attractiveness,
despite  the  interesting growth rates  in  demand,  because
product prices have eroded drastically.<P>

In   consequence,   many  takeovers,  joint   ventures   and
divestitures have taken place in past years.<P>

Food enzymes, as applied in the production of virtually  all
food and drink products, may strategically fit into a number
of  other  food  ingredients and, therefore,  are  preferred
targets  for consideration in diversification and completion
of product ranges.<P>

Feed  enzymes,  although traded and handled as  commodities,
are still specialties and may only fit those companies which
have some experience already in the marketing of specialties
for   the   feed  additive  market.  Many  food   ingredient
specialties  are  used also as specialties for  feed  (e.g.,
vitamins,  some pigments, antioxidants, etc.) and many  food
ingredient   suppliers  are  at  the  same  time   specialty
suppliers for the feed ingredient market.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This  report  reviews the markets for food and feed  enzymes
such as enzymes used in:<P>

     <UL>

     <LI> Starch conversion
       
     <LI> Dairy and cheese industry
     <LI> Fruit juice, wine and beer manufacture
     <LI> Flour improvement and baking
     <LI> Confectionary and specialty applications
     <LI> Broiler, layer and pig feed.

</UL>

This report tries to give an overview of the global food and
feed enzyme industry. It:<P>

     
       Reviews trends in the relevant food and feed sectors<P>
       
       Estimates the quantities of each enzyme  used  in
       specific applications<P>
       
     
       Analyzes the producing and distributing/formulating
       industry<P>
      
     
       Extrapolates the future of the food and feed enzyme
       business to the year 2000.<P>
       

Special attention is given to feed enzymes. The feed  enzyme
market  is rarely analyzed on a global scale. As the  market
already shows a global sales value comparable to that of the
dairy enzyme market, some special attention is given to  the
specific developments in this area: Details are given of the
development  of individual feed types, which  may  influence
future  growth of enzyme applications, penetration rates  of
different products in different global selling areas  and  a
profound analysis of the companies offering such products.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC  seeks to provide insight into an industry which  is  at
the  forefront of technology and which is still growing well
above other feed or food ingredients.<P>

This  report is intended to assist companies and players  in
the  food and feed additive market by providing them with  a
comprehensive  overview  of  the  industry.  Strategic   and
business  planning becomes easier and more  reliable.   Also
companies  and  players  active  in  other  food  ingredient
markets that are considering diversification into attractive
and  well-fitting sectors, one of which may be food and feed
enzymes.<P>

        
<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

After  a  review of the food and feed ingredient market  and
the  business environment, each type of enzyme is  discussed
in  relation to its application. The rationale  of  using  a
specific  type of enzyme is shown first, followed  by  price
and  margin  discussions, and estimates on current  use  and
future  developments to the year 2000. A special section  on
the production of enzymes, especially on production costs of
different  types  of enzymes, may complete the  picture  and
demonstrate  that  despite a significant erosion  of  market
prices  there  is still some room for margins. Market  share
estimates  of major and important players, company profiles,
and  a  description of how the industry works  complete  the
picture and conclude this report.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

The  methodology  which is applied in this report  is  split
into three major blocks:<P>

     
     1.   Analysis of the markets for which food and feed enzymes
       are  used. Structures and trends in these markets are
       identified. For each relevant food market, developments 
       are discussed and shown.<P>
       
     
     2.   For each of the so defined application fields, the most
       important food and feed enzymes are identified, and
       volumes and values estimated.<P>
       
     
     3.    Price  trends and estimates of production margins
       complement the picture.<P>
       

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

As  there  are only a few players in the producing  industry
and the distributing and application industries, the sources
of information are limited.<P>

In  addition  to  company reports, product brochures,  trade
journals, and many other food ingredient journals as well as
feed  ingredient and feed stuff journals, it is  mostly  the
direct contact with representatives of the relevant industry
that  provided reliable and quantitative information on  the
enzymes that ensure the high quality of this report.<P>


<B>BCC ON-LINE SERVICES</B><P>

<B>INTERNET</B><P>

Now you can locate the hard-to-find information you need  on
the Internet's World Wide Web.  By directing your browser to
Business  Communications Co.'s new "home page" you  will  be
able to:<P>

     
       Examine our complete catalog of Business Opportunity
       Reports and order directly from BCC.<P>
      
       Subscribe  to  any of our more  than  20  monthly
       technology/marketing newsletters.<P>
       

     
       Read announcements of recently published reports and
       newly launched newsletters.<P>
       

     
       Register for BCC's well-known conferences.<P>
       

     
      Request additional information about any BCC
product.<P>
       

     
      Take advantage of special offers.<P>
       

To  reach  this  important new information resource,  go  to
http/www.buscom.com<P>


<B>Direct Access</B><P>

Direct  access  to BCC on-line is achieved by calling  (203)
866-9534.<P>




