<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-047N MASS MERCHANDISED HEALTHY FOODS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-047N MASS MERCHANDISED HEALTHY FOODS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Sandra McGowan</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

In his 1991 State of the Union address, President Bush cited the
responsibility of individuals toward maintaining a healthful diet.
Increasing consumer demand for more healthful foods and beverages that
are also good-tasting and convenient was a dominant food trend of the
1980s.  Maturing of the population is the major force behind the
continued strong growth that is forecast for this market segment
during the 1990s.  Recent passage of the food labeling law will not
only benefit the consumer, it will also benefit those food and
beverage suppliers who focus on supplying more healthful foods and
beverages to meet the needs of health-conscious consumers.<P>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

BCC attempts to provide in-depth market information and insights into
future directions and opportunities for foods and beverages that have
an overall healthful image.  "Healthy" food is an evolving category
composed of products that the consumer views as being "better for
you."  Today, "healthy" foods tend to be natural products that are
fresh, low in fat or without fat, without cholesterol, relatively low
in sodium, and nutrient-dense or high in specific important nutrients
such as protein, calcium, fiber, and vitamins.  Product categories in
this "Healthy" Foods Update range from fresh fruits and vegetables to
"healthy" snacks and main meals.  They had a total market value
estimated at almost $79 billion in 1990.<P>

Some products such as granola bars, because of a change in the
consumers' image of their healthfulness, are no longer considered a
part of the "healthy" food market.  Orientation has shifted from
natural food suppliers and the health/natural-food stores that
developed the market during the early 1980s to mainstream food and
beverage producers who have achieved strong sales growth through new
product introductions.  In some categories, however, such as "new age"
beverages, emphasis is on small companies that are the leading market
innovators.  Some emerging categories such as nonfat dairy-based
frozen desserts and nonfat salad dressings along with fish/seafood,
poultry, vitamins and nutritional supplements are not included in this
analysis.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is oriented toward the needs of the health-conscious
consumer.  Many competing reports are product-oriented and do not
provide sufficient data to compare "healthy" and regular segments
within product categories.  News reports often indicate that, although
consumers say they are interested in "healthy" foods, purchasing
behavior tends toward high calorie, high-fat foods.  BCC attempts to
present relatively complete market data that substantiate increasing
consumer demand for healthful foods and beverages in the marketplace.
This strong trend is translated into forecasts for various product
segments.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM IT IS INTENDED</B><P>

Market data from a variety of sources have been analyzed and converted
to information that enables food and beverage suppliers to respond to
the increasing consumer demand for more healthful foods and beverages.
This market analysis points to emerging opportunities for food and
beverage concerns, ingredient suppliers, food consultants and other
food marketers.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This in-depth study analyzes an assortment of healthful beverages, and
fresh and processed foods for which markets are substantially
developed and sizable including:<P>

<MENU>fruit juices and fruit drinks<BR>
bottled water<BR>
sports drinks<BR>
"new age" beverages<BR>
herbal and decaffeinated teas<BR>
skim and low-fat milk<BR>
low-fat, nonfat and aspartame-sweetened yogurt<BR>
reduced-fat cottage cheese<BR>
ice milk and frozen yogurt<BR>
fresh fruits and vegetables<BR>
"healthy" cereals<BR>
healthful variety breads<BR>
"healthy" main meals<BR>
"healthy" crackers, baked snacks, and related products<BR>
dried fruits and fruit snacks<BR>
miscellaneous food products that have a healthful image</MENU><P>

Market data for both the grocery and food-service segments of the
frozen yogurt market are presented, and all distribution channels for
bottled water are covered.  New product trends and market shares for
industry leaders are also included.  In addition, BCC discusses the
impact of technology, health issues, consumer trends, and the economic
and regulatory environments on demand for "healthy" food during the
1990s.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

For most product segments, BCC presents historical growth trends for
1985 or 1986 through 1989 or 1990, often including both total
consumption and manufacturers' and retail sales.  All sales are in
current dollars.  BCC estimates for 1990 are based on available data.
Market forecasts for 1995 are compounded on an annual basis.
Forecasts take into account changing demographics, consumer trends,
new product developments, expected marketing "push" by market leaders,
the evolving regulatory climate, pricing and other economic trends.
However, the present recession and chaotic pricing for some food and
beverage segments make forecasting uncertain.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC analyzed and consolidated data from various government and
industry sources including company annual reports, business and trade
journals, government publications and newspapers.  Personal interviews
provided additional information.  The U.S.D.A. and the U.S.D.O.C.
provided production and consumption data.  Market estimates are made
by BCC based on production and market data in government publications,
Supermarket Business, Progressive Grocer, Prepared Foods, Food
Engineering, Beverage Industry, The Wall Street Journal and other
sources besides personal contacts.<P>

<B>RELATED WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The author is a trained food technologist and nutritionist.  She has
prepared numerous business opportunity reports focusing on various
segments of the industry including the "healthy" food market.  Recent
BCC reports include Opportunities in Aquaculture  and  The Fishery
Products Industry and The Seafood Market.<P>



