<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-057R: PREPARED ETHNIC FOODS-TRENDS
AND DEVELOPMENTS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-057R: PREPARED ETHNIC FOODS-TRENDS
AND DEVELOPMENTS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Dorothy Kroll
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>
 
In recent years, health professionals have advised consumers that
more plant-derived than animal-derived foods should be consumed for
a healthier diet. The diets of various nations around the world
have been cited as examples of plant-based foods, and are
correlated with health statistics showing lower incidence of such
major diseases as cancer and heart disease.<P>  
 
In addition to being healthy, ethnic foods offer new taste
experiences for nonethnic consumers. When the foods are marketed as
prepared foods, requiring minimal cooking at home, the extra
dimension of convenience is added for both ethnic and nonethnic
consumers.<P> 
 
The prepared ethnic foods market consists of two categories. One
category is comprised of those foods which are so familiar to
consumers that they are no longer considered to be specialty foods,
but rather mass market or mainstream products.<P>  
 
Prepared Italian, Mexican and Asian/Chinese foods fall into this
category because the ethnic populations have been in the U.S. for
decades and are dispersed throughout the nation. Also, nonethnics
have become familiar with the foods through eating places or
travel. The numerous eating places can include the ethnic
restaurants themselves or mainstream eateries that include the
ethnic items on their menus.<P>  
 
With such familiarity comes wide consumer demand to create large
enough markets that interest the major food processors. The major
companies, in turn, have the clout to sell their products in the
larger grocery stores and supermarkets, thereby expanding product
exposure for nonethnics.<P> 
 
The second group is made up of various ethnic populations that are
small yet growing rapidly, are more or less confined to specific
localities and regions of the nation precluding wide exposure to
nonethnics, and are more likely to have their own stores where they
prefer to buy fresh ingredients for their own food preparation.<P>   
 
Some of these ethnics are just becoming acquainted with the idea of
prepared foods for their own use as well as for nonethnic
communities interested in varying their diets. With such low
demand, major food processors show less interest. Ethnics continue
to shop in their own stores, and nonethnics get little exposure to
them because there are few products in their supermarkets.<P>  

This second group of foods includes some Mediterranean and Middle
Eastern; Caribbean; Asian in a current market consisting of
Japanese and Indian foods, and a potential market of Thai, Korean,
Vietnamese and Indonesian foods; American in a current market of
Cajun/creole and kosher/Jewish, and a potential market of black and
native Americans; and European consisting of western and eastern
foods.<P> 
 
The prepared ethnic foods considered in this report have more
similarities than differences. Most of the basic ingredients are
the same, such as rice, noodles, vegetables, chicken or fish. The
differences lie in the types of seasonings and spices used that
characterize the food's ethnicity, how the ingredients are used and
the ways that the foods are prepared and cooked.<P>   
 
Many of the products resemble one another but are called by
different names. Turnover/pocket type products, for example, are
grain-based products that are rolled and then filled with
vegetables, cheese, meat or fish, and then baked, fried or boiled.
They can be called strombolis, burritos, egg rolls, crepes,
dumplings or blintzes but they are essentially the same type of
product and just about every ethnic group has at least one. In
addition to product similarity, many of the foods touted for their
healthfulness also have some not-so-healthful aspects such as high
salt and fat content, and use of certain fats and oils for frying.<P> 
 
The goal of this report is to learn if each type of prepared ethnic
food comprises a large or small market, or a growing or static
market, and what factors related to ethnic and nonethnic consumers
affect size and growth.<P> 
 

<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P> 
 
This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:<P> 
 
<LI> To describe the fresh diets of each ethnic group and show which
products have been selected for marketing as prepared products and
which have not.<P>   
 
<LI> To compare and contrast the range and variety of prepared foods
marketed as belonging to each ethnic group.<P> 
 
<LI> To suggest the market size of each type of prepared food as
influenced by various social and market factors related to both
ethnic and nonethnic consumers.<P> 
 
<LI> To analyze the structure of the industry, and companies involved in
marketing each type of prepared ethnic product, in terms of
perceived consumer demand, real and potential market size.<P>   
 
<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>
 
BCC seeks to provide insight into one key question: Which types of
prepared ethnic foods can help consumers reach healthful dietary
goals while bringing economic health to their marketers?<P>  
 
The report examines each type prepared ethnic food and then
suggests other types of prepared foods that could be adopted from
the group's fresh diet.<P> 
 
The report presents the various types of prepared foods marketed as
a given ethnic product, and suggests why there are so many or so
few and why some are included and others excluded.<P> 
 
The report discusses the buying and eating habits of ethnics, as
well as certain social and market factors that influence both
ethnics and nonethnics, that help to create consumer demand.<P> 
 
The report analyzes why some food processors have entered the
specific prepared ethnic foods market, why they have marketed
certain products and not others, and how their entrance in specific
markets contribute to market size and growth.<P> 
 

<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P> 
 
Each type of prepared ethnic food is described in terms of its
basis, such as grains, vegetables or dairy, and then presented as
it is offered to consumers in its prepared form - frozen,
refrigerated or shelf-stable. Then social and market factors
influencing consumer demand and manufacturing trends are discussed.<P>

 

<b>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

Sales estimates and projections for each type of prepared ethnic
food were presented, some in both current markets from 1993 to 1998
and potential markets for just 1998. Estimates and projections were
developed from such factors as how long the ethnic groups have been
resident in this nation, their immigration rate, their degree of
dispersion around the nation, their buying and cooking habits and
attitudes toward prepared foods, and then how all these factors
shape the type and degree of exposure their foods will have for
nonethnics.<P> 
 
<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P> 
 
BCC first conducted an extensive review of the secondary
literature, consisting of materials gathered from trade journals
and magazines, trade and professional associations, government and
industry sources, and company materials. Subsequently, some one
hundred telephone interviews were conducted with personnel in
technical, marketing and sales departments of large and small food
processors, importers and distributors.<P> 


