<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-068R  OPPORTUNITIES IN AQUACULTURE
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-068R  OPPORTUNITIES IN AQUACULTURE
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Periodic media reports about the safety of wild fish caught in polluted
waters, the decline of some wild stocks through overfishing, and the growing
seafood component of the trade deficit have contributed to interest in
aquaculture. Water farming can provide such benefits as a year-round supply of
certain species once available only seasonally, and with consistent quality
and stable prices. Safety is also enhanced because the fish and shellfish are
grown under controlled conditions, with farmers monitoring water quality and
feeding.<P>

However, like land farming and animal husbandry, not all species can be
farmed. Species are geographically determined because water of certain types
and temperatures is needed, and not all farmable species will be commercially
viable. Moreover, for even those species which can be farm-raised, there can
be different types of constraints. For example, less costly imports are
impeding the growth of domestic shrimp farming, while it is disease that is
endangering the future industry of oysters grown on the east coast. Lack of
available and appropriate sites are also problems confronting new and
expanding farms of rainbow trout, salmon and shrimp.<P>


Once the site and species have been selected, the farmer has to control
production costs in order to remain competitive with the price of imports or
wild-caught fish, as well as deal with mortality from disease, pollution and
predators, and conflicts with recreational fishermen and environmentalists.<P>

The goal of this report is to understand how farmers of freshwater and marine
species are dealing with each type of situation or problem, and suggest what
this means for the future growth of aquaculture as an industry, as well as for
each farmed species.<P>

Farms are mostly small mom-and-pop operations, often growing only one species.
Often, however, some farms are part of large operations.  Some operations
serve their markets directly while others use wholesalers and distributors to
sell to end-user markets. In some cases, farms have processing facilities on-site. In other situations, processors have agreements with farmers who supply
them steadily  and/or serve as their marketing units.  Farmers as primary processors have a wide range of seafood suppliers serving as middlemen that help bring products to foodservice operators and retailers: secondary processors who prepare the fish in some ready-to-eat form, wholesaler/distributors, trader/brokers or importer/exporters. Some suppliers actually fulfill all these roles, handle many species, and buy from both farmers and commercial fishermen.<P>

In this report, fish and shellfish are categorized as freshwater or
marine/saltwater species. Freshwater varieties include catfish, crawfish,
rainbow trout, hybrid striped bass and tilapia.  Marine varieties include
salmon, shrimp, oysters, clams and mussels. These species are raised in
various types of onshore and offshore rearing units. Depending upon stage of
growth, some species can be grown onshore and then transferred into some type
of offshore unit for continued growth.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:<P>

<UL><LI>To identify which species are the most commercially viable for farmers,
processors and other types of seafood suppliers.<P>

<LI>To describe the domestic factors (geographical location, growing period,
market size, production costs, price and supply of wild stock) and
international competitive factors (price and supply of imports) that farmers
and suppliers must contend with in order to meet production costs and realize
a profit.<P>

<LI>To understand how consumer demand is shaped by regional tastes, income, age,
pricing, health attitudes and safety concerns, and how this demand promotes or
hinders the growth of individual species.<P>

<LI>To discuss the technological and regulatory trends that either foster or
retard the development of farming and marketing farmed fish and shellfish.<P>

<LI>To analyze the structure of the farming and supplier industry, how size and
complexity of farming operations can affect channels of distribution from farm
to end-user. To ascertain opportunities for food processors, suppliers,
cooperatives and farms.</UL><P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC strives to provide insight into one key question:  With which species can
farmers and suppliers best achieve economic viability, by meeting production
costs and still keep prices competitive and affordable for end-users?  To this
end, the report:<P>

<UL><LI>Compares and contrasts freshwater and marine species in terms of domestic
    and international competitive factors that affect supply, pricing and the
    economic viability of domestic farmers;<P>

<LI>Discusses the demographic, social and economic factors, both in the U.S.
    and in foreign nations, that shape consumer demand for individual species
    from domestic farmers;<P>

<LI>Examines how marketing strategies used by farmers and processors can
    expand markets and satisfy needs and interests of different types of
    consumers, e.g. trading a species up or down to increase sales;<P>

<LI>Explores technological trends that can advance growth of aquaculture, and
    regulatory trends that can impede or promote the status of the industry;<P>

<LI>Describes how size of farming operation, number of species raised and
    marketing strategy influence the use and type of channels of distribution
    from farm to end-user.</UL><P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study is confined to aquacultured products only insofar as they  are used
as a food source and not for any other purpose.  BCC discusses each freshwater
and marine species in terms of how it is farmed and produced, market outlook
for farmer and processor sales, market and driving forces influencing the
selection of species and growth of farming, industry structure and types of
suppliers, and international trade environment.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

BCC discusses each species in terms of type of rearing unit needed, water,
feeding, problems and conflicts that can arise, and marketing aspects. The
market outlook for each species is then discussed, presenting sales for
domestic farmers and processors, as well as imports and exports. Profiles of
certain farming operations are  presented, either because they are leaders in
their states or are doing something particularly new with a species. Major
suppliers of some farmed species are also described.<P>

BCC sales estimates and projections for each species were calculated according
to historical trends indicated in materials compiled by government and
industry sources, and/or evaluations discussed during interviews with farmers,
processors and other types of seafood suppliers. Some species are not tracked
by government or industry sources, either because they are just beginning to
be farmed or because figures are not broken down into farmed and wild-caught.
In these cases, estimates were made of the percentage of the total represented
by the farmed varieties.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first conducted an extensive review of the secondary literature,
consisting of materials gathered from trade journals and magazines, trade
associations, state promotional boards, government and industry sources, and
materials from farm operations and seafood suppliers. Subsequently, some one
hundred telephone interviews were conducted with farmers, marketing and sales
personnel at suppliers, as well as technical, research and development
personnel at farming operations and sea grant programs.<P>

