<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-069  THE WEIGHT CONTROL INDUSTRY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> GA-069  THE WEIGHT CONTROL INDUSTRY
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I> DOROTHY KROLL </I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This study indicates that there is increasing worldwide consumer
interest in weight control products and services because they are
related to healthful living as much as they are to controlling
weight. Specifically, the weight control industry is composed of
separate and distinct industries marketing foods, beverages,
medically and non-medically supervised weight loss programs, and
diet aids that an individual selects in a self-designed,
self-administered weight loss program.<P>

Studies report that the number of people actually on diets slightly
declines each year, suggesting that diet foods and beverages are
being used for purposes other than weight reduction. Consumers
choose diet brands, when available, as alternatives to regular
brands because they reduce or eliminate the intake of certain
ingredients associated with some health risks and disorders, as
well as caloric intake.<P>

For the individual serious about losing weight, there are other
choices in addition to consuming diet foods and beverages. They
include a wide range of supervised weight reduction programs in a
variety of settings, and self-selected diet aids in the form of
over-the-counter (OTC) meal-replacements and appetite suppressants.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

* To learn how global media information influences the development
of attitudes regarding the link between obesity and health
disorders as well as the latest diet fad, and how this knowledge
subsequently influences buying decisions of certain diet products
and services.<P>

* To gain understanding of the multi-national, multi-faceted
consumer who strives to be fit on the one hand, and longs to
self-indulge in a calorie-laden taste pleasure pursuit on the
other, thereby enabling both market segments to grow in sales.<P>

* To analyze current diet foods and beverages that best suit
consumer needs in relation to societal and cultural trends, and
expected products from research and technological advances that can
further benefit weight control and health.<P>

* To compare and contrast supervised weight reduction  programs
designed for different types of overweight persons with varying
psychological, social and physiological needs, as well as time and
money allowances.<P>

* To describe the needs and goals of the self-directed dieter, the
various OTC choices available to meet those needs, and to suggest
how product selections are influenced by the success or failure of
food supplements used in the supervised programs.<P>

BCC recognizes the problems and criticisms that periodically bring
to the public's attention certain types of weight loss programs and
foods labelled as diet, low calorie, and the like.  Each situation
is usually characterized by an initial flurry of media coverage,
followed by rejoinders from the companies and persons involved, and
even promises of governmental scrutiny.  This high level of
activity reflects the public's interest in weight loss per se and
as it relates to health, as well as the size of the potential
market for all types of weight loss products and services.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

* Suggests the impact that health information and diet news have on
consumer buying patterns here and abroad, and how perceived health
and weight loss benefits can contribute to the sales growth of diet
products and services.<P>

* Provides insight into consumers as individuals with sometimes
seemingly contradictory tastes and preferences, so that
international marketers can better understand consumer motivations
and develop products and services to satisfy them.<P>

* Discusses diet foods and beverages that best fit into current
cultural, social and living patterns, and accordingly suggests
areas of growth or decline for specific products.<P>

* Delineates characteristics of the various medically and
non-medically supervised weight reduction programs, discusses their
components and how each is designed to meet certain consumer needs
and interests in the US and foreign markets.<P>

* Explores the motivations of the self-directed dieter, examines
the range of product choices in the OTC diet aid market and
suggests how the role of publicity and media information can
influence sales growth.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report was confined to diet foods and beverages, supervised
weight control programs and self-administered OTC diet aids. These
products and services are promoted as aids in weight control and/or
healthful living, and marketers use such terms as "diet," "weight
loss," "weight control" or "weight reduction" to describe them<P>.


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

BCC describes each type of weight control product and service, then
evaluates it in terms of how it fits into various social trends --
current lifestyles, family and household composition, health
attitudes and varying consumer characteristics in the domestic and
foreign markets.<P>

When discussing weight control programs, BCC first estimates and
projects the number of severely and mildly overweight people who
might be interested in entering some type of weight reduction
program, develops average costs for each type of program, and
analyzes social and product trends within each in order to
formulate sales forecasts.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first conducted an extensive search of secondary sources,
including the business, consumer and health literature. This was
followed by more than one hundred telephone interviews, including
manufacturers of diet and weight control products, marketing,
technical and sales personnel in industry, trade and professional
associations, independent retailers and service providers. Where
precise information was difficult to ascertain, a common occurrence
in such a highly fragmented industry, BCC attempted to formulate
reasonable estimates and projections.<P>

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>


