<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-070 FLAVORS AND FLAVOR DEVELOPMENT FOR
AND GENERIC CUSTOM/SPECIALITY MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> GA-070 FLAVORS AND FLAVOR DEVELOPMENT FOR
AND GENERIC CUSTOM/SPECIALITY MARKETS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This BCC study sought to understand how flavor companies are
responding to the changing needs of food and beverage
manufacturers as they, in turn, respond to the shifting needs
and interests of consumers.<P>

The flavor industry is composed of flavor companies, of varying
size and scope, that develop flavors and flavor systems. Food
and beverage  makers are, essentially, in the flavor business,
too, because flavor is actually what they are selling in any
given product. The unique taste of an item is the chief
motivating factor for a consumer to make repeated purchases, and
allows the consumer to associate it with a particular
manufacturer's brand.<P>

Consumers seem to have an almost insatiable appetite for new
flavors incorporated in either new or existing products. But
while new, distinctive flavors have always given manufacturers
their competitive edge, recent techniques of processing,
packaging, and marketing have posed problems with flavor loss or
change that require the skills and expertise of flavor houses.
A customized solution, involving special flavoring substances
and ingredients, or techniques for flavor development, must be
developed in order to fit the individual requirements of that
particular application.<P>

By trying to satisfy consumer demands for more convenient and
healthful foods, while still maintaining flavor, manufacturers
are sometimes forced to look for ways to protect flavor quality.
Consumers want microwaveable, chilled/refrigerated and
shelf-stable foods that can be cooked in the microwave oven or
are otherwise easy to prepare and consume. Consumers also want
healthful versions of regular products that have their fat,
cholesterol, salt and sugar reduced or removed.<P>

For the purposes of this report, BCC has defined two distinct
markets shaped by these differing needs of manufacturers. The
generic flavor market includes those off-the-shelf flavors
developed by flavor companies that are available to all who
request them. The custom flavor market includes flavors
developed specifically upon request, available only to those
contracting for them. Customized flavors can be new flavors
meant to gain market share, or flavors developed as remedies for
a flavor problems.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

To compare and contrast the various forces shaping the generic
and custom flavor markets, for food and beverage makers, in
order to understand what influences each market has on the
development of specific flavor types, food types and flavoring
substances.<P>

To identify the driving forces for flavor houses as they seek to
satisfy manufacturers by determining trends in consumer
preferences, finding new flavors and new sources for flavors,
discovering flavor substances and ingredients that maintain
flavor integrity as well as ensure safety, and devising ways to
protect flavor quality in each type of application that requires
an individualized solution.<P>

To determine the specific consumer attitudes and perceptions
linked to each type of flavor and food type so that flavor
companies and manufacturers can gain insight into how their
flavors and products are viewed in the public mind.<P>

To analyze the structure of the flavor industry, and the nature
and type of flavor houses, in order to gain insight into how
they are able to respond to the demands and concerns of food and
beverage makers.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

Suggests the demographic, social, economic, regional and
seasonal factors that can shape consumer preferences for
specific flavors, food types and flavoring substances, and how
manufacturers must respond to consumer needs of convenience and
foods with healthful benefits.<P>

Discusses the role of flavor houses and flavorists as they
combine their artistic and scientific skills to translate
consumer demands for various flavors and food types from food
and beverage makers, and accordingly suggests areas of growth or
decline for each type.<P>

Examines the impact of information on the development of
perceptions, and sometimes even misperceptions that, in turn,
influence the formation of consumer demands for given flavors
and food types.<P>

Analyzes the general atmosphere of secrecy and confidentiality
in the flavor industry, and how certain factors such as prices
for raw materials and regulations for manufacturers will
directly and indirectly affect the conduct of the industry's
business.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

BCC has defined flavors as the finished flavor blend or mixture
that industrial users will incorporate into a commercially
prepared item,  ultimately to be purchased by a consumer in a
retail setting. We have confined this report to examining
industrial users only, the food and beverage manufacturers,
rather than including food service or retail/consumer users.
While all types of foods are considered, only soft drinks,
bottled waters and teas are considered for beverages.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

BCC describes the flavor types and food types in the generic and
custom markets, then evaluates each market in terms of how it is
being shaped by certain market forces exerted by consumers --
current lifestyles, population and social trends, and health
attitudes, exerted on industrial users, and how the latter are
calling upon flavor houses as a means of responding to
consumers.<P>

BCC first makes estimates and projects for the industrial
market, then by type of market for each type of industrial user,
and then used these breakdowns for further analyses of flavor
types, food types and flavoring substances.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first conducted an extensive search of the secondary
literature, including business, consumer and technical materials
from the trade and professional press and government sources.
Subsequently, we conducted more than one hundred telephone
interviews with flavor houses, food and beverage makers, and
suppliers, manufacturers and brokers of various substances and
ingredients.  Interviewees included marketing, sales and
technical personnel. Where precise information was difficult to
ascertain, a common phenomenon in such a highly secretive,
competitive business, BCC attempted to formulate reasonable
estimates and projections.<P>

 
