<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-072  INGREDIENTS AND ADDITIVES FOR THE DAIRY INDUSTRY</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-072  INGREDIENTS AND ADDITIVES FOR THE DAIRY INDUSTRY</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goal of this report is to understand how suppliers of
ingredients and additives for the dairy industry are responding to
the changing needs of dairy makers as they, in turn, respond to the
changing needs and interests of consumers of dairy products.<P>

At one time, consumers looked to dairy products as a nutritious,
wholesome part of their diets, and the sole consumer concern was
how a product tasted. However, an increasing body of scientific and
medical evidence pointing to the dangers of cancer risks of
chemicals used in foods, health risks of fat, cholesterol and salt,
and health and weight problems associated with sugar and fats, has
influenced the development of certain consumer attitudes toward
dairy foods. These attitudes have shaped preferences for what
consumers demand and expect from dairy products.<P>

Essentially, today's consumers are concerned with what is taken
out, left out, and put into dairy foods. But they also care
strongly about what is left in, and are unwilling to compromise on
flavor, texture, appearance and safety. With such strong consumer
demands and expectations, dairy makers have been forced to change
formulations, and they look to their suppliers to provide them with
the necessary materials.<P>

Suppliers, then, are required to develop and market ingredients and
additives that will enable dairy makers to deliver products that
meet consumer demands. The supplier industry is highly fragmented
and composed of flavor houses, food and dairy processors -- some
with ingredient divisions -- ingredient suppliers and growers,
chemical and pharmaceutical companies. Any one type of company can
be involved in marketing one or more kinds of substances.<P>

In this report, BCC has defined ingredients and additives as those
substances that can change or improve a product component, namely
its flavor, texture, color-appearance, safety and nutritional
value. Further, ingredients are defined as those substances used
for their flavoring properties, and which could be consumed on
their own, such as a fruit.  Additives are defined as substances
used for their technological effects, not to be consumed on their
own, and include all natural and synthetic substances used for
flavoring, texture, color, as preservatives (mold/yeast inhibitors)
and as nutrients (vitamins).<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The report was designed:<P>

<MENU><LI>To identify specific areas of concern for consumers
     regarding health, nutrition and food safety, and analyze
     how these concerns affect consumption of various dairy
     products.<P>

<LI>To gain understanding of consumer interests in product
     appeal, flavor, nutrition, safety and healthful, light
     versions of regular products and to suggest how these
     interests affect ingredients and additives marketed by
     suppliers and used by dairy makers.<P>

<LI>To learn how the economic, regulatory and technological
     climate helps or hinders dairy makers in the development
     of products that consumers want.<P>

<LI>To analyze the role of supplier as problem-solver, and
     the structure of the supplier industry as it tries to
     help dairy makers develop products that consumers demand
     by providing functional, cost- competitive ingredients
     and additives.</MENU><P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC sought to provide insight into one key question: How can
suppliers help dairy makers( and with what types of ingredients and
additives) develop and market products that satisfy consumer
demands? The study:<P>

<MENU><LI>Discusses the medical, health, demographic, social and
     economic influences that contribute to the development of
     attitudes and preferences about the components of dairy
     products, and how they affect consumption patterns.<P>

<LI>Suggests how these consumption patterns will affect the
     markets for certain ingredients and additives required by
     dairy makers from suppliers, and how these markets could
     grow or decline in the future.<P>

<LI>Examines how the prices of raw materials, the force of
     regulations,  research and technological developments can
     limit or aid dairy makers in the development of products.<P>

<LI>Describes how suppliers are similarly constrained or
     helped in their pursuit of ingredients and additives that
     could solve development problems for dairy makers.</MENU><P>

The insights and conclusions developed in this study can be of
value to suppliers who are trying to meet the needs of dairy makers
who are themselves trying to understand what consumers want from
dairy foods. This information can serve as a guide to suppliers who
must develop ingredients and additives that will best serve their
clients.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

BCC has confined this report to examining the need for ingredients
and additives only for processed dairy products and excluding fluid
milk products. Included for consideration are cultured products,
such as cottage cheese, sour cream and yogurts; processed cheese
and cheese products; frozen desserts, such as ice cream, ice milk,
frozen yogurt, frozen dairy desserts, novelty bars, sticks and
cones.<P>

Further, BCC is concerned with the non-milk solid components of
these products. Specifically, the flavor section deals with all
those ingredients and additives meant to influence taste. The
texture section is chiefly concerned with "light" products, the
textural changes occurring from the reduction or removal of fat,
cholesterol, sugar and salt, and how fat replacers, sugar
substitutes and bulking agents are compensating for the losses. The
section dealing with colors describes the various natural and
certified colors used in dairy products. The section on
preservatives includes only mold/yeast inhibitors, and the section
on nutrients discusses only vitamins.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

BCC describes the ingredients and additives used in each component
of dairy products, then evaluates each in terms of how it is being
shaped by consumer demands, then discusses how dairy makers are
working to satisfy these demands and how suppliers are responding
to the needs of dairy makers. Estimates and projections of sales
for ingredients and additives were calculated according to expected
growth or decline in  consumption patterns of certain dairy
products, and the perceived  need for substances in these products
in relation to various consumer, dairy manufacturing and supplier
trends.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first conducted an extensive review of the secondary
literature, and obtained materials from trade and professional
associations, government and industry sources and company reports.
This review was followed up with one hundred telephone interviews
with personnel in technical, quality control, marketing and sales
departments and food science and with dairy researchers working at
academic sites.<P>


