<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE> GA-073  NEW DEVELOPMENTS IN FARM MACHINERY:
OPPORTUNITIES IN NEW TECHNOLOGIES, SELECTED EQUIPMENT AND OVERSEAS
MARKET
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> GA-073  NEW DEVELOPMENTS IN FARM MACHINERY:
OPPORTUNITIES IN NEW TECHNOLOGIES, SELECTED EQUIPMENT AND OVERSEAS
MARKET
</H2>
<HR><P>
<I>HEBER BOULAND</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>


<P>This study is designed to provide facts and highlight issues to help you make better
business decisions -- to help you discover farm machinery opportunities through
information on:</P>

         <P>1.       Trends in domestic farm machinery demands</P>

         <P>2.       How the industry is structured, and how it's changing</P>

         <P>3.       Emerging farm machinery technology</P>

         <P>4.       The impact of new laws and regulations</P>

         <P>5.       What equipment is hot and what's not</P>

         <P>6.       Major shifts in the worldwide farm machinery trade.</P>


<B>REASONS FOR THE STUDY</B>

<P>One, changing domestic farming practices are dramatically changing the demands for
farm machinery.  Economics and regulations, such as the Conservation Compliance
Provision and various environmental laws, will continue to drive farmers to purchase
different types of machines.</P>

<P>Second, new farm machinery technology is emerging, such as sensors that more
accurately measure soil fertility and other field conditions, navigation systems
operating from space satellites that locate the tractor's field position, and precision
devices controlling tillage, seeding, and chemical applications.</P>

<P>Third, farm machinery sales have been slow for several years, farmers have postponed
machinery purchases, and the stock of farm machinery is aging.  How long can the
trend continue?  When will the market turn around?</P>

<P>Fourth, worldwide food demands are growing, but the availability of additional arable
and irrigated lands are limited.  Since crop yields can't be easily increased through
more chemicals without environmental degradation, use of more farm machinery may
well be the answer.  Also globalization and liberalization of markets are having an
impact on farm machinery trade.</P>

<P>Moreover, most of the major farm machinery manufacturers also produce construction
equipment such as bulldozers, graders, etc. -- equipment used in building highways,
railroads, and utility lines.  The demand for this type of equipment should improve
by 1994 as Clinton's program for rebuilding the country's infrastructure is
implemented.  Chapter VIII on company profiles provides information on the extent
to which individual farm machinery firms produce construction equipment.</P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B>

<P>This report will be valuable to a wide variety of people interested in farm machinery.
It will:</P>

         <P>Help investors and lenders evaluate where the industry is going, and who the
         potential losers and winners may be;</P>

         <P>Provide major machinery producers with information useful in strategic
         planning and forecasting;</P>

         <P>Help short line manufacturers stay ahead of the market and find areas
         of opportunity;</P>

         <P>Help machinery brokers, distributors, and farm cooperatives plan storage and
         distribution systems and discover marketing opportunities;</P>

         <P>Help firms that supply farm machinery manufacturers with goods and services,
         e.g., supplies of high tech sensors, find the best markets;</P>

         <P>Provide importers and exporters with information on potential markets;</P>

         <P>Assist analysts and consultants to the farm machinery industry in advising their 
         clients.</P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>This study covers primarily machinery used in field crop production and harvesting -
- tillage, seeding, chemical applicators, cultivators, haymaking, and combines.  To a
lesser degree, it covers irrigation equipment.  It does not cover post harvesting,
livestock, or dairy equipment.  All statistics refer to new as opposed to used machinery
unless otherwise noted.  In the report the term "farm machinery" usually means farm
machinery and equipment.</P>

<P> Following this introductory chapter are:</P>

         <P>Chapter II - An executive summary highlighting the findings</P>

         <P>Chapter III - An overview of the farm machinery industry</P>

         <P>Chapter IV - Forecasts of domestic farm machinery demand</P>

         <P>Chapter V - Forecasts of farm machinery demand for four regions: corn,
         cotton, dairy, and wheat.</P>

         <P>Chapter VI - New technology developments</P>

         <P>Chapter VII - International aspects</P>

         <P>Chapter VIII - Details of the industry structure, the major firms, and
         what they are doing</P>

         <P>Chapter IX - Government incentives and regulations</P>

         <P>Chapter X - Profiles of major companies</P>

         <P>Chapter XI - References.  Lists of more than 100 references: books,
         articles, reports, etc.</P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>This research is based on a review of the literature, a survey of knowledgeable people,
and collection and analysis of statistics -- the various sources listed in the next
section.  A survey was made of experts in major agricultural producing states.   The
experts include more than 120 county agricultural extension agents plus agricultural
economists, agricultural and mechanical engineers, farm equipment dealers,
manufacturers, and other specialists.   Discussions were held with officials of: USDA,
Department of Commerce, various think tanks, trade associations, Congressional staff,
the World Bank, and USAID.  In addition, time series and regression analysis were
used to project demand.</P>




<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>The following are the major published data sources:</P>

         <B>DOMESTIC MARKET TRENDS</B>

<UL>
                  <LI>USDA's Agricultural Resources

                  <LI>U.S. Census of Manufactures

                  <LI>International Trade Commission reports.

                  <LI>FAPRI, 1992 Agricultural Outlook

                  <LI>U.S. Census Current Industrial Reports

                  <LI>Various industry newsletters, i.e., EMI
</UL>

         <B>WORLDWIDE TRADE</B>

<UL>
                  <LI>FAPRI, 1990 World Agricultural Outlook

                  <LI>U.S. Department of Commerce's import and export data

                  <LI>FAO publications on trade

                  <LI>UN International Statistics on Trade handbook

                  <LI>Euromonitor, International Marketing Data and Statistics 1992

         <B>INDUSTRY STRUCTURE</B>

<UL>
                  <LI>Annual reports of major firms

                  <LI>Wards' Business Directory

                  <LI>Dun's Business Directory
</UL>

<P>In addition, more than a hundred articles or reports were reviewed.</P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK AND CREDENTIALS</B>

<P>Since 1971 Business Communications Company, Inc., (BCC), has provided important
technical and economic studies that address vital concerns in marketing and strategic
planning.  BCC has specialized in the areas of chemicals, foods, energy, and materials.
Heber Bouland, the project analyst, has a Bachelors Degree in Agricultural
Engineering and a Masters Degree in Engineering Administration.  He worked nine
years at USDA in agricultural marketing research and thirteen years at the U.S.
General Accounting Office in evaluating agricultural and related programs and
policies.</P>

<P>Related BCC studies include:</P>

<UL>
         <LI>Biotechnology in Agriculture:  New Technologies, Product Development,
         Markets, GA-051R, Nov. '85.

         <LI>Biotechnology in Plant and Animal Agriculture, (Conference report), Stamford,
         CT., April 12 & 13, 1985.

         <LI>THE AGRICULTURAL CHEMICALS INDUSTRY:  Regulations, Technology,
         Economic Change and New Profit Opportunities, BCC, INC., Norwalk, CT.,
         April 1991.
</UL>



 

