<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-074 NUTRITIONALLY BENEFICIAL INGREDIENTS AND ADDITIVES
FOR PROCESSED FOODS AND BEVERAGES</H2>
<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

     The goal of this  report is to understand  how suppliers  of
     nutritional ingredients and  additives used by food and
     beverage makers are responding  to their changing needs, as
     they in turn, respond to the changing needs and preferences of
     increasingly health-conscious consumers.<P>

     Although taste  is still king, consumers have been paying more
     and more  attention to  what they eat and how it affects their
     health. With  health professionals  advising consumers what to
     consume and  what to  avoid, the media highlighting the latest
     scientific and medical evidence about substances in foods that
     pose health risks, and the government taking a direct interest
     in food  labeling and  health claims,  the consumer has become
     highly aware  of what  goes into food and what should be taken
     out.<P>

     This heightened  awareness has  influenced the  development of
     attitudes, preferences  and  demands  for  certain  foods  and
     beverages. Today's consumers want products that promote health
     by providing  the extra  bonus  of  nutrition  and  protective
     influences against certain disorders.<P>

     Foods and  beverage makers can foster this desired wellness in
     two basic ways. One way is to fortify products with substances
     that provide  protective influences  against certain  diseases
     and conditions.  These protective  substances are  included in
     two groups.  One group  includes currently marketed fortifiers
     that  are  accepted  by  health  professionals  as  protective
     influences, such  as vitamins,  minerals, proteins,  fiber and
     omega-3 oils. The other group includes substances still in the
     research stage,  such as  extracts of  garlic, certain spices,
     caffeine and  tea, to  determine if  they can be extracted for
     later incorporation  as protective  influences into  so-called
     designer foods.<P>

     The second  way to  market healthful  products is to reduce or
     remove those  ingredients that  are related  to health  risks.
     Fat, cholesterol,  sugar and  salt are ingredients linked with
     such conditions  as cancer, heart disease, obesity and related
     problems, and  hypertension. In  order for  consumers to lower
     their intake  of these ingredients, manufacturers must develop
     "light" versions  of the  products containing  them, and  this
     requires  the   use  of   various  types   of  replacers   and
     substitutes.<P>

     While the  consumer does  want to  reap health  benefits  from
     foods, this  does not  mean that  there can be any compromises
     with flavor, texture and appearance. In order to fully satisfy
today's savvy  consumers, manufacturers  must offer  all these
characteristics  in   addition  to   health   benefits.   This
formidable task,  then, falls  to  suppliers  to  develop  the
substances that  will enable  manufacturers  to  deliver  what
consumers want.<P>

The highly fragmented supplier  industry is composed of small
companies  serving  niche  markets,  and  giant  companies  or
company divisions  that offer  the whole  range of nutritional
ingredients  and   additives.   Suppliers   include   chemical
companies, food  and beverage makers, ingredient suppliers and
flavor houses.<P>

In this  report, BCC  has defined ingredients and additives as
those substances  that  can  change  or  improve  a  product's
nutritional and  health value  either  by  theirtcw  addition,
reduction or  removal. In  some cases,  the  terms  were  used
interchangeably, but  generally the  additives  refer  to  the
current and  future protective  substances  incorporated  into
products, while  the ingredients  refer to the substances that
are to be reduced or removed.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The report was designed:<P>

<MENU><LI>To  identify  specific  areas  of  concern  to  consumers
     regarding  nutrition,   health   promotion,   risks   and
     benefits, and  analyze how  these  concerns  have  shaped
     attitudes that,  in  turn,  have  influenced  buying  and
     consumption patterns of foods and beverages.<P>

<LI>To gain understanding of consumer demands that influence
     consumption patterns  in order  to suggest  how they will
     affect  manufacturers   who  will   ultimately  rely   on
     suppliers to  provide them with the necessary ingredients
     and additives.<P>

<LI>To learn how  the  social,  economic,  regulatory  and
     technological environment  aid or hamper manufacturers in
     the development  and marketing  of  products  that  would
     satisfy consumer demand.<P>

<LI>To analyze  the role  of suppliers,  the structure of the
     supplier  industry,  and  indicate  how  the  efforts  of
     suppliers are  moving in  various directions  in order to
     develop the  ingredients and additives needed by food and
     beverage makers.</MENU><P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC sought to provide insight into one key question:  How, and
with what types of ingredients and additives, can suppliers
serve food and beverage  makers interested in satisfying
consumer demands for healthful and health-promoting products?<P>

<MENU><LI>Discusses  the   medical,  health,  social,  demographic,
     marketing and  economic influences  that  shape  consumer
     preferences and  demands for  foods  and  beverages  that
     foster good  health and  reduce the  harmful  effects  of
     certain ingredients.<P>

<LI>Suggests how  consumer  shifts  in  attitudes  result  in
     shifts  in  consumption  patterns  that  will  ultimately
     affect manufacturers' higher or lower demands for certain
     ingredients and additives from suppliers.<P>

<LI>Examines the  key ingredients and additives as related to
     factors, such  as price,  functionality, caloric content,
     ability to cause flavor or texture problems, and how they
     affect choices  made by  food and  beverage  makers  from
     their suppliers.<P>

<LI>Analyzes such  market forces as regulations, research and
     technology,  and   how  they  either  advance  or  retard
     development of  new, and  growth of existing, ingredients
     and additives  that suppliers  can provide  to  food  and
     beverage makers.</MENU><P>

The insights and conclusions reached in  this study can be
valuable to suppliers of food ingredients to food and beverage
makers.  They can help them develop  products that will enable
the latter to stay competitive or even gain a competitive
edge.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

BCC has  confined this  report to  examining only  nutritional
ingredients and  additives, those current or future substances
that can either promote health through fortification, or serve
as replacers  for substances  reduced or  removed in  order to
minimize health risks.<P>

The first  section deals with the vitamins, minerals and
proteins that are current,  familiar  fortifiers.  The next
section deals with some recently identified fortifiers in use,
namely fiber and omega-3 oils, as well as those natural
protective substances  that are being researched for their
value as future fortifiers. The final section is called risk-
reducers because the ingredients related to health risks are
reduced or removed and are replaced with a variety of
substances, including full and partial fat replacers,
artificial sweeteners, bulking agents and salt substitutes.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

BCC describes the ingredients and additives in each section by
evaluating each in terms  of its health benefits or risks for
consumers, the need for fortification or replacement of each,
its nutritional and functional value for manufacturers and any
disadvantages or  technical problems each can pose, its use in
processed foods  and beverages,  and the market forces shaping
consumer interests.  Then, there is discussion of how food and
beverage makers are trying to satisfy these demands, what they
require from  their suppliers, and how suppliers are trying to
develop the  desired substances.  Estimates and projections of
sales  for   each  ingredient  and  additive  were  calculated
according to  expected growth  or decline  in  consumption  of
certain foods  and beverages;  taking into account advantages,
disadvantages, limitations,  price and  technical problems for
manufacturers,   health    problems   for    consumers;    and
manufacturing and supplier trends that exert influence on each
substance.<P>

