<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-076  NEW CONVENIENCE FOODS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-076  NEW CONVENIENCE FOODS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>CAROL CURTIS</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The main goal of this study is to provide a guide to business
opportunities in the new convenience food industry.  It examines
each of the major categories of convenience foods, discusses past
trends, and details the prospects for future growth.<P>

A secondary goal is to inform readers in business and government
about the new convenience food industry. This industry is not
tracked as a separate category by any trade association, government
agency, or company.  Data were gathered through firsthand
interviews with experts in business, government, and on Wall
Street, in addition to primary sources such as company data,
libraries, and private research reports.<P>

This comprehensive study:<P>

<DD>1) Defines the new convenience food industry;<BR>
<DD>2) Provides insight into technological developments and their
   impact on the industry;<BR>
<DD>3) Examines each segment of the industry and its relationship to
   the industry as a whole;<BR>
<DD>4) Explores government regulation of the food industry as it
   relates to new convenience foods;<BR>
<DD>5) Analyzes the industry by types of companies involved, areas
   of fast and slow growth, and influencing factors, including
   mergers and acquisitions, the environmental movement, the
   economic climate, and research and development;<BR>
<DD>6) Examines the impact of consumption trends on the new
   convenience food industry;<BR>
<DD>7) Discusses international developments and their relationship
   to the U.S. convenience food industry;<BR>
<DD>8) Makes informed forecasts about the direction of the industry
   as a whole, and of individual segments.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This study to provides an in-depth guide to the past, present and
future of the new convenience food industry, and identifies
business and marketing opportunities for those involved in the
industry.<P>

The study was also done because there is no single source of
information on the convenience food industry.  Some industry
segments, such as frozen foods, are tracked by trade associations
and the government.  However, there is no "umbrella" source for
data on convenience foods, partly because the category (as defined
in this report) is relatively new, having emerged in tandem with
the microwave oven.<P>

Changing American lifestyles are increasingly putting a premium on
quick preparation of food.  Two income families, single parents,
school-age children home alone, and other lifestyle changes have
worked to make the convenience factor crucial in food preparation,
superseding price in many instances as the most important factor in
deciding which foods to buy.<P>

At the same time, food technology and the popularity of the
microwave oven have substantially improved the quality of
convenience foods, and made preparation quicker and easier in the
average kitchen of the average consumer.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study focuses on the industry these developments have created,
and, where appropriate, identifies marketing opportunities that are
developing as the industry evolves.<P>

This study is intended for those in the private and public sector
who need to know about, or have an interest in, new convenience
foods, including securities analysts, food company executives, food
researchers, trade association executives, specialty librarians,
government regulators, and others with a need to be informed about
cutting-edge developments in the food business.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study aims to cover the entire new convenience food industry,
which includes new prepared foods that put a premium on quickness
of preparation.  In many instances, this means microwavable.  For
example, in the area of new frozen convenience foods, the
definition of convenience is that the food is intended primarily
for the microwave oven.  This is also true for most new chilled and
shelf-stable convenience foods.<P>

The format of the study is a chapter-by-chapter treatment of each
of the main categories of new convenience foods, including:<P>

<MENU>New frozen convenience foods<BR>
   New chilled convenience foods<BR>
   New sous vide convenience foods<BR>
   New shelf-stable convenience foods<BR>
   New aseptically packaged foods<BR>
   New microwavable snacks<BR>
   New processed meats, poultry, and seafood<BR>
   New convenience dairy foods</MENU><P>

The study also contains chapters on government regulation, the next
generation of convenience foods, the structure of the industry, and
the most important companies in the industry.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The methodology used in the preparation of this study was to gather
data from as wide a range as possible of primary and secondary
sources, then organize the data, prepare an outline, and write the
report.  As the need arose, supplementary information was sought in
the process of writing this report.  In preparing the tables, all
of the forecases were made in current dollars.<P>


<B>SOURCES OF INFORMATION</B><P>

This study was prepared using both primary and secondary sources of
information.  Primary sources included personal and telephone
interviews with government officials, company executives, trade
association executives, researchers in private industry and at
universities, securities analysts, and other food experts.<P>

Secondary sources included magazines, trade journals, investment
house research reports, other research reports, government reports,
newspapers, electronic data bases, annual reports, filings with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, and other written material.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS, INCLUDING WORK DONE
BY OTHER AUTHORS</B><P>
The author of this report, Carol E. Curtis, is a senior editorial
professional with over 15 years of experience in business and
financial writing.  Ms. Curtis spent over eight years as an editor
at Forbes and Business Week, where she covered a broad range of
topics, including the food industry. She also spent two years as an
executive editor at Macmillan Publishing Co., specializing in books
about American business.<P>

Related BCC work on the convenience food industry includes:<P>

<DD>1. Aseptic  Food Packaging and Processing:  Markets,
   Developments, Technologies, by Bobbi Bernard, July 1983 (GA-050)<BR>
<DD>2. Aseptic Food Processing and Packaging, a Technical/Economic
   Analysis, by Becki Gipson, May 1986 (GA-050R)<BR>
<DD>3. Convenience Foods and Microwave:  Directions, August 1980
   (GA-044)<BR>
<DD>4. Food Processing:  Developments, Overview, by Paula Dranov, May
   1978 (GA-041)<BR>
<DD>5. Health Foods and Competing Products, by Danielle Mooney, June
   1983 (GA-037)<BR>
<DD>6. Mass Merchandised Health Foods:  Market Trends, by Danielle
   Mooney, April 1982 (GA-047)<BR>
<DD>7. Mass Merchandised Health Foods Update, by Sandra McGowan,
   April 1987 (GA-047R)<BR>
<DD>8. New Trends in Food Retailing, by Sandra McGowan, July 1985
   (GA-045R)<BR>
<DD>9. Retail Fast Foods:  Business Opportunities, February 1980
   (GA-038)<BR>
<DD>10. Specialty Foods:  New Developments, by Gail Greenberg,
      1985 (GA-042).</DD><P>

