<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-078  THE CHANGING COMMERCIAL AND INSTITUTIONAL
FOODSERVICE INDUSTRY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-078  THE CHANGING COMMERCIAL AND INSTITUTIONAL
FOODSERVICE INDUSTRY
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The recession  and increasing  competition  among  foodservice
establishments, either  as single  factors or  in combination,
have affected  foodservice sales in commercial, non-commercial
and institutional markets. This report analyzes and quantifies
how these   segments  are responding with marketing strategies
designed to  change menus,  styles, price,  and on-premise and
off-premise services  in order  to attract  an  ever-shrinking
number of  consumers willing  to spend money on food away from
home.<P>

The recession  has affected  customer traffic  levels  at  all
types of  facilities as  people choose  not to  spend money on
food away from home, or attend activities where foodservice is
provided. Lower  customer traffic levels have been reported at
separate eating  places and  retailing sites.  Lower occupancy
rates at  lodging places, lower attendance at some leisure and
recreational sites,  and lower volume of business and pleasure
travelers have affected in-transit foodservice.<P>

In  addition,   the  recession   has   caused   business   and
institutions to  suffer budget  and staff cutbacks that reduce
customer volume.  For example,  fewer employees at offices and
factories  mean   fewer  customers   for  on-premise  employee
cafeterias, mobile  carts and  vending machines, as well as at
nearby, off-premise commercial eating places.<P>

Hospitals are closing, keeping patients for shorter stays, and
reducing  personnel   which  affect  patient  and  non-patient
foodservice.   Subsidy cuts  at schools  mean fewer  lunch and
breakfast programs.  Even military  foodservice is  slated  to
suffer because of base closings and personnel cutbacks.<P>

More pervasive  is the  lack of confidence in the economy that
makes consumers  spend less,  once they  have decided to spend
money on  food away  from home. Changing patterns can be noted
as consumers  scale down  by going  to less  expensive  eating
places and trade down by ordering less costly items. Corporate
and social  party planners,  too, are asking caterers for less
elaborate menus and service.<P>

The competition  from the  increasing  number  of  foodservice
sites has  meant that  many  different  types  of  places  are
serving similar  menus and  providing similar services. Eating
places that once had a specific menu identity are now blurring
their images as they expand menus to attract customers looking
for greater  variety. Similarly, many establishments providing
only eat-in  service  are  now  looking  at  such  off-premise
activities as  takeout, delivery,  mobile and social catering,
in order to reach customers that might not visit the premises.
Even on-premise  services are changing as places move to self-
service, buffets, casual dining or fast food operations.<P>

In order  to maintain  the high  profits  of  the  foodservice
industry, where  wholesale value  can  range  from  33-55% of  sales, operators have been forced to rethink their marketing strategies.   The  newly focused  aim is to meet the needs, interests  and lifestyles of today's consumers who have certain perceptions  and expectations  about the experience of eating outside  the home.  Foodservice operators  seek to make their settings  more appealing  to  consumers  so  that  after entering, they  will upgrade  to items with higher prices, and
then, perhaps,  take advantage  of a  variety  of  convenience services offered for off-premise consumption.<P>

In  this  report,  BCC  defines  three  market  segments:  The
commercial segment  includes those places where foodservice is
the  prime  activity  (separate  eating  and  drinking  places
located at  various fixed  sites, independent caterers, mobile
caterers  and   vending  machines).  Separate  eating  places,
include various  types of  restaurants/lunchrooms, cafeterias,
fast food  places, ice cream/frozen yogurt shops, and drinking
places (bars and taverns serving food).<P>

The non-commercial  and institutional  segments include places that provide   foodservice  as  a  secondary  activity.  Non-commercial foodservice  is provided  at business  and industry sites, as  a transportation/in-transit service, and at various leisure, recreation and   sports   sites.   Institutional foodservice is  provided at  educational, healthcare, military and prison facilities.<P>

With so  many different  types of  facilities within segments,
the foodservice  industry is  a highly  fragmented industry in
which chains,  independent/family-owned  businesses,  contract
feeders and  self-operating facilities  tend to  specialize in
certain market segments.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:<P>

<UL>  (1) To understand how recession and competition have affected
     foodservice facilities,  and to  identify the  changes in
     menu, service, style, price and off-premise services that
     have been  subsequently developed  in order  to  maintain
     profits.<P>

  (2) To describe  how foodservice  is used as a marketing tool
     in places  where it is not the prime activity, such as at
     lodging places, retailers, drinking places, sports arenas
     and   institutional    facilities,   and   how   consumer
     expectations and  tastes are influenced by foodservice in
     places for which it is a prime activity.<P>

  (3) To learn  what consumer  perceptions  and  attitudes  are
     toward quality  and how certain marketing strategies will
     promote  or  retard  traffic  volume  and  sales  growth,
     particularly at  those sites  which are not linked in the
     public mind with quality foodservice -- vending machines,
     convenience   stores,    railroads,    healthcare,    and
     educational institutions.<P>

  (4) To analyze which marketing strategies best fit the needs,
     interests, and lifestyle demands of today's consumers, in
     each type of foodservice facility.<P></UL>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC seeks to provide insight into one key question: What types
of menus,  on and off-premise services, styles and prices must
foodservice operators offer in order to encourage consumers to
spend money  on food  away from  home, and patronize any given
establishment?<P>

The study  discusses the  recessionary and competitive factors
most directly  influencing each  type of  foodservice facility
within each  market segment,  as well  as the most influential
market forces,  consumer attitudes  and  demographic  factors.
Further, sales  for  segments  and  subsegments,  most  active
companies   and    ownership/management    arrangements    are
delineated.<P>

The insights  and conclusions  reached in this study can be of
special value  and import  to foodservice operators looking to
expand current  facilities or  enter new markets, and food and
equipment suppliers  interested  in  learning  where  business
opportunities may lie.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

BCC confines  this report  to examining  foodservice  only  in
terms of the delivery and sales of foods and beverages, rather
than  specific   types   of   each   at   various   types   of
establishments. Foods  and beverages  are  described  as  they
relate to  marketing  strategies  designed  to  meet  consumer
preferences and  interests at  different types  of foodservice
operations in the three major market segments.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

BCC  describes   foodservice  facilities  within  each  market
segment, their market conditions shaped by recessionary and/or
competitive factors,  and subsequent  marketing strategies  to
sustain growth.  Estimates and  projections are  made for each
type  of   facility,  and   where  applicable,   by   consumer
demographics,  type   of  dining,   and  on   and  off-premise
activities. Sales  and market analyses are based upon previous
rates of sales growth, expectations of expansion in the number
of units,  marketability, effectiveness and competitiveness of
marketing strategies, and various consumer factors.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first  conducted an  extensive  review  of  the  secondary
literature by  gathering materials from the library, trade and
professional associations,  government and  industry  sources.
This review  was  then  followed  up  with  some  one  hundred
telephone interviews  with personnel  in marketing,  sales and
marketing communications  departments of  companies owning  or
operating foodservice establishments.<P>

