<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-079 STABILIZERS AND EMULSIFIERS: NEW USES AND FUNCTIONS IN CONVENTIONAL LOWFAT/FAT-FREE, MICROWAVE-SPECIFIC AND LOW SUGAR/SUGAR-FREE FOODS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-079 STABILIZERS AND EMULSIFIERS: NEW USES AND FUNCTIONS IN CONVENTIONAL LOWFAT/FAT-FREE, MICROWAVE-SPECIFIC AND LOW SUGAR/SUGAR-FREE FOODS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Changing consumer  interests  and  needs  have  brought  about
changes in preferences for certain types of food. At one time,
consumers asked  only that  a food look appealing, taste good,
and  keep  them  nourished    until  the  next  meal.  Today's
consumers, however,  are demanding  more from food processors,
so food processors are demanding more from their suppliers.<P>

Media  messages   from  health  professionals  and  government
agencies make  consumers aware  that food  content can  be  an
instrument for  good or  ill health.  This does  not mean that
taste and  overall quality  are now  secondary  considerations
because the  ever-demanding consumer  wants no  sacrifice in a
product's flavor, texture, or appearance.<P>

Rather, these  traditional requirements  now head  the list of
additional demands:  that foods  provide nutritional benefits,
eliminate or  reduce health  risks by removing or reducing fat
and  sugar  levels,  contain  only  natural  ingredients  that
replace chemicals  in food that could pose health dangers, and
cook equally  well  in  both  conventional  and  fast-heating,
convenient  microwave   ovens  so   that  coping  with  hectic
lifestyles can be facilitated.<P>

Food processors  look to  their suppliers  for the ingredients
needed to  develop products  that will  satisfy these  varying
consumer demands.   The  task set  for suppliers is to develop
and market  ingredients that  are  the  functional  and  price
equivalents of  ingredients with  which  food  processors  are
familiar, so  that ease  of use is maximized and reformulation
is minimized.<P>

The goal  of this  report is  to understand  how suppliers  of
gums,        starches/starch         maltodextrins,        and
emulsifiers/emsulfier-types are  responding to  these  varying
demands from  food processors.  The  supplier  industry  is  a
highly fragmented  one, composed of such companies as chemical
companies manufacturing  raw materials,  flavor and stabilizer
houses, millers,  food processors  with ingredient  divisions,
and an array of middlemen serving as importers and brokers.<P>

In  this   report,  BCC   defines  four   main   food   types:
conventional,  lowfat/fat-free,  microwave-specific,  and  low
sugar/sugar-free.   In a  section devoted  to each  food type,
there are descriptions of gums, starches, and emulsifiers that
suppliers are  recently marketing  to food  processors.  These
can be  either familiar  ones with  improved functional values
and/or  intended   for  new  use,  or  totally  new  types  of
ingredients for use in new food applications.<P>

The ingredients  are  broadly  described  in  terms  of  their
marketing and  promotional characteristics.  Some  ingredients
are marketed  as generic  and have  applicability to  all food
types. Suppliers  do not necessarily promote these ingredients
for their  effectiveness in  one food  type over  another, but
rather recommend  when requested  from food processors what an
ingredient can  or cannot  do. Specialty ingredients, however,
are developed  as finished products and, usually, are intended
for use  in one  or more  specific food applications. Some can
also be recommended for use in one or more food types.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:<P>

<UL><LI>To identify  consumer  interests,  needs,  concerns,  and
     preferences for  certain food types and applications, and
     analyze  how   they  shape  demands  and  attitudes  that
     influence consumption and sales.<P>

<LI>To gain insight into how these consumer demands influence
     food processors  in their  development of  products,  and
     suggest how  processors, in  turn, make  demands on their
     suppliers to  provide them  with ingredients  that can be
     used as marketing tools.<P>

<LI>To  delineate   the  social,  economic,  regulatory,  and
     technological  climate   that  either  helps  or  hinders
     development and marketing of products by food processors,
     and how  the outcome  ultimately  affects  the  level  of
     demand from suppliers.<P>

<LI>To analyze  the role of suppliers, the structure of their
     industry, how  and why  they market a specific ingredient
     as generic or specialty, and to show how the intensity of
     development activity  moves in  tandem with  the pressure
     from food processors.<P></UL>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

<UL><LI> BCC seeks to provide insight into one key question:  How,
     and with  which gums,  starches/starch maltodextrins, and
     emulsifiers/emulsifier-types, can  suppliers best provide
     food processors interested in satisfying consumer demands
     for a  broad range  of  quality,  healthful,  convenient,
     reasonably priced foods?  Furthermore the report:<P>

<LI> Discusses the  demographic,  social,  technological,  and
     regulatory factors  that influence  consumer demands  for
     foods that are flavorful, are appealing in appearance and
     texture, promote  good health,  are easy  to prepare, and
     meet needs  for self-reward  and even  a new and exciting
     eating experience.<P>

<LI> Suggests how  consumer attitudes and perceptions not only
     influence consumption  of certain foods, but also the use
     of ingredients  that are cited on labels and perceived as
     helpful or  harmful to  health, and  how that  ultimately
     affects demand from suppliers.<P>

<LI> Explores  the  additional  influences  of  functionality,
     price, nutritional benefits, caloric content, and ability
     to cause  flavor or  texture problems on the selection of
     ingredients by food processors   from their suppliers.<P>

<LI> Examines  how  such  market  forces  as  regulations  and
     technological advances, both within the food industry and
     without (such  as in the packaging industry), can advance
     or hamper the development of foods by food processors and
     the demand for ingredients from suppliers.<P></UL>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report  examines how gums, starches/starch maltodextrins,
and emulsifiers/emulsifier-types  are being  used and marketed
as ingredients  in conventional,  lowfat/fat-free,  microwave-
specific, and low sugar/sugar-free foods.<P>

The first section deals with these ingredients used in a broad
range of  conventional foods.  The next  section describes how
some of  these ingredients  are being  marketed  as  specialty
ingredients for  use as  fat replacers,  while others  are the
same  generic   substances  used   in  other  food  types  but
recommended for use in lowfat/fat-free applications.<P>

The third section discusses microwave-specific foods, designed
for cooking  only in  the microwave  oven, and the generic and
specialty ingredients  used in  their development  in order to
overcome certain  deficits of  microwave cooking.   The fourth
and final  section deals  with low  sugar/sugar-free foods and
how these ingredients are being used with sugar substitutes.<P>

This  report   describes  the  ingredients  in  terms  of  how
suppliers  are  promoting  them  as  recent  developments  for
generic or  specialty use,  their functional  value in certain
applications, their  nutritional  and  price  advantages,  and
other positive  or negative factors that could influence usage
by food  processors.   It then  discusses how consumer demands
are shaped by various demographic and social factors which, in
turn, become  demands placed  upon food  processors to develop
and market  specific types  of foods. The discussion continues
with a  description of  how suppliers  are responding  to food
processors with   ingredients that will enable food processors
to deliver foods to satisfy consumers.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

Estimates and projections of sales for each type of ingredient
were calculated  according to  various factors,  such as sales
for main product applications and expansion of applications as
new product introductions due to such factors as technological
advances in  packaging or ingredients, taking into account the
functional,   price,   supply,   nutritional,   and   consumer
perceptual advantages and disadvantages for each.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>
BCC first  conducted an  extensive  review  of  the  secondary
literature  consisting   of  materials   gathered  from  trade
journals and  magazines, trade  and professional associations,
government  and   industry  sources,   and  company   reports.
Subsequently, one  hundred telephone interviews were conducted
with personnel  in technical,  marketing, sales,  research and
development departments of food processors and suppliers.<P>  

