<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-080A  VITAMINS, MINERALS, AND PROTEINS/AMINO ACIDS
USED FOR HUMAN HEALTH
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-080A  VITAMINS, MINERALS, AND PROTEINS/AMINO ACIDS
USED FOR HUMAN HEALTH
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

In recent  years the  escalating costs  of  health  care  have
shifted the  focus from treatment of diseases to prevention by
promoting   wellness   and   overall   good   health.   Health
professionals, nutritionists,  government and special interest
groups have  sought to  educate consumers  about the values of
vitamins, minerals,  proteins and  amino acids  in  the  diet,
obtained   from   fortified   foods   or   dietary/nutritional
supplements.<P>

Media  attention  directed  toward  specific  nutrients,  when
research discovers  linkages with  specific disorders, further
heightens consumer awareness of health benefits. Awareness and
knowledge is  then  translated  into  positive  attitudes  and
consumer demands  from food and beverage makers and supplement
marketers.<P>

Foods and  beverages are  fortified to  compensate for  losses
during their  manufacturing, and  because processors  want  to
market nutrition.   Maintaining  the nutritional integrity and
quality of  products is now of prime importance to processors,
even when  foods appear  healthful in  non-nutrient ways.  For
example, the  new  lowfat  foods  are  responses  to  consumer
demands  for   reducing  health  risks.  However,  fat-soluble
vitamins are  removed with  the fat, and minerals and proteins
are removed  along with  dairy products  removed for lower fat
content. Food  processors use  health as  a key marketing tool
would be interested in adding lost nutrients.<P>

Supplement  makers   are  also  compensating  for  losses  and
marketing nutrition.  They offer  consumers the opportunity to
make up  for real or perceived losses in the diet. Supplements
provide  higher   potencies  of   nutrients  than  regular  or
fortified foods,  allow for  an easier  way to  obtain  higher
amounts  of  nutrients  believed  to  provide  greater  health
benefits, and  allow  consumers  to  believe  that  are  doing
something positive for their health.<P>

The sources  from which  nutrients are  derived  can  also  be
important to  consumers. Health professionals stress lower fat
intake from  animal sources  in the  diet and higher intake of
vegetable and  plant  sources.  Consumers  have  responded  by
demanding ingredients derived from vegetable and plant sources
for use  as fortifiers  and in  dietary supplements.  Consumer
interest in  natural ingredients  to reduce health risks posed
by the  use of  chemicals has  also meant manufacturing use of
ingredients  linked   in  the  public  mind  with  health  and
nutrition.<P>

Suppliers of vitamins, minerals, proteins and amino acids play
a key  role in  satisfying consumer demands. Food and beverage
makers, as  well as  dietary/nutritional supplement marketers,
rely on  their suppliers  for nutrients  of high quality, easy
availability, in  forms that are easy to handle, ship and use,
and at  prices that  allow the  finished  products  to  remain
competitive.<P>

The goal  of this  report is  to understand  how suppliers are
satisfying   demand from  their clients. The supplier industry
is a  highly fragmented  one, including  manufacturers of  raw
materials  and  bulk  ingredients,  makers  and  suppliers  of
premixes, distributors,  importers, brokers, and manufacturers
of finished  products. Many  nutrients are  imported,  thereby
subject  to   economic  and   political  constraints,  forcing
suppliers to deal with price and supply problems.<P>

In this  report, each  nutrient is  discussed in  terms of two
chief reasons  for use:  fortification of foods and beverages,
and use  in dietary/nutritional  supplements. In the case of a
nutrient used  as a  fortifier, consumer  demand is  just  one
determining influence  because nutrients  also have functional
value. The  food  and  beverage  maker  has  to  decide  which
nutrient is needed in order to maintain the product's quality,
and which nutrient will be most consistent with consumer image
of the product.<P>

No such conditions exist for marketing supplements because the
manufacturer relies  solely on consumer initiative to make the
purchase in  the OTC  segment.  The  marketer  offers  a  wide
variety of forms and potencies to suit variability in consumer
choices. (The  smaller Rx  market relies  on the  judgment  of
health professionals.)<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:<P>

<LI> To identify  which nutrients  attract the  strongest  consumer
attention  and   interest  so  that  manufacturers  of  foods,
beverages and  supplements can use them as marketing tools for
increasing consumption and sales.<P>

<LI> To understand how consumer demand is shaped by media messages,
how the intensity of demand can be correlated to the intensity
of messages,  and how  this demand influences manufacturers in
the development  of products  using ingredients  obtained from
their suppliers.<P>

<LI> To discuss  the social,  demographic, economic,  manufacturing
and regulatory  trends  that  either  promote  or  hamper  the
development and  marketing of  products, as  well  as  produce
changes in  development, and  how these  factors  subsequently
impact on demands from suppliers.<P>

<LI>To  analyze  the  structure  of  the  supplier  industry,  its
environments and  channels of  distribution from  raw material
manufacturers to end-users.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC seeks  to provide  insight into  one key  question:   With
which nutrients  can  suppliers  best  help  manufacturers  of
foods, beverages  and supplements  satisfy consumer demand for
products that  promote and  maintain good  health?  The report
also:<P>

<LI> Discusses  the   demographic,  social,   manufacturing   and
  regulatory trends  that help to shape consumer attitudes and
  demands for  products  that  are  equated  with  health  and
  nutrition.<P>

<LI> Examines how  consumer  demands  for  foods,  beverages  and
  supplements are  influenced  not  only  by  an  interest  in
  general health  as defined by health professionals, but also
  by specific  needs dictated  by a particular lifestyle, such
  as taking part in sports and exercise activities, or dieting
  and weight control.<P>

<LI> Suggests how  attitudes toward  sources  of  ingredients  in
  general will   also  be applied to sources of nutrients used
  in foods,  beverages and  supplements, and  how that affects
  the development of nutrients by suppliers.<P>

<LI> Explores how  other issues  such as  price, availability  of
  supply and  usage  levels  in  a  formulation,  influence  a
  manufacturer's choice in developing the product.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

BCC discusses  each nutrient  classification in  terms of  its
value for  bodily functions,  health benefits  both known  and
suggested by  recent research findings, applications in foods,
beverages and supplements, forms available, market and driving
forces exerted  on the  supplier industry  and the  industry's
complex structure.  In the  case of  fortification,  nutrients
were examined  only in terms of their addition for nutritional
value, rather than functional value.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

Within each nutrient classification, BCC describes the various
types   in terms  of their  value and  importance to  the body
which, in  turn, influence  their use and need as fortifier or
supplement.  Nutrients   performing  important  functions  and
needed in  significant amounts  by the body, therefore, are in
wider use  and promoted  more heavily  by  manufacturers,  and
subsequently in greater demand from suppliers.<P>

BCC sales  estimates and projections for each type of nutrient
were calculated  according to  these bodily  needs and various
other  factors   such  sales  of  main  product  applications,
development of  new types  of products  whose quality would be
enhanced by nutrients, and development of different supplement
forms available to suit a wide range of consumer needs.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first  conducted an  extensive  review  of  the  secondary
literature  consisting   of  materials   gathered  from  trade
journals and  magazines, trade  and professional associations,
government  and   industry  sources,   and  company   reports.
Subsequently, 100 telephone interviews were conducted
with personnel  in technical,  marketing, sales,  research and
development departments of manufacturers and suppliers.<P>


