<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-080B  VITAMINS, MINERALS, AND PROTEINS/AMINO ACIDS USED
FOR ANIMAL HEALTH
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-080B  VITAMINS, MINERALS, AND PROTEINS/AMINO ACIDS USED
FOR ANIMAL HEALTH
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Pet owners  and owners of horses and food animals want to keep
their  animals  healthy  by  preventing  nutritional  diseases
caused by  deficient amounts  of vitamins,  minerals, proteins
and amino acids in their diets. Growth, overall health, energy
levels,  production  and  reproduction  will  be  hindered  if
nutrient intakes do not meet the requirements of each species.<P>

For pet  and horse  owners, keeping  their animals on balanced
diets will  help the  animals   live longer,  healthier lives.
For farmers with food animals, keeping animals healthy means a
faster return  on an  investment because  only healthy animals
are marketable.  Both types  of owners will also want to avoid
the high costs of veterinary services needed during illness.<P>

Providing animals  with  complete,  balanced  foods  that  are
fortified with  nutrients in amounts recommended to meet daily
requirements  will  prevent  the  development  of  nutritional
deficiencies that  lead to  various disorders and debilitating
conditions. Pet  food manufacturers are able to offer owners a
premium  product   at  little  extra  cost  for  animal  grade
nutrients used to fortify foods. Feed mills adding premixes of
nutrients to feeds similarly are able to market nutrition with
a quality  product.  Both  types  of  manufacturers  are  also
compensating   for    nutrient   losses    occurring    during
manufacturing and storage.<P>

Marketers of dietary/nutritional supplements serve the various
needs and  interests of  animal owners. For some pet and horse
owners, supplements  are given  as preventives,  on  the  same
assumption of  providing insurance against disease that humans
use when  they take  supplements. For  the more cost-conscious
farmers, supplements  are more often given to food animals for
therapeutic  purposes,   when  signs   of   deficiencies   and
imbalances are observed.<P>

Suppliers of  nutrients to  manufacturers play a vital role in
containing costs,  maintaining supply  and availability. Price
fluctuations and supply disruptions can be due to weather, and
political and  economic conditions  here and abroad. Moreover,
suppliers must  keep abreast  of research  reports  and  media
messages regarding  the purported  health benefits of specific
nutrients so  that they  are prepared to satisfy the interests
and demands of animal owners.<P>

The goal  of this report is to gain insight into how suppliers
are  satisfying   demand  for  nutrients  from  pet  food  and
commercial (fortified) feed makers, and farmers who make their
own complete, fortified feeds. The supplier industry is highly
fragmented, one  that includes  manufacturers of raw materials
and bulk  ingredients, a variety of middlemen such as brokers,
importers,  distributors  and  premixers  selling  to  end-use
manufacturers and farmers.<P>

In this  report, each  type of nutrient is delineated in terms
of reasons  for use:  as a  fortifier  in  pet  foods  and  in
commercial  feeds,  and  as  dietary/nutritional  supplements.
Fortified pet foods and commercial feeds are used by owners as
preventives,  as   insurance  against   the  animals  becoming
deficient in  nutrients. Supplements  can be  used  either  as
preventives or  therapeutics, when  animals are  perceived  to
have,  or  actually  do  have,  symptoms  of  deficiencies  or
imbalances. Animal owners or vets can make decisions about the
use of foods and supplements.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:<P>

<LI> To discuss the nutrient requirements of each animal species so
that suppliers  can direct  their marketing  strategies toward
different types of food and feed manufacturers.<P>

<LI> To understand  how changes  in animal  production and  use  of
nutrients are affected by changes in the human sector, such as
declining consumption  of dairy  products and beef as a source
of red  meat causing farmers to raise more animals with leaner
meats.<P>

<LI> To gain  insight into  how owners'  attitudes toward their own
intake of  nutrients affect  the use  of nutrients  for  their
animals, such  as pet  owners giving  healthy animals the same
type of  nutrients that  they take,  and how  media  attention
relating specific  nutrients to  purported health benefits can
help to develop new attitudes.<P>

<LI> To  discuss   the  demographic,  economic,  manufacturing  and
regulatory trends  that either  foster  or  hinder  growth  of
nutrient use  by manufacturers  and owners,  and how they will
impact on demand from suppliers.<P>

<LI> To describe  the structure  of the  supplier industry, how raw
materials and  bulk ingredients pass from manufacturer through
different types  of  middlemen  to  end-users  -  namely  food
manufacturers and farmers.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC seeks to provide insight into one key question: With which
nutrients can  suppliers best  help manufacturers of pet foods
and commercial  feeds, as  well as  owners of pets, horses and
food animals,  maintain the  growth potential  and  health  of
their animals?<P>

Discusses how  the standards  and regulations  established for
nutrient intake  for each  type of  animal helps  to set usage
levels for  fortification of  pet foods,  commercial feeds and
separate premixes used to make a complete feed or supplement.<P>

Describes how trends and behavior patterns in the human sector
affect how animals will be owned, produced, fed and cared for,
and  how   these  factors   will,  in  turn,  affect  nutrient
suppliers.<P>

Examines  how   economic  and   manufacturing   trends   among
manufacturers of  foods for  animals will  shape  demands  for
specific types of nutrients from suppliers.<P>

Delineates how price, availability, regional and international
conditions, weather  and crop  conditions  can  influence  the
choice and usage level of nutrients demanded from suppliers.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

BCC first discusses the nutrient requirements for each type of
animal, the  health benefits of each nutrient for each type of
animal,   the    conditions   resulting   from   deficiencies,
applications in foods, feeds and supplements, forms available,
market and  driving forces  shaping the  supplier industry  as
well as its fragmented structure.<P>

The terms pet foods and commercial feeds are used in the sense
that they  are complete,  finished products to which nutrients
have been added. Our concern here, however, is the addition of
nutrients to  whatever will  be consumed by an animal. Whether
the addition  takes place  by a  manufacturer who packages the
complete, fortified food in a can or bag, or by the farmer who
simply adds  a nutrient  premix to  grains and  makes his  own
complete food, is immaterial.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

Within each  nutrient classification, BCC describes each type,
its bodily  function for each species, conditions and diseases
produced by nutrient deficiencies, possible toxic effects from
MEGAPHONES,  natural   food  sources,   reasons  for   use  by
manufacturers of  pet foods  and  commercial  feeds,  and  the
structure of the supplier industry that meets their needs.<P>

BCC sales  estimates and projections for each type of nutrient
were calculated  according to  nutrient requirements  for each
animal,  and   consideration  of   such  factors   as   animal
production, changes  in feeding patterns by farmers, trends in
ownership of  pets and  food animals,  and  price  and  supply
conditions of nutrients.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first  conducted an  extensive  review  of  the  secondary
literature  consisting   of  materials   gathered  from  trade
journals and  magazines, trade  and professional associations,
government and  industry sources.  Subsequently,  one  hundred
telephone  interviews   were  conducted   with  personnel   in
technical,  marketing,   sales,   research   and   development
departments  of   nutrient  and   food   manufacturers,   feed
companies, and various types of nutrient suppliers.<P>


