<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-081 LIGHT/HEALTHY PROCESSED FOODS AND SOFT DRINKS: WINNERS AND LOSERS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-081 LIGHT/HEALTHY PROCESSED FOODS AND SOFT DRINKS:
WINNERS AND LOSERS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Growing public awareness concerning the health risks posed by fat,
cholesterol, salt, sugar, and high caloric intake has led to certain consumer
demands. Consumers want light and healthy processed, packaged foods that
either reduce or eliminate these ingredients linked with certain health
disorders in order to help them maintain good health and minimize health
risks.<P>

Responding to consumer concerns, many food and soft drink processors jumped on
the bandwagon and marketed so-called healthier versions of regular products.
However, two problems arose with this flurry of product activity. The first
problem was that some manufacturers misled consumers by giving false or
confusing nutritional information on their product labels.<P>

The outcome was that the FDA developed the Nutrition Labeling and Education
Act of 1990 (NLEA). These new regulations not only set labelling guidelines
for processors, to be effective on May 8, 1994, but are designed to help
consumers create more healthful diets. Health-conscious consumers will now
have clear, nutritional information on labels that allows them to evaluate
their intake of these ingredients and compare that intake among brands
marketed by different processors. For their part, processors now have a level
playing field as a result of the NLEA  and have the incentive to develop
healthful products.<P>

The second problem is related to technology and is less easily resolved. There
are periodic reports about some light/healthy products having disappointing
sales because they reportedly fall short of consumer expectations of quality
and value. The reason is that while consumers are increasingly health-
conscious, taste still remains supreme with them. While they are demanding
more healthful items so they can create proper diets, consumers want the
benefits with absolutely no sacrifice in taste or texture. In other words,
product quality should be indistinguishable from their regular counterparts,
but with the added value of high nutrition.<P>

The challenge for food and soft drink makers is to use existing technology, or
develop new technologies, that will allow the development of light/healthy
products that match the quality and value of the regular versions. In a few
cases, ingredients or technologies are awaiting FDA approval, thereby holding
up product development.<P>

The goal of this report is to learn which, and why, certain types of foods and
soft drinks are experiencing wide consumer acceptance and strong sales growth
while others are lagging. Food and soft drink processors generally make up two
separate industries, with the exception of one or two giant beverage makers
that may also have a food division.<P>

To date, the light/healthy foods industry is dominated by national brands from
companies that are market leaders in their given food categories. Some
companies are marketing whole lines and sub-lines of light/healthy foods, a
few even having new brand names. Diet soft drinks also are dominated by the
leading beverage companies, but this market is seeing heavy participation from
lower-priced private label brands.<P>

In this report, BCC examines various food and soft drink categories. Included
as food products are dairy, meat/poultry, baked, candy/ confections,
condiments, and products classified in a single section as "other types of
foods," which includes soups, cereals, pancake syrups/fruit syrups,
jams/jellies/fruit spreads, puddings, and dessert toppings. Soft drinks
include the various types and flavors of diet products, including colas,
pepper-types, 7-Up/citrus types, and fruit juice added/others.<P>

The range of products in light/healthy versions are referred to as "Low and
Free" and include: lowfat, fat-free, low cholesterol, cholesterol-free, low in
saturated fat, low calorie, low sugar, sugar-free, low salt and salt-free. BCC
classified each product type according to the first descriptor used by the
processor. In some cases, a given product could be promoted with four or five
descriptors.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Identify consumer needs, interests and preferences for light/ healthy versions of certain types of foods and soft drinks, and analyze how         they shape demands and attitudes that affect consumption and sales.<P>

<LI>Gain insight into how perceived consumer demand, as well as real
          market   size for the overall category, influence processors in the
         development of certain light/healthy products.<P>

<LI>Discuss the regulatory, technological, social and economic
         forces that either foster or hamper the development and marketing
         of light/healthy products by processors.<P>

<LI>Describe the structure of the industry, the companies involved, and the
         competitive factors, such as marketing from private label brands and
         rivalling a processor's own regular brands, that shape the industry
         environment.</UL><P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC seeks to provide insight into one key question: What types of light/healthy
products, and in what food and soft drink categories, are there winners because
they're enjoying wide consumer acceptance and losers because they fail to meet
consumer expectations?  Furthermore, the report:<P>
<UL><LI>Discusses the social and demographic factors that influence consumer
         demands for products that are tasty, price-competitive,
         convenient, possibly self-indulgent treats, and provide health
         benefits -- all at the same time.<P>

<LI>Suggests how consumer attitudes and perceptions toward certain types of
         foods and soft drinks influence processors, which in turn, form their
         perceptions of consumer demand and potential market size, and thereby
         decide which type of light/healthy product should be marketed.<P>

<LI>Describes the regulatory and technological forces driving
         processors, and how they provide incentives or disincentives
         to develop light/healthy foods and soft drinks.<P>

<LI>Examines the needs of processors to develop marketing strategies that
         enable them to compete with lower-priced regional and
         private label brands, and how the availability of technology and
         market size help to determine participation of these brands.</UL><P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

Each food category is described in terms of the various types of light/healthy
versions being marketed with some examples marketed by the leading processors.
The industry structure for each food category is delineated in terms of market
forces shaping consumer attitudes, driving forces for processors, most active
processors, market leaders and shares, and industry environment.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

Sales estimates and projections for each type of light/healthy food were based
on one or more factors: size of market for regular products and perceived
demand for light/healthy versions; historical trends and sales patterns of
each regular and light/healthy food and soft drink categories; technological
availability and cost, and discernible consumer consumption patterns.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first conducted an extensive review of the secondary literature consisting
of materials gathered from trade journals and magazines, trade and
professional associations, government and industry sources, and company
materials. Subsequently, some 100 telephone interviews were conducted with
personnel in technical, marketing, sales, and research and development
departments of food and soft drink processors.<P>


<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
