<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-082  SPECIALTY INGREDIENTS AND RELATED TECHNOLOGIES FOR
LOWFAT AND FAT-FREE APPLICATIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-082  SPECIALTY INGREDIENTS AND RELATED TECHNOLOGIES FOR
LOWFAT AND FAT-FREE APPLICATIONS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Media messages linking such disorders as heart disease, cancer and
obesity with high fat intake have influenced the development of
consumer demands for lowfat and fat-free foods. Today's consumers
are health-conscious consumers who want processed foods that help
them minimize health risks.<P>

Food processors began to respond to these consumer demands in the
late 1980s. However, since that time two conditions have occurred
which influenced the need for specialty ingredients. Specialty
ingredients are designed to provide specific purposes and functions
that arise from the reduction or removal of fat. These specialty
ingredients include flavors, flavor enhancers, fat replacers, and
certain ingredients produced by special technologies.<P>

The first condition is that consumers complained about many of the
reduced fat foods because their taste and texture failed to meet
expectations. The need for ingredients specially designed for these
applications was thereby created.  Taste is the number one priority
for most consumers. While they also want health benefits, they mean
health benefits with no compromise in taste or texture. In other
words, consumers want the same quality products as the full-fat
versions, but now the products must have the additional value of
good nutrition.<P>

The second condition was that some food processors tried to falsely
market nutrition by putting misleading health claims or confusing
nutritional information on their product labels. The result was
that the FDA stepped in to protect the consumer and issued the
Nutrition Labeling and Education Act of 1990 (NLEA), due to take
effect on May 8, 1994.<P>

Food processors now report that the NLEA is the single most
influential factor in product development, which includes
reformulation of existing products and to a lesser degree
development of new products. The new regulations will not only set
guidelines for product labels but will provide nutritional
information to help consumers create healthy diets. With clear,
easy-to-read and easy-to- understand listings of ingredients and
numerical values, the consumer will be able to compare nutritional
contents among many products marketed by different food processors
to determine which provides the most healthful item.<P>

This anticipated consumer behavior not only gives food processors
a clear incentive to create healthful products, but also to use
ingredients that help the product appear healthful. The choice of
ingredients, then, becomes one of utmost importance because a high
amount of fat or a "zero" next to the protein or fiber listing, for
example, could make a product look "bad" or "unhealthy".
The demand for quality foods from food processors, in turn, has
created demands from suppliers for the necessary ingredients that
would enable reduced fat foods to match the quality of their
full-fat counterparts. Many food processors found that conventional
ingredients failed to adequately address the deficits caused by the
loss of fat.<P>

Suppliers have responded with specialty ingredients that include
flavors that mimic the taste and texture of fat or oil, impart the
specific flavors of high fat content ingredients, strengthen the
product's overall flavor, or combination flavors that provide both
flavor and one or more properties of fat; flavor enhancers to
enhance specific flavors and/or mimic the flavor and mouthfeel
properties of fat; fat replacers to mimic the properties of fat or
serve more as fat reducers because they help to lower the product's
fat content in some way; and ingredients produced by special
technologies such as defatted ingredients, a processing aid to
lower cholesterol content, substances to improve flavor and texture
or otherwise serve such specific function.<P>

In order to more effectively serve the needs of food processors,
many companies in the highly fragmented supplier industry have
undergone restructuring. The supplier industry is composed of large
and small companies serving niche and mass markets. These companies
can be flavor houses, ingredient suppliers, food processors,
chemical and biotech companies and even academic institutions.<P>

The goal of this report is to learn which, and why, certain
specialty ingredients are meeting with the satisfaction of food
processors and thereby experiencing good growth, while others are
expected to grow more slowly.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:<P>

<LI> To identify the various needs of food processors for specialty
ingredients that can serve specific purposes and functions in
lowfat and fat-free foods.<P>

<LI> To describe the various types of specialty ingredients that
suppliers are offering to food processors in order to help them
develop quality foods that meet with consumer approval.<P>

<LI> To learn the regulatory, technological, social and economic forces
that either promote or hinder the development and marketing of
lowfat and fat-free foods by food processors.<P>

<LI> To analyze the supplier industry that seeks to meet the needs of
food processors, and delineate its role and structure for
delivering  products and services needed by food processors.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC seeks to provide insight into one key question: How, and with
what types of specialty ingredients, can suppliers best serve food
processors interested in developing quality lowfat and fat-free
foods?<P>

Examines each type of specialty ingredient in terms of its special
purpose, function and value in the development of lowfat and
fat-free foods.<P>

Describes each type of specialty ingredient in terms of derivation,
suggested applications, usage level, price per pound and major
suppliers.<P>

Discusses the regulatory, social and technological forces that
drive processors, and how they provide incentives or disincentives
to develop lowfat and fat-free foods.<P>

Analyzes the role of suppliers, value and importance to food
processors as they increasingly rely on suppliers' technical
expertise in the wake of cutbacks in R&D personnel at food
companies.<P>


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

Each specialty ingredient is described in terms of its purpose and
function to food processors, how it differs or compares with its
conventional counterpart, some examples of the ingredient and its
suppliers, and its derivation and/or technology used to develop it.
Then the industry structure for each type of specialty ingredient
is delineated in terms of market forces shaping consumer attitudes
that affect food processors, driving forces for suppliers serving
food processors, usage level and costs per pound, industry
environment for suppliers and most active suppliers of each type of
specialty ingredients.<P>


<b>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

Sales estimates and projections for each type of specialty
ingredient were based on one or more factors: size of market for
the ingredient in its conventional form, usage level in a reduced
fat application,  sales patterns of main reduced fat applications
that use the ingredient, technological availability, and cost
factors.<P>


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first conducted an extensive review of the secondary literature
consisting of materials gathered from trade journals and magazines,
trade and professional associations, government and industry
sources, and company materials. Subsequently, some one hundred
telephone interviews were conducted with personnel in technical,
marketing, sales, and R&D departments of food processors, as well
as researchers at universities, marketing boards and biotech
companies.<P>


<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
