<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-085: NEW NICHE NUTRACEUTICALS: NUTRIENTS, FOOD
SUBSTANCES & FOODS/BEVERAGES USED AS FORTIFIERS 
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-085: NEW NICHE NUTRACEUTICALS: NUTRIENTS, FOOD
SUBSTANCES & FOODS/BEVERAGES USED AS FORTIFIERS 
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Dorothy Kroll
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>
 
Consumers are continually given messages by the media, health professionals 
and the government that they can take control of their health, and prevent 
certain major disorders that incur high health costs. One of the ways that 
consumers are advised to achieve this goal is to plan a proper diet, since 
diet and nutrition are increasingly linked with disease prevention and 
treatment in clinical studies.<P>  
 
Through research, certain naturally occurring substances are showing purported 
protective influences against such life-threatening conditions as heart 
disease and cancer. The studies seek to identify the natural substances, 
referred to as phytochemicals, with the intention of extracting them for use 
as fortifiers to be incorporated into foods and beverages, once approved by 
the FDA. The fortification process would be similar to the current industry 
practice of using nutrients as fortifiers to prevent deficiencies such as 
vitamin C to prevent scurvy.<P> 
 
The fortifiers would be classified as nutraceuticals, which are defined in 
this study as parts of foods rather than actual processed foods or beverages. 
The nutraceuticals would be added to foods as fortifiers for the express 
purpose of producing a health benefit and not for any functional or technical 
value. As such, they would be an alternative to drugs but not their 
replacements, and their usage as preventive medicine would be to supplement 
medical science and not replace it.<P> 
 
In most cases, the nutraceuticals discussed in this report are marketed 
already in some other form and used by consumers or manufacturers. The 
nutraceuticals include certain nutrients, food substances, and foods and 
beverages consumed as such.<P>   
 
The nutrients include vitamins, minerals, proteins/amino acids, which 
consumers know as supplements and processors know as fortifiers and additives.  The food substances include fiber sources, some of which consumers may use as supplements, and omega-3 oils, which consumers may know as cooking oils or supplements. Processors know both these sources as fortifiers for nutritional value and as additives. Also included are herbs/spices which consumers know as seasonings, and processors know as ingredients and additives.<P>  
 
Foods include certain vegetables and fruits which consumers use raw or cooked, and beverages include certain non-alcoholic and alcoholic products which consumers drink, both of which are used by manufacturers as ingredients. As this listing suggests, nutrients and fiber sources are currently used as fortifiers, and some omega-3 oils are used for fortification/nutritional value. Most, however, are still in the research stage as to their links to health benefits. This group includes some omega-3 oils, herbs/spices, and those phytochemicals derived from foods and beverages.<P> 
 
These current and potential nutraceuticals are supplied by various segments of the raw materials, processing and marketing industries, such as chemical companies, biotechnology companies, food and beverage processors, ingredient 
suppliers, distributors and brokers.  A given supplier may be involved in 
supplying one or more types of nutraceutical. 
 
The goal of this report is to learn why each type of nutraceutical, whether 
currently marketed or still in the research stage, is being considered as a 
fortifier and what factors affect its present or future level of consumer and 
processor acceptance.<P> 
 

<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P> 
 
This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:<P> 
 

<LI> To describe the different types of nutraceuticals that are being 
  investigated for their purported protective influences against  major disease that incur high health costs<P>
 

<LI> To compare and contrast each type in terms of suitability as a fortifier or    unsuitability due to inherent self-limiting factors, such as flavor, odor, consumer perceptions, availability and price<P>

<LI> To learn the regulatory (health claims), technological, social, demographic, and economic factors that are either promoting the nutraceutical industry, including identification, extraction, FDA approval, and marketing, or hampering it<P>
 
<LI> To analyze the structure of each industry interested in 
     developing, marketing and/or using nutraceuticals as fortifiers.<P> 
 

<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P> 
 
BCC seeks to provide insight into one key question:  How, and with which 
nutraceuticals, can marketers help consumers contain high health costs while 
both demonstrating social responsibility and realizing a profit?<P> 
 
The report examines each type of nutraceutical and its purportedly  protective 
influence against various types of major diseases, with the view that each is 
a current or potential fortifier.<P> 
 
The report presents the various advantages and disadvantages that processors 
may confront while using each nutraceutical as a fortifier, and factors that 
could influence its limited or wide usage in food and beverage applications.<P> 
 
The report discusses the regulatory, technological, social, demographic and 
market trends that provide incentives or disincentives for the development and 
growth of the nutraceuticals as fortifiers industry.<P> 
 
The report analyzes the roles of interested parties, such as government, 
various types of manufacturers and academic institutions, in influencing the 
marketing of current nutraceuticals and those still in the research stage.<P> 
 

<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P> 
 
Each type of nutraceutical is described in terms of its purported influences 
against specific major diseases as determined by recent clinical 
investigations, possible dual/multifunctionality for processors, social and 
market forces influencing usage, and regulatory and technological forces 
affecting the development and growth of the nutraceutical industry.<P>

<b>METHODOLOGIES</B><P> 
 
Sales estimates and projections for each type of nutraceutical were presented in two scenarios. Scenario one took a business as usual approach and made sales estimates and forecasts based on current social and market trends influencing usage by processors.  Scenario two took the view that certain regulatory and technological changes will occur between 1993 and 1998 that will affect higher sales and faster sales growth. The assumed changes will be the result of pressure from health professionals taking note of clinical research data, and from consumers who learn about the research from the media and demand them.<P>  
 

<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P> 
 
BCC first conducted an extensive review of the secondary literature, 
consisting of materials gathered from trade journals and magazines, trade and professional associations, academic institutions, government and industry 
sources, and company materials. Subsequently, some one hundred telephone 
interviews were conducted with personnel in technical, marketing and sales 
departments of food and beverage manufacturers, and food science/nutritional 
specialists in academia and professional groups.<P> 

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
